{ [Roadmap 1.d4 sidelines] }1. d4
1. Nf6{ Apart from the Grünfeld, I covered all the main  1.d4 sidelines , namely lines where White does not venture into the  2.c4  mainlines.     Most of this coverage overlaps with my previous Chessable course  Beat 1.  d4  systems  as I still believe they offer the best chances for playing for the full point with Black. }( 2.Bg5 { We are going to meet the  Trompowsky  with }2...c5 { as discussed here . I recommended 2... d5  in  Beat 1.d4 systems , which is perfectly fine. Nevertheless, I wanted to offer something new that is more in the spirit of the Grünfeld. } )( 2.Bf4 {  London  system lines involving  Nc3  are analyzed here  while those based on  Nf3  setups are covered here . } )( 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 { We meet the  Veresov  with }3...c5 { as discussed here . I like how practical 3... c5  is, although I should note that 3... h6 , which I recommended in  Beat 1.d4 systems , is another good option. } )( 2.Nf3 g6 3.Bg5 { The  Torre  system is a viable approach against our 2... g6  setup and is covered here . } )( {   }3.e3 { denotes the  Colle  system - a harmless yet club-player favorite  d4  system analyzed here . } )( {   }3.g3 { The  3.g3  system is covered here . } )( {   }3.Nbd2 { and }3.b4 { are analyzed here . } )( {   }3.Nc3 d5 4.Bg5 { The  Barry attack  is addressed here . } )( { Finally, the  Hübsch Gambit  after }2.Nc3 d5 3.e4 { as well as the  Richter attack  with }3.f3 { are refuted here . } )
