{ [Inspirational games]There's no better way to start a course than with two fantastic games by Fischer against the Byrne brothers.     In the Chessable course  The Best Chess Moves of All time , I lay out the context for this game which I'll partly transcribe here:      At the age of 13, Fischer became the youngest ever to win US Junior Chess Championship in 1956 with an impressive 8.5/10 score. This earned him an invitation to the prestigious Third Lessing J. Rosenwald Trophy Tournament in New York City.     The countries 12 best players dueled each other in this premier event, with Fischer only scoring 4.5/11. Notwithstanding, Fischer won the brilliancy prize for the following fabulous win over IM Donald Byrne: }1. Nf3
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. Bg7
4. d4
4. O-O
5. Bf4
5. d5
6. Qb3{ From an unusual move-order, we've landed in a rare variation of the Russian system. }
6. dxc4
7. Qxc4
7. c6
8. e4
8. Nbd7( 8...b5 9.Qb3 Qa5 { with the idea ... b4  is the modern treatment of this position. } )
9. Rd1
9. Nb6
10. Qc5
10. Bg4
11. Bg5{ White prevents Black from playing ... Nfd7  (which would now hang the  e7  pawn), but this move is a clear mistake. Believe it or not, moving the bishop a second time in the opening ends costing up White the game. Granted, some incredibly imaginative and precise play from Fischer was required! }
{ The American prodigy set off the fireworks right away with }11. Na4( { A bolt from the blue! The knight is untouchable as the following lines illustrate: }12.Nxa4? Nxe4 { . Now } )( {  (a)    }13.Qc1 Qa5+ 14.Nc3 Bxf3 15.gxf3 Nxg5-+ { regains the sacrificed piece with interest. Black is completely winning with an extra pawn and far superior structure. } )( {  (b)    }13.Bxe7 { fails to }13...Nxc5 14.Bxd8 Nxa4 15.Bg5 Bxf3 16.gxf3 Nxb2-+ { leaves Black up a pawn and White's structure in ruins. } )( {  (c)    }13.Qb4 Nxg5 14.Nxg5 Bxd1 15.Kxd1 b5 16.Nc5 Bxd4-+ { is decisive. White's king is in no man's land. } )
12. Qa3{ White keeps tabs on the  e7  pawn hoping that'll dissuade Black from taking on  e4 . }
12. Nxc3
13. bxc3
13. Nxe4{ No chance! Black ignores the attack on the  e7  pawn and instead goes after White's king. }
14. Bxe7
14. Qb6
15. Bc4{ A sensible move - White hurries to complete development and get the king to safety. }{ White is so far behind in development that the materialistic }( 15.Bxf8 { falls flat after }15...Bxf8 16.Qb3 Nxc3! { The tactical justification of this move is that }17.Qxc3 Bb4-+ { pins and wins the queen. } )( { while   }17.Qxb6 axb6 18.Ra1 Bb4 { sets up a deadly discovered attack. For example }19.Bd3 Nxa2+ 20.Kf1 Bc3-+ { gives Black a winning position with 2 pawns for the exchange and incredibly active pieces. White's rook on  h1  will take a long time to enter the game. } )
15. Nxc3
16. Bc5( 16.Qxc3 Rae8 17.Qe3 Bxf3 18.gxf3 Bf6-+ { recoups the sacrificed piece with interest. } )
16. Rfe8+
17. Kf1{ Onto the next puzzle for the game continuation! }
