18. Bxb6
{  18. Bxb6  was Byrne's choice. How did Fischer respond? }18. Bxc4+{ is the start of a series of discovered checks that Fischer used to pick up more than enough material to outweigh White's queen. }
19. Kg1
19. Ne2+{ White's king has been cornered and can now only move left and right. Black's knight is ready to say goodnight! }
20. Kf1
20. Nxd4+
21. Kg1( 21.Rd3 axb6 22.Qc3 Nxf3-+ { hitting the queen on  c3  wins. White's queen cannot capture the bishop on  c4  }23.Qxc4 { as }23...Re1 { is checkmate. } )
21. Ne2+
22. Kf1
22. Nc3+
23. Kg1
23. axb6{ An important intermezzo.  Black recaptures the bishop with a double-attack on White's queen and rook on  d1 . }
24. Qb4
24. Ra4
25. Qxb6
25. Nxd1{ The dust has settled. Black has an overwhelming position with a rook, two bishops, and a pawn for White's queen. On top of that, White's rook on  h1  is out of the game. }( { Fischer had no trouble converting: }26.h3 Rxa2 27.Kh2 Nxf2 28.Re1 Rxe1 29.Qd8+ Bf8 30.Nxe1 Bd5 31.Nf3 Ne4 32.Qb8 b5 33.h4 h5 34.Ne5 Kg7 35.Kg1 Bc5+ 36.Kf1 Ng3+ 37.Ke1 Bb4+ 38.Kd1 Bb3+ 39.Kc1 Ne2+ 40.Kb1 Nc3+ 41.Kc1 Rc2 { 0-1 (41) Byrne,D-Fischer,R New York 1956. Fischer's opponent graciously allowed him to deliver checkmate. } ){ Hans Kmoch dubbed this outstanding game  The Game of the Century  and wrote in Chess Review  A stunning masterpiece of combination play performed by a boy of 13 against a formidable opponent, matches the finest on record in the history of chess prodigies.  }
