{ [Inspirational games]Fast-forwarding five years to 1963, Fischer is in New York playing another US Championship. Fischer's rating going into the event was 2702, more than 80 points above his closest rival. Fischer was clearly the favorite rating-wise and was expected to win the event. The way he did it was, however, truly unexpected.     In round 3, he was paired up against Robert Bryne. Born in 1928 and a college lecturer, Bryne decided to dedicate himself full-time to chess in the late 1960s. A strong player by his own account - Bryne won the US Open in 1960 and represented the US in many chess Olympiads. He became a candidate for the World Championship cycle by coming in 3rd in the 1973 Leningrad Olympiad. }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. g3
3. c6
4. Bg2
4. d5
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Nc3
6. Bg7
7. e3{ Perhaps based on the crazy tactics that featured in Fischer's game against his brother Donald, Robert Bryne opts for a solid variation versus the Grünfeld. However, the game will be far from peaceful! }
7. O-O
8. Nge2
8. Nc6
9. O-O
9. b6
10. b3
10. Ba6{ The bishop stands excellently on  a6  and the pin along the  a6 - f1  diagonal will end up playing a major role in the game. }
11. Ba3
11. Re8{ Black steps out of the  f8 - a3  diagonal and prepares the ... e5  break, which White can hardly stop. }
12. Qd2
12. e5{  I was amazed at this advance, which seems to leave Black’s queen’s pawn a hopelessly weak isolani. - Robert Bryne  It's true that Black will be left with an isolani - a stactic weakness that will, nevertheless, be offset by Black's active pieces as Fischer writes:   I was a bit worried about weakening my queen's pawn, but felt that the tremendous activity obtained by my minor pieces would permit White no time to exploit it.  }
13. dxe5
13. Nxe5
14. Rfd1{ Bryne brings the wrong rook to the center of the board. White likely wanted to step out of the pin along the  a6 - f1  diagonal, but ends up leaving the  f2  pawn too exposed. Fischer wastes no time and jumps in right away with }
14. Nd3
15. Qc2{ Onto the next puzzle for the game continuation! }
