[Black "Inspirational game | Exercise #2"]
[FEN "r2qr1k1/p4pbp/bp4p1/3p4/8/BPN1n1P1/P2QN1BP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 18"]
[Result "*"]

{ Byrne wrote   As I sat pondering why Fischer would choose such a line, because it was so obviously lost for Black.  What did he miss? }18. Nxg2{ In 1962, live game transmission on chess.com was not a thing. The game was played in a private room and the moves had to be telephoned into the analysis room. The game was being analyzed by GM Nicolas Rossolimo and IM James Sherwin.  Rossolimo found Fischer's 18th move incomprehensible and some audience members questioned whether an incorrect move had been relayed.      This dazzling move came as the shocker... the culminating combination is of such depth that, even at the very moment at which I resigned, both grandmasters who were commenting on the play for the spectators in a separate room believed I had a won the game! - Robert Byrne  }
19. Kxg2
19. d4{ Liberates the  b7 - g2  diagonal for ... Bb7 . It's remarkable that despite all of Black's pieces being on the last 3 ranks, White is dead lost. }
20. Nxd4
20. Bb7+{  The King is at Black's mercy. - Fischer  }
21. Kf1{ At this point, two GMs commentating in the next room told the spectators that Byrne was about to win. Fischer's next move must have been jaw dropping! }( {  (a)  }21.Kf2 Qd7 { The queen is the way to  h3 . White won't survive this: }22.Nce2 Qh3 23.Nf3 Bxa1 { Fischer later pointed out that } )( { ( }a1 { )   }24.Rxa1 Rad8 25.Qc2 Qe6-+ { is decisive. } )( { ( }a2 { )   }24.Neg1 { is no improvement. }Qf5 25.Rxa1 Rad8 26.Qb2 Rd3-+ { White's king is toast. } )( {  (b)    Retreating with }21.Kg1 { is also no good. }21...Bxd4+ 22.Qxd4 Re1+! { is the killer shot. } )( { ( }b1 { )   The point of the tactic is that }23.Rxe1 Qxd4+-+ { wins the queen. } )( { ( }b2 { )   }23.Kf2 { is not much of an improvement. After }23...Qxd4+ 24.Rxd4 Rxa1 { Black ends up with an extra exchange. } )
21. Qd7{ 0-1 (3) Byrne, R. - Fischer, R., New York 1963.    GM Rossolimo exclamed  I don't understand this at all. Fischer has nothing at all for his piece.   IM Sherwin wasn’t so sure and the analysts kept waiting for Byrne’s move, but it never came. Byrne finally emerged in the analysis room and announced he had resigned. He then proceeded to explain what the commentators had missed.    Head on to the next puzzle to learn what that was. }
