{ [Inspirational games]In modern times, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave is arguably the world's leading Grünfeld player. In the following rapid game from the 2021 Opera Euro Rapid tournament, the Frenchman takes down Levon Aronian in crushing style! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. Qb3{ Aronian goes for the Russian variation - one of the most challenging lines at White's disposal. }
5. dxc4
6. Qxc4
6. Be6( 6...O-O 7.e4 a6 { The Hugarian variation is my recommendation in the theoretical section of the course. } )
7. Qa4+( 7.Qb5+ Bd7 8.Qxb7 { is the mainline. A complicated position arises after }8...Nc6 9.Qb3 Rb8 10.Qd1 Bf5 { where Black's lead in development should compensate for the pawn deficit. } )
7. Bd7
8. Qb3
8. c5
9. d5( 9.Qxb7?? { is definitely not a pawn White should take as after }9...Nc6! { ... Rb8  is a huge threat and the  d4  pawn is hanging. For example }10.Bf4 cxd4 11.Nb5 O-O−+ { and White's pieces make no sense whatsoever. } )
9. b5
10. Nxb5
10. Na6{ is a rare move that had only been played in one game prior to this encounter. Rare and strong I should say! Black clears the  b8  square and keeps ... Qa5  in his pocket. }( 10...Qa5+ { was well known to lead to a balanced endgame after }11.Nc3 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 Bxc3+ 13.Bd2 Bc6 14.Bxc3 Qxc3+ 15.bxc3 Bxd5= { . } )
11. Nc3
11. Rb8
12. Qd1
12. Qa5{ Black has a huge lead in development for a measly pawn. The immediate threat is ... Ne4  so White hurries to unpin the  c3  knight. }
13. Qd2{ White moves the queen a 5th time , which ends up costing Aronian the game. }( 13.Bd2 { drops material to }13...Rxb2 { but was nevertheless preferable to the text. } )
13. Nb4{ Black's pieces start flooding into White's position. ... Bf5  followed by  ...  Nc2 +  is now a big threat. }
14. e4{ White succeeds in stopping ... Bf5  but Black can approach from another angle, namely }
14. Ba4{ renewing the threat of  ... Nc2 + . }
15. b3
15. Bxb3{ There goes White's extra pawn. What remains is a completely hopeless position! }
16. Rb1
16. Bc2( 16...Nxe4 17.Nxe4 Bxa2-+ { was also winning. The  b1  rook is out of squares. } )
17. Rb3{ White is forced to give the exchange to continue the game. }( 17.Ra1 Nxe4-+ { crashes through. } )( { Note that }17.Rxb4 Qxb4 18.Qxc2? { fails to win two pieces for the rook as after }18...Nxe4 19.Qa4+ Qxa4 20.Nxa4 Rb1−+ { Black wins the material back and then some. } )( { (  }19.Qxe4 Bxc3+−+ { removes the defender of the queen with check.) } )
17. Bxb3
18. axb3
18. Nd7{ Black is up an exchange, which a player of MVL's caliber had zero trouble converting into a full point. }
19. Bb2
19. O-O
20. Be2
20. Na2( 20...Nd3+ { was also possible. A true testament to how bad White's position is. The point is that after }21.Bxd3 Rxb3 { The  c3  knight is attacked three times. Dropping it back with }22.Nd1 { loses to }22...Qxd2+ 23.Kxd2 Bxb2-+ { is lights out. } )
21. Na4( 21.Nxa2 Qxa2 22.Bxg7 Qb1+ 23.Qd1 Qxd1+ 24.Kxd1 Kxg7-+ { is hopeless for White. } ){ Head onto the next puzzle for the game continuation! }
