{ I played this game in a closed round robin event with a National Master norm at stake - in Ukraine, this is a rather coveted title, probably comparable to the FIDE Master strength, and getting it is tricky as you need to play enough master players in the same event, they have to be from different regions of the country, etc..  I believe this was round six and the first five games ended in a draw. So, I was craving my first victory! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5{ Of course, I used my trusty weapon - the Grunfeld! My opponent was a solid positional player, and I thought getting a more complex game will be the best choice - both versus him, and in this tournament situation. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Bd2{ I was somewhat upset to see this move, as the arising positions tend to be rather solid for White and I really wanted to break the drawing streak. But, as we will see, soon I had no reasons to be disappointed! }
5. Bg7
6. e4
6. Nxc3
7. Bxc3
7. O-O
8. h3{ Typically, White would just develop the knight to  f3 . Doing so allows Black to pin it with ... Bg4 .  I suppose in this game the White player, who seemed to be experimenting with this variation for the first time, didn't have much experience and wasn't comfortable with the idea of that pin.  However, his last move doesn't contribute to the piece development, which allows Black to immediately strike in the center and take over the initiative! }( 8.Nf3 { Is the main line here, developing and reinforcing the center. } )
8. c5{ Simple and strong. Of course, I am immediately undermining the center! }
9. Nf3( 9.d5 { Although advancing the pawn seems a bit risky, as it allows Black to open the position up fast, the opponent should have still played this way.   The beauty of having the White pieces is that there is more margin for error, so despite his lazy move  h2 - h3 , he still isn't in trouble. }9...e6! 10.Bc4 exd5! 11.Bxd5 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 Nc6 { With a roughly equal position. The  c3 -pawn and the White queenside structure seem a bit ugly, but the bishop on  d5  is very powerful, so things look balanced. } )
9. cxd4{ Now things are opening up really fast! }
10. Bxd4( 10.Nxd4□ { Like it or not, White had to play this way. }10...Qb6! { Now, the move ... Rd8  is about to win Black a piece!   Therefore, the knight has to retreat. }11.Nf3 Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 Nd7 { Black is definitely better due to the better pawn structure and outposts on the c-file for his pieces, such as  c5  for the knight, or maybe  c4  in the future for one of the pieces.  However, White would be able to develop and castle, which at this point is the best he could hope for! } )
10. Qa5+{ Somehow White's position is really lacking coordination! }
11. Qd2
11. Qxd2+
12. Kxd2{ Sometimes in the Grunfeld it's okay to have the king in the center, but not when the d-file is open! }
12. Rd8
13. Ke3( 13.Kc3 { Loses on the spot due to a lovely pin idea. }13...Rxd4! 14.Nxd4 Nc6 15.Rd1 { So far everything seemed forced. }15...Be6 { The threat, of course, is ... Rd8 , winning a piece due to the pin. It doesn't look like White is able to do much here!  Perhaps his best attempt is }16.Bb5 { but after }16...Nxd4 17.Rxd4 Rc8+! 18.Kd3 Bxd4 19.Kxd4 Rc2-+ { Black's pieces are decisively active, so the material gains are happening in no time. } )
13. Bh6+
14. Ke2( 14.Kd3 e5! { Would be another great showcase of the problematic pin on the d-file. }15.Nxe5 Bg7! 16.f4 Bxe5 17.fxe5 Nc6-+ { And Black again wins a piece! } )
14. b6{ I thought including the other bishop in the attack would be the quickest and most convincing way to finish the game. Seems logical! }( 14...Nc6 15.Bc3 Be6 { Also looks extremely awkward for White. How do the kingside pieces come out?! } )
15. Bc3
15. Bb7{ The check on  a6  wasn't yielding anything particular yet, so why not just attack the pawn? }
16. e5
16. Nd7{ Now, Black is ready to play ... Nc5 , and then either ... Ne4 , going after the bishop pair, or ... Ba6 - Nd3 , exploiting the weak light squares.  It's also worth mentioning that the c-file would be a great place to attack further, for example with ... Rc8 - c2 . It's kind of unfortunate that the White bishop is currently blocking it, therefore the ...  Nc5 - e4 , or ... Nc5 - a4  idea would be not just nice overall, but potentially decisive! }
17. e6{ Desperate to avoid losing the weaknesses, my opponent chooses to give up his pawn right away to at least spoil my pawn structure.   But unfortunately, now I am also a pawn up, on top of my superior development! }( 17.Rd1 { Developing moves wouldn't help White much either.  For instance, after }17...Nc5! 18.Ke1 Rxd1+ 19.Kxd1 Ne4 20.Bd4? Rc8-+ { The decisive check on  c1  is unstoppable, and White has no way of unraveling the kingside. }21.a3?? Rc1+ 22.Ke2 Ba6-+ { is a rather cute checkmate! } )
17. fxe6
18. Ke1
18. Nc5( 18...Bxf3! 19.gxf3 Bg7 20.Bxg7 Kxg7 { Would have also been a great way to convert - trade the pieces, spoil the opponent's structure - what else could you want?! } )
19. Bc4
19. Bd5
20. Bxd5{ This is the sign of my youth. Nowadays, I would have improved my pawn structure without a single thought. Back then, all I wanted was piece activity! Of course, both moves are reasonable. }
20. Rxd5( 20...exd5 21.Ke2 Rac8 22.Rhd1 Na4-+ { Would have been another convincing and simple way to convert! } )
21. Ke2
21. Na4{ I am immediately exploiting the loose  b2 -pawn, as well as the fact White cannot fight for the c-file, as my bishop controls the  c1 -square. }
22. Rhd1
22. Nxc3+
23. bxc3{ Now, White has a pawn weakness too! }
23. Rc8
24. Rxd5
24. exd5
25. Kd3
25. Bg7{ Time for the bishop to switch activities - it no longer has use on that diagonal, so it should start attacking the  c3 -pawn! }
26. Nd4
26. e5{ Having the center is also pretty great!  Now, I am ready to push ... e5 - e4  at any convenient moment, opening up the bishop and exposing the weakness of the  c3 -pawn. }
27. Ne2
27. Rc4{ Black has an extra pawn, the much better pawn structure and a superior minor piece.  Later on, I went on to win pretty easily - I will just leave the remaining moves with brief annotations. }
28. a4
28. Kf7{ The king is an active piece in the endgame. Get it to work! }
29. f3
29. Ke6
30. Kc2
30. Rc5{ The goal is to play ... Ra5  and then ... b6 - b5 , getting a passed pawn on the a-file. }
31. Kb3
31. Ra5
32. Re1
32. Kd6
33. Nc1
33. b5
34. axb5
34. Rxb5+{ Mission accomplished! The a-pawn is ready to run. }
35. Kc2
35. Rc5
36. Ne2
36. a5
37. Rb1
37. Kc7
38. Ra1
38. e4{ I decided that it's possible to force an easily winning rook endgame with a little trick. }
39. fxe4
39. Bxc3
40. Nxc3
40. d4
41. Kd3
41. dxc3
42. Kc2
42. Kd6{ Now the king is just coming over to collect the kingside pawns, while the opponent's pieces are dealing with the ones on the queenside.   Principle of two weaknesses in action! }
43. Rb1
43. Ke5
44. Rb7
44. h5
45. Rg7
45. Rc6
46. Ra7
46. Kxe4
47. Rxa5
47. Kf4
48. Rd5
48. Kg3
49. Rg5+
49. Kh4
50. Re5
50. Ra6{ It seemed a bit difficult to make decisive progress with the bare king only.  So, the rook is joining the attack! Yes, the  c3 -pawn would be lost, but as long as I get to win the kingside pawns, it's irrelevant! }
51. Kxc3
51. Ra2
52. g4
52. hxg4
53. hxg4
53. Kxg4
54. Kd3
54. Rf2{ Now we have a standard Lucena rook endgame. Thankfully, my coach made me understand this one very well back in the day! }
55. Ke3
55. Rf5
56. Re4+
56. Kg3
57. Ke2
57. g5
58. Re3+
58. Kg2
59. Re4
59. Rf4
60. Re3
60. g4
61. Ke1
61. g3
62. Re8
62. Kg1
63. Ke2
63. g2
64. Ke1
64. Kh2
65. Rh8+
65. Kg3
66. Rg8+
66. Kf3
67. Rg7
67. Re4+
68. Kd1
68. Rg4{ And the opponent resigned as the pawn is queening.  As we can see, it's possible to get a really bad position with the White pieces very fast, even in the most innocuous-looking variations! The slow move  h2 - h3 , followed by not closing the center with  d4 - d5  somehow landed White in so much trouble!    Hopefully you will be able to win a game like that too some day. This one really helped me - after this first win in that tournament, I won a few more and got the National Master title with a round to spare! }
