{ This game was rather interesting and special for the following unusual reason: I was facing an older opponent, who was one of the top correspondence chess players in the world!  So, despite his significantly lower rating, I was a bit concerned about how this game would go! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. Qb3{ The Russian System is a very ambitious way to play, since White is forcing us to surrender the entire center, hoping to occupy it with his pawns. However, moving the queen several times has downsides too - he is wasting a lot of time! }
5. dxc4
6. Qxc4
6. O-O
7. e4
7. Nc6{ This is one of the more provocative ways to meet the Russian System.  Black is asking the opponent to throw everything he has at his knights: the moves  e4 - e5  and  d4 - d5  seem to be winning a tempo and are so tempting! }
8. d5{ However, White actually isn't ready to advance the central pawns, as we are about to find out! }
8. Na5
9. Qd3
9. c6{ Now the center is getting blown up, and the fact White wasted time moving his queen around is starting to become very noticeable! }
10. dxc6( 10.b4!? { Of course, White cannot actually trap my knight, as this move would weaken his long diagonal too much. }10...Nxe4-+ { And Black wins a knight or a rook. } )
10. Nxc6{ Now, Black all of a sudden has significant advantage.  This is because the  d4 -square is weak, and the  g7 -bishop is incredibly powerful.   Plus, of course, I am ahead in development! }
11. a3
11. Be6{ The pieces keep coming out to natural squares. I could also develop the bishop to  g4 , but since I don't really want to exchange it for the knight, there isn't much reason to do so. }
12. Be3
12. Qxd3{ My solution to this position proves decent, but not as amazing as the immediate ... Ng4 ! }( 12...Ng4! { Was an even better opportunity.  Key is that White cannot rescue his bishop, as after }13.Bg5? Qb6-+ { Black double attacks the pawns on  f2  and  b2  and wins on the spot.  For example, after }14.Qd2 Rfd8 15.Qc2 Bb3 16.Qe2 Bc4! { That's it - lights out! } )
13. Bxd3
13. Rfd8
14. Ke2
14. Ng4{ While trading the queens, I saw that White couldn't save his bishops here, which is crucial. }
15. h3( 15.Bd2? Nxf2 16.Kxf2 Rxd3-+ { would win a pawn and leave Black in a completely winning position, of course. } )
15. Nxe3
16. fxe3{ This way, White avoided losing material, but now his pawn structure is horrible, and we have a pair of amazing bishops! }( 16.Kxe3 Nd4! { Also leaves White in a terrible position.  For example, after }17.Nxd4 Bxd4+ 18.Ke2 Bxf2 { Black is winning a pawn on the spot! } )
16. Ne5
17. Nxe5
17. Bxe5{ The rest of this game was pretty easy. }
18. Rhd1
18. Rac8( 18...Bxc3 { It is also tempting to worsen White's pawn structure further, but my dark-squared bishop is so powerful, so I didn't feel like it was necessary to rush with that decision. } )
19. Rac1
19. Bb3{ Now White is forced to trade more pieces and accept an even more passive position. }
20. Bc2( 20.Rd2? { would leave his rooks pinned and tied down. }20...Rc7-+ { Black is choosing whether to double on the c-file next, looking to capture on  c3  and win a pawn, or on the d-file. In either case, the opponent is helpless. } )
20. Rxd1
21. Kxd1( 21.Bxd1 Bc4+ 22.Ke1 Bd3 { Is also an awful position for White! } )
21. Bc4{ Now the Black bishops are finally infiltrating the opponent's position! }
22. Bb1
22. Bf1( 22...Rd8+! { Would have won even faster. The point is that after }23.Kc2 Bd3+! { Of course, the king cannot step onto the d-file as a discovered check would win a piece. }24.Kb3 Bxb1 { Taking with the rook allows us to invade with ... Rd2  and pick up some weak pawns, while }25.Nxb1 Rd3+∓ { Wins a pawn right away. } )
23. Rc2
23. e6{ The White pieces are absolutely stuck. For example, the knight on  c3  barely has any moves!  Next, Black can fix the weak kingside pawns with ...  h7 - h5 - h4 , or consider activating the king with ... Kg7 - h6 - g5 - h4 ! }( 23...Bxc3 24.bxc3 Bd3 25.Rb2 Bxb1 26.Rxb1 Rxc3 27.Rxb7 Rxa3 28.Rxe7 Rxe3 29.Rxa7 Rxe4= { . } )
24. Rf2
24. Rd8+
25. Kc1
25. Bc4
26. Ba2
26. Bd3{ A bit of maneuvering follows.  We are threatening to take on  c3  and win the  e4 -pawn. }
27. Rd2
27. Rd6{ The rook is protected. }
28. Bb1
28. Bc4
29. Rxd6( 29.Rf2! { Like it or not, White HAD to keep the rooks on the board, as the minor piece endgame is absolutely hopeless. } )
29. Bxd6
30. g4
30. g5{ The key winning move. Now the  h3 -pawn is doomed and so is the game! }
31. Kd2( 31.e5! Bxe5 32.Be4  )
31. Bf1
32. Bd3
32. Bxh3
33. Be2
33. Bg2
34. Kd3
34. Be5{ Now, the goal is to open up the kingside with ... f7 - f5  and create a passed pawn. }
35. Nd1
35. Kg7
36. b3
36. Kg6
37. b4
37. f5{ Done! }
38. exf5+
38. exf5
39. gxf5+
39. Kxf5
40. Nf2
40. Bg3{ And White resigned, as the kingside pawns are ready to roll and his pieces are helpless.  This was by no means the most complicated or difficult game I ever played, but given the correspondence experience of my opponent, I found it interesting how fast White's position collapsed! }
