{ I needed to score 2.5/3 in the remaining rounds to get my first IM norm.  With two more Black games, the task was even harder. But of course you have to try, so I was really excited about getting a fighting Grunfeld position! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. e4
5. Nxc3
6. bxc3
6. Bg7
7. Nf3
7. c5
8. Be3{ My opponent chooses a very solid variation, championed by Kramnik and many other strong GMs.  White wants to play  Qd2 , alleviating pressure on the  c3 -pawn, and hopefully in many cases trade queens, reaching a safe endgame.  My opponent was an older gentleman with a ton of positional experience, so I was hoping to keep the position more complicated. }
8. Qa5
9. Qd2{ Here comes the time to choose. Black can trade queens, or keep the position more complicated in a ton of different ways! }
9. O-O( 9...Nc6 10.Rc1 cxd4 11.cxd4 Qxd2+ 12.Kxd2 { is a very popular endgame that Kramnik played with the White pieces on multiple occasions.  Unfortunately, it's rather difficult for Black to confuse the opponent here and play for a win...so not this time, thanks! } )
10. Rc1
10. Nd7{ This variation is a perfect mix of complexity, since queens stay on the board, and low theory, as there are no forcing sequences.  White can close the center with  d4 - d5 , or keep the tension with  Bd3 , or try to trade bishops and attack with  Bh6 . }
11. Bd3{ My opponent chooses to just keep developing. }
11. Nb6{ With this move, Black opens up the  c8 -bishop, while also taking the  c4  and  a4 -squares under control.  Of course, we are not afraid of White taking on  c5 , as that would ruin his pawn structure! }( 11...e5 { Is the most common move, and after }12.d5 f5 { We reach the complicated theoretical positions of our course! } )
12. O-O
12. Bg4{ The arising position is actually not that easy to play with the White pieces. Does he allow for a trade on  f3 ? Does the knight have to retreat? Does he have to play a passive move like  Be2 ? }
13. dxc5{ My opponent decides he cannot keep the tension anymore, and opens up the position.  That's amazing for me, as now his pawn structure is ruined and the  g7 -bishop is set free! }( 13.Be2 { is no fun either.  Black can keep the tension, or proceed with }13...Bxf3 14.gxf3 cxd4 15.cxd4 Qxd2 16.Bxd2 Bxd4 { White can threaten to get the pawn back with }17.Rc7 { and after }17...Rfd8 18.Rxb7 Bxf2+ 19.Rxf2 Rxd2 20.Bb5 { Get enough activity to draw a pawn down, but obviously the possibility of this sequence, and the fact Black can choose to keep tension instead, isn't fun for him! } )( 13.d5! { Was the right way for White to go.  He had to allow for ... Bxf3 , which is actually not really dangerous for his king.  After }13...Bxf3 14.gxf3 c4! { Black would be able to prevent the opponent from connecting all the central pawns with  c3 - c4 . }15.Be2 Rfd8 { With ... e7 - e6  coming up, the position will be incredibly complicated and fun to play!  White has the center, but it also seems fragile. But it could also unexpectedly advance! The  c4 -pawn could fall, but also the White king is somewhat open...fun stuff! } )
13. Na4{ Of course, I am easily getting the pawn back. }
14. Nd4
14. Nxc5
15. Nb3{ White makes me improve his structure, however now I get an incredible amount of piece activity. }
15. Nxb3
16. axb3
16. Rfd8{ The pin on the d-file is very ugly! }
17. Qc2
17. Rac8{ Now the pawn is hanging. White always has to deal with some, even if minor, threats! }
18. b4( 18.c4 { Was the only chance, but after }18...Bd4 19.Bxd4 Rxd4 { Black owns the dark squares and White's bishop looks awful! } )
18. Qa3{ Now the White pawns are falling apart. Or something else does, which would be even worse! }
19. Bd2{ The bishops seem very dangerously loose on the d-file... }
19. Be6{ ... Bb3  is about to prove a rather annoying move to deal with. And, as it turns out, Black has another idea, too! }
20. Rfe1
20. Qb3{ After the queen trade, the d-file problems become too much for White to handle. }
21. Be2
21. Qxc2
22. Rxc2{ Now, how can Black win something? }
22. Rxd2
23. Rxd2
23. Bxc3{ This simple but lovely tactic wins me a pawn and offers a completely winning position. }
24. Rdd1
24. Bxe1
25. Rxe1
25. Rc2{ This move is tempting, but rushed.  Of course, Black is winning, but this position turned out to be rather tricky! }( 25...a6! { Would have been a much cleaner way to convert, in hindsight, as it would have allowed to meet  b4 - b5  with ... a6 - a5 !, getting a protected passed pawn. } )
26. b5
26. Rb2
27. Kf1
27. Bd7
28. Ra1
28. Bxb5
29. Bxb5
29. Rxb5
30. Rxa7{ Now White got to trade off a pair of pawns on the queenside.  I was pretty sure I had seen a similar endgame in the "Endgame Strategy" book many years ago.  Black just needs to advance the pawn to  b2 , provoke the White rook to be on the b-file, and then come in with the king to win the kingside pawns. Or so I thought! But it turned out not that easy in practice. }
30. Kg7
31. Ke2
31. Rb3
32. f4
32. Kf6
33. Ra5
33. b5
34. Ra6+
34. e6
35. Rb6
35. Rb2+
36. Kf3
36. b4{ I definitely underestimated White's idea. }( 36...g5! { Breaking up the White structure and preventing him from locking my king out would have been a very easy path to victory, especially compared to what happened in the game! } )
37. e5+
37. Kg7
38. Rb8
38. Rb1
39. g4{ I thought White was crazy for advancing these pawns.  In reality, he is still losing, but practically my task turned out a lot harder than I thought.  Why? Because if the pawn reaches the  b2 -square, White is almost in zugzwang, but his rook can sit on  b8  and cut off my king... so I am in zugzwang too! Black will be forced to trade his  b2 -pawn for one of the kingside pawns, and that position will take forever to win. }
39. b3
40. h4
40. h6
41. g5
41. h5
42. Kg2{ White's plan has been a success!  He can wait with  Kh2 - g2  endlessly, but my king cannot get out! }
42. b2
43. Kh2
43. Rf1{ So, I am forced to trade the pawns... }
44. Rxb2
44. Rxf4
45. Kg3
45. Rg4+
46. Kh3
46. Re4
47. Rb5
47. Rd4
48. Kg3
48. Rd3+
49. Kg2{ Little calculation assignment - is ... Rd5  a good move? }
