{ This was the second round of that day, and my opponent hardly ever played 1.  d4 . So, I was a bit alert! What did he prepare?! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. h4{ To be honest, this variation came across as a really annoying surprise.  About a year and a half before this game, I faced it without knowing about its existence, played 5... c5  and quickly lost.  Then, a year ago, I played the principled 5... dxc4 , knew a lot, got a winning position, but also lost.  So, I had a line where I had bad memories, and I wasn't prepared at all!  Thankfully, Black can also choose to play solid chess. }
5. c6{ This move isn't the most ambitious one, but the risk of getting in trouble because you didn't review theory before the game is miniscule. }
6. Bg5
6. Ne4{ Akin to many 5.Bg5  Ne4  lines, I am looking to trade down and simplify the position. }( 6...dxc4 { Is a much sharper way of handling this position - Black can give up the center and try to hold on to the extra queenside pawn.  But again, in this game, I wasn't intending to make things too complex. } )
7. e3
7. Qa5
8. Qb3
8. dxc4{ I had a specific idea in mind, but generally this move isn't great as it just helps White develop the bishop with a tempo! }( 8...Nd7= { Should equalize pretty easily.  The goal is to bring the knight on  b6  and put a lot of pressure on the  c4 -pawn, making White release the central pressure! }9.Rc1 Nb6 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Bd3 Nexc3 12.bxc3 h6! { And I get the bishop pair, too! Black's position here seems very attractive. } )
9. Bxc4
9. Nd6{ I thought White was looking to quickly push his h-pawn, initiating some complications on the kingside, and thought my idea would prevent that.  But he could keep things simple, retaining a nice spatial edge... }
10. h5{ My opponent allows me to do exactly what I wanted! }( 10.Be2! { White should have just kept his center and prevented me from grabbing the bishop pair! }10...Be6 11.Qc2 { Now White is just better. The key point is that I cannot prevent the  e3 - e4  push with }11...Bf5 12.Qd2 Nd7? { as after }13.e4! { The pawn is untouchable: White will take with the knight and expose my hanging queen, winning a piece! } )
10. Nxc4
11. Qxc4( 11.h6!? { Would have still offered White a promising position, although he had to be ready to sacrifice a pawn. }11...Bxh6 12.Bxh6 Nd6 { Would, of course, offer White ample compensation, as my king feels rather unsafe! } )( {   }11...Bxd4? { opening the e-file is just a suicide! }12.exd4 Nd6 13.O-O { → }{ With  Rfe1  coming next and the Black king being this unsafe, we definitely aren't happy! } )
11. h6{ Now, I finally get rid of all the kingside pressure and stop White's h-pawn! }
12. Bf4
12. Be6
13. Qd3
13. g5{ Of course, we cannot allow the h-file to open up! }
14. Be5
14. f6{ If White retreats, I just castle, hide the bishop on  f7 , and eventually blow up the center with ... c6 - c5  or ... e7 - e5 !  On top of that, the  h5 -pawn is a bit of a weakness if White ever wants to castle short. }( 14...O-O { The computer claims it's okay to allow White to trade the bishops, but it clearly looks rather scary. }15.Bxg7 Kxg7 { White is unable to castle long without hanging the  a2 -pawn, or weakening his king safety with  a2 - a3  first, so it seems fair that Black is hanging on. I still don't have a great feeling about giving up this bishop! } )
15. Bxb8{ He has to make this move in order to avoid wasting a tempo moving the bishop back. That crucial tempo would have allowed me to castle! }
15. Rxb8
16. Qg6+
16. Kf8
17. Qd3
17. Kf7{ I thought I had to repeat the moves, as otherwise how would the  h8 -rook get in the game? }
18. Qg6+
18. Kf8
19. Qc2
19. Kf7
20. Nd2{ Very fortunately for me, in a position where White had to force a draw, he refuses to.  Now I manage to get the rook out, and thanks to the bishop pair, get significant advantage! }
20. Rhd8{ Now, I am just about to hide the king on  g8  and blow up the center! }
21. Nb3( 21.O-O-O !? Qf5 22.Nce4 Qa5 23.Nc3 Kg8  )
21. Qf5
22. Qe2
22. Qg4
23. f3{ My opponent offered me a draw. No, thank you! Not anymore! }
23. Qg3+
24. Kf1
24. Kg8
25. Nc5
25. Bf7{ Now, the  h5 -pawn is incredible weak, and we are ready for some lovely central break! }
26. Rc1
26. Qc7
27. g4
27. e5
28. Qh2
28. Qe7( 28...Qc8!? { Staring at the  g4 -pawn and the  f5 -square would have also been very effective. }29.dxe5 f5-+ 30.gxf5 Qxf5 { And White's position is just falling apart. } )
29. Kg2{ What should Black do? }
29. f5{ Open things up!  The bishops are beyond excited, while the White king is opposite of that! }
30. gxf5
30. exd4
31. exd4
31. Qf6{ I should have just grabbed the  d4 -pawn, but instead, I found a very cute idea and couldn't resist going for it. }( 31...Bxd4 32.N3e4 Bxb2-+ { Would have been very simple and very strong! } )
32. Nd7{ And thankfully, White falls for the trap!  Why did I seemingly give up an exchange? }( 32.Qe5! { White should have insisted on a queen trade! }32...Qxe5 33.dxe5 Bxe5 34.Rhd1  )
32. Qxf5
33. Nxb8
33. Rxd4{ No, not the exchange! This is a rook sacrifice!  Of course, now Black has a myriad of threats, from the very direct ones like ... Rd2 + to ... Be5 , ... Bd5 , and so on!  The knight on  b8  isn't getting out, and White's king safety is just atrocious. }
34. Rhf1( 34.Rhe1 Rd2+ 35.Ne2 Bd5 { Would have also left White completely paralyzed. } )( {   }35.Re2 Bxc3-+  )
34. Be5
35. Qg1{ Up to this moment, I played what I thought was one of the most beautiful attacking games of my life, and unfortunately now I ruin everything...  What is the best way for Black to convert the tremendous initiative he has? }
35. Rh4{ I am still winning, but not nearly as directly as I could have been. }( 35...Rg4+-+ { Would have definitely been the easiest way forward.  After the forced }36.fxg4 Qxg4+ 37.Kf2 Bd4+ { It's lights out! } )( {   }37.Kh1 Qh3+ { is mate! } )( 35...Rd2+ 36.Rf2 Bxh5-+  )
36. Rcd1
36. Qf4( 36...Bxh5-+ { As time trouble approached, I was a bit afraid of checks, but after }37.Rd8+ Kg7 38.Rd7+ Kg6-+ { White runs out of checks and my threats, such as ... Qh3 + or ... Rh2 +, are absolutely decisive.  Of course, this is already easy to misunderstand with a few minutes only left on the clock. } )
37. Rf2
37. Bxb8{ Low on time, I decided to just start capturing all the free material I could see.  I thought I sacrificed a rook for a few pawns, so picking the knight and the h-pawn would give me a huge material advantage. Somehow I miscounted! }( 37...Bc4 38.Ne2 Bxe2 39.Rxe2 Rh2+ 40.Kf1 Qxf3+-+  )
38. Rd8+
38. Kg7
39. Ne2
39. Qc7( 39...Qf5-+ { Keeping the tension would have still won, but in time trouble it was too much for me to see. } )
40. Qd1
40. Bd5( 40...Qh2+ 41.Kf1 Qh3+ 42.Ke1 Bc7-+ { This move as key - Black is able to incorporate the bishop into the attack from the other diagonal and win! Not an easy idea to notice! } )
41. Rxd5{ Somehow it turns out I am not material up! During the game, it was a huge discovery to me, and not a pleasant one. }
41. cxd5
42. Qxd5
42. Rxh5( 42...Qh2+ 43.Kf1 Qd6 44.Qxb7+ Bc7  )
43. f4{ With this key move, White blocks my attack and activates the knight.  The threat of  Ng3 - f5  forces me to seek a draw. }
43. Rh4( 43...Qc6 44.Qxc6 bxc6 45.Ng3! Rh4 46.Nf5++- { Would trap the rook and win White the game. } )
44. Ng3
44. Rg4{ I have no choice but to pin the knight. }
45. Qd4+{ There is no way to avoid the perpetual. }
45. Kg8
46. Qd5+
46. Qf7
47. Qd8+
47. Qf8
48. Qd5+
48. Qf7
49. Qd8+
49. Qf8
50. Qd5+
50. Qf7
51. Qd8+{ This was a rich game with a lot of lessons to take away!  1) When you are caught astray and forced into a line you didn't prepare, consider playing the safer way;  2) As we can see, White can easily push too far. My opponent didn't want to take a draw early on, and quickly ended up in a terrible position;  3) The bishops proved very powerful here, while White's h-pawn was rather weak, as well as his king shelter overall;  4) Unfortunately, converting requires precise calculation, as this game proved again. }
