{ This was a game from a round robin event, where winning in the last round would have given me an IM norm. My first one!  Did I succeed? Let's see! }1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. e4
5. Nxc3
6. bxc3
6. Bg7
7. Bc4{ White chooses the Classical Variation. I was happy to see that choice, as the arising positions offer a lot of chances for both sides, unlike some more solid variations. }
7. c5
8. Ne2
8. Nc6
9. Be3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Qc7
11. Rc1
11. b6
12. Qd2
12. Bb7{ So far so good, these are some major theoretical moves.  Now, White mostly chooses to offer a bishop trade, which is exactly what my opponent did. }
13. Bh6{ Trading these bishops seems both right and wrong.  Right because the Black one is safeguarding his king, while also putting pressure on the  d4 -pawn. Wrong because Black has less space and White is spending time to accomplish this goal.  But, everyone does it for White...he doesn't have much choice! }
13. Rad8
14. Bxg7
14. Kxg7
15. Qe3{ White removes the queen from the unpleasant x-ray on the d-file. Here, I made the move that everyone makes, but in hindsight, Black has some very promising other ideas, too! }
15. e5{ I was hoping White would go  d4 - d5 , closing down the center. Being very experienced in those positions, I felt really comfortable about that idea! }( 15...Na5!? 16.Bd3 e6!? 17.f4 f5∞ { Offers very interesting play without giving White a chance to use the  d5 -square as an outpost for his piece and simplify the situation, unlike in the game. } )( {   }17.Rfd1 Qe7⇆  )( {   }16...e5 17.d5 c4 18.Bc2 Bc8 { Would result in play similar to the immediate 15... e5 . } )
16. Bd5{ With this move, White keeps the position as balanced as possible, which was of course unfortunate given the tournament circumstances! }( 16.d5 Na5 17.Bd3 { Here is the key advice about this structure.  Our goal is to play on the queenside with ... c5 - c4 , ... b6 - b5 , ... a7 - a5 , ... b5 - b4 , etc.  Of course, the knight belongs on  d6 .  That's why you should never allow White to play  c3 - c3  himself, as then our play would die! }17...c4! 18.Bc2 Bc8⇆ { With ... Nb7 - d6  coming, followed by the queenside expansion, and the ability to meet  f2 - f4  with the simple ... f7 - f6 , Black is enjoying amazing chances.  I played these positions a ton and always had a lot of fun doing that! } )( 16.dxc5 { is a terrible idea, as after }16...Na5 { Black is getting the pawn back, leaving White with a loose structure.  For instance, after }17.Bd5 Bxd5 18.cxb6 axb6 19.exd5 Nc4 20.Qg3 Rxd5∓ { Black's pieces are dominating the board, the b-pawn is restraining two of the White queenside pawns, and the  e5 -pawn is doing an incredible job restricting the poor knight on  e2 ! } )
16. Na5
17. Bxb7
17. Nxb7{ I wanted to be able to bring the knight to  d6 , but of course, leaving it on  a5 , from where it could jump to  c4  in one move, would have been a lot simpler and better. }( 17...Qxb7! { Is the better way to recapture.  The key point is that }18.dxc5? Nc4 { is bad for White, as always!  Otherwise, the knight can come to  c4  much faster! } )
18. dxe5{ This move is a serious mistake. Opening up the d-file and weakening control over the  e5  and  c5 -square allows me to create a ton of counterplay! }( 18.f4! { would have put me in a rather awkward position.  Of course, Black isn't losing or anything like that, but after }18...f6 ( 18...exf4? 19.Nxf4+- { White is just winning due to ideas of  Nd5  as well as  e4 - e5 - e6 , ruining my king shelter! } )19.f5! { White is definitely building up a lot of free pressure on the kingside. } )
18. Qxe5
19. f4
19. Qd6{ The point of this move is to harass White with a queen trade with ... Qd3  or ... Qd2 , which should be good enough to neutralize his attacking attempts. }
20. Rcd1{ My opponent makes a very ambitious, but an objectively unsound decision. }( 20.e5!? { Would have maintained balance, but Black has nothing to worry about. }20...Qd3 21.Qf2 Na5! { Of course, the knight belongs on  c4 . Too bad I took it so far away from there! }22.f5 Qxf5 23.Qxf5 gxf5 24.Rxf5 Nc4= { Thankfully, White has counterplay due to ideas like  Nf4 - h5 , but the fact that Black owns the  c4 -square and the d-file, while also enjoying the weak  e5 -pawn, definitely gives us a great position. White has to be careful to maintain balance! } )( 20.f5?! { doesn't yield White much, as after }20...Qd2⩱ 21.f6+ Kh8 { My queen is controlling the  h6 -square and the attack more or less disappears.  In fact, after }22.Qf3 Rd3! { I am likely forcing the queen trade with ... Qe3 + soon. } )
20. Qxd1
21. Rxd1
21. Rxd1+
22. Kf2{ The queen can definitely prove rather scary if he manages to weaken my king shelter, but I had a very strong idea here, which likely would have gotten me the IM norm! }
22. Nd6{ I wanted to make sure the knight can help defend the king, but unfortunately, it's very unstable on the kingside. }( 22...c4!! { It was crucial to activate the knight, and this was the only way to do that in a safe way - after all,  c5  and  d3  are outposts, so the knight cannot be chased away! }23.f5 Nc5 24.e5 { White definitely needs to do his best to urgently open up my king. }24...Rd5↑ { With ..Nd3+ being a threat, and ideas like }25.f6+? Kh8 26.Qh6? Rg8-+ { not getting White anywhere, he would have definitely been in trouble - at least, practically! } )
23. e5
23. Re8{ This is already pushing it a bit too far.  After 24.g4!, my knight would have been unable to stick around on the kingside, and I could have easily ended up in trouble. }( 23...Nf5 24.Qe4 { And ideas like  g2 - g4  followed by  f4 - f5 , as well as  Qb7  followed by  e5 - e6  offer White enough counterplay, I am afraid! } )
24. Ng3{ White fails to use the g-pawn, which was quite lucky for me! }
24. Nc4
25. Qe4
25. Rd2+
26. Ke1
26. b5{ Now, both parties have just enough counterplay against each other's kings. It seems like some kind of perpetual check is inevitable.  Later on, White opened up my king a bit more with  e5 - e6  and gave a perpetual.  Unfortunately, by missing the key idea ... c5 - c4 , activating the knight via  c5  and  d3 , I likely missed out on my first IM norm.  However, this was a really fun fighting game, and I think it's rather interesting to see that the position went from a really theoretical one on move 16-17 to a very unbalanced one, where White was likely in trouble, already by move 20!  This just proves again how rich these positions are and how many opportunities are available to outplay even the titled opponents! }
