[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key middlegame and endgame themes"]
[Black "Basic Grünfeld strategy"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5{ The  Grünfeld  is named after the Austrian Chess player Ernst Franz Grünfeld, who defeated Alekhine in his first foray with this defense in Vienna 1922. Botvinnik, Fischer and Kasparov would then take it up with great results and, nowadays, this defense features in the repertoire of almost every single top player.      Classified as a hypermodern opening, Black lets White erect a strong pawn center in order to later attack it. This is best illustrated in the Exchange variation, which occurs after }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. e4
5. Nxc3
6. bxc3
6. Bg7
7. Nf3
7. c5{  Black's plans  in the Grünfeld:     (1)  Mainly revolve around attacking White's center, for example with ... Bg7 , ... c5 , ... Nc6 , and ... Bg4  as shown in the diagram     (2)  which can be combined with playing on the queenside, where Black typically has a local force superiority.     White  has control over the center and can:     (1)  try to secure it (and thus minimize Black's counterplay) and then advance the central pawns to create a passed pawn (often with  d4 - d5 )      (2)  or launch a kingside attack, where the  e4 - e5  advance commonly features. This plan can be justified by noting that, in many lines of the Grünfeld, the  g7  bishop is the sole protector of Black's king (the  f6  knight is usually traded on  c3  or drops back to  b6 ). }
