{ In the game Kavalek,L }{ (2540) }{ -Tseshkovsky,V }{ (2550) }{ Manila 1976, White pushed ahead with  e4 - e5  signaling the start of a kingside attack. }14. e5{ This is a good moment to advance the e-pawn as Black lacks control over the  d5  square (note White's knight on  f4 ). With  e4 - e5 , White gains space on the kingside, opens up the  d3  bishop and blunts the bishop on  g7 . }
14. Rad8
15. Qg4
15. Nc6
16. Rfd1
16. e6
17. h4{  h4- h5 xg6  is a common way to weaken the kingside. Black's in big trouble here as he lacks counterplay against White's center, meaning the first player effectively has a free hand to attack on the kingside. }
17. Qd7
18. h5
18. cxd4
19. cxd4
19. Nb4
20. hxg6
20. hxg6{ The h-file is now open and the  g6  point is greatly weakened. }
21. Qh4( 21.Nxg6! { would have crashed through immediately. }21...fxg6 22.Bxg6+- { Black's king is completely bare and  Qh5 - h7 ,  Bg5  and  Rd3  are all coming. Black is busted. } )
21. Nxd3
22. Rxd3
22. Rc8
23. Rcd1
23. Rc2
24. Bd2{ White clears the 3rd rank for  Rh3 , threatening to deliver mate on  h7 . }
24. Qd8{ Black would love to exchange queens, but White is having none of it. }
25. Qg4
25. Re8
26. Bb4
26. Qc8
27. Rh3{ Here comes the ROVER (rook up and over)! }
27. a5
28. Bd6
28. Rc3
29. f3
29. Rd8
30. Be7
30. Bxe5
31. Qh4{ There's no stopping checkmate so Black resigned.      e4 - e5  usually signals a kingside attack is coming, which was particularly effective here as Black lacked pressure on White's center. However, this advance can also weaken White's position (particularly the  d5  square), which Black can look to exploit. Head on over to the next game to see how! }
