{ In the game Naumkin,I }{ (2412) }{ -Kortschnoj,V }{ (2642) }{ Saint Vincent 2003, White pushed ahead with }16. e5{ hoping to create a kingside attack with  Bh6 . Contrary to the previous example, White has insufficient control over the  d5  square and the  d4  pawn lacks protection. As such, White's attack never gets off the ground! }
16. Nc6{ Black immediately puts pressure on the  d4  pawn not giving White any time for  Bh6 . }
17. Be4( 17.Bh6? { blunders }17...Bxh6 18.Qxh6 cxd4 19.cxd4 Nxe5-+ { . } )
17. b6
18. h4
18. Rfd8{ Black continues to put pressure on the  d4  pawn. }( 18...Rfd8 19.Bh6 { fails to }19...Bxe5-+ { Note how Black's bishop on  a4  takes the  d1  square away from White's rook, which means White's queen lacks protection and ... Bxe5  is possible. } )
