{ An important pawn structure we have yet to discuss, is the following  Closed center  structure: }13. d5{ White has more space and a protected passer on  d5  - a structure that would normally guarantee White a significant advantage. However, with the c-pawn on  c3  instead of  b2  (courtesy of an earlier ... Nxc3   bxc3 ) things are not so simple. Were the pawn back on  b2 , White would have a straightforward plan of  b2 - b4  to open the c-file when the  d5  pawn would really matter.     As it stands, with the pawn on  c3 , the queenside is completely locked. The first player cannot easily open the queenside - the only pawn lever with  a4 - a5  is impossible with Black's knight on  a5 .     What about playing on the kingside? The only real break there is  f2 - f4  but that would open up the  g7  bishop to White's disadvantage. }
13. f5{ Conversely, Black has a ready-made kingside attack with  ... f5 -f4  }
14. f3
14. f4
15. Bf2
15. c4{ is a key move. Black should not allow White to play  c4  himself when the first player could find counterplay on the queenside by kicking the  a5  knight with a move like  Be1  followed by  a4 - a5  as well as being able to bring the  e2  knight into the game via  c3 .     With ... c4 , the  e2  knight is deprived of the  c3  square and the queenside is completely shut. }
16. Bc2
16. Bd7
17. Kh1
17. g5{ Black followed up with ... Qe8 - h5  and  Rf6 - h6  - standard King's Indian attacking moves and won a convincing game: }( 18.Rg1 Qe8 19.Bd1 Rf6 20.Nc1 Qh5 21.g4 Qh3 22.Qe2 h5 23.Qf1 Qxf1 24.Rxf1 hxg4 25.fxg4 Kf7-+ 26.Kg2 Rh8 27.h3 Rfh6 28.Rh1 Bf8 29.Rb1 Ba3 30.Bf3 Ba4 31.Ne2 Nb7 32.Ng1 Nd6 33.h4 Bc2 34.Re1 gxh4 35.Nh3 Rg6 36.Nxf4 exf4 37.e5 Nf5 38.Be4 Ne3+ 39.Kf3 Bxe4+ 40.Kxe4 Rxg4 41.Bxe3 fxe3+ 42.Kxe3 Bc5+ 43.Kf3 Rg3+ 44.Ke4 Rg4+ 45.Kf3 Rhg8 46.Re4 Rg3+ 47.Ke2 Rxc3 48.Rf1+ Ke8 { 0-1 (48) Zude,A (2446)-Heinatz,T  (2331) Germany 2012. } )
