1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5{ The  Grünfeld  is named after the Austrian Chess player Ernst Franz Grünfeld, who defeated Alekhine in his first foray with this defense in Vienna 1922. Botvinnik, Fischer and Kasparov would then take it up with great results and, nowadays, this defense features in the repertoire of almost every single top player.    Classified as a hypermodern opening, Black lets White erect a strong pawn center in order to later attack it. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. e4{ White takes over the center and expels our knight from  d5 . }
5. Nxc3
6. bxc3
6. Bg7
7. Nf3{ is one of the main tabiyas in the Grünfeld. White has a full pawn center that Black will now look to undermine with moves like ... c5 , ... Nc6 , and ... Bg4 . }
7. c5{ Black should waste no time in undermining White's center. Here's a  rule of thumb  in the Grünfeld: when there's a choice between immediately putting pressure on White's center or first playing ... O-O , the former is usually the way to go. }
8. Bb5+{ has been played in a couple of top-level encounters. Anand essayed it against Gelfand in game 1 of the 2012 World Championship so it certainly deserves some attention.     What's the point behind this early bishop sortie? First and foremost, White clears the way for a quick  O-O  with tempo. Moreover, White hopes to hinder Black's development and, in case of ... Nc6 , has the extra option of easing the pressure on the  d4  pawn with  Bxc6  while damaging Black's structure.     It's not all great though as the bishop on  b5  can easily find itself exposed to moves like ... Qa5 . }
8. Nc6{ This is Black's most ambitious and strongest continuation. Black's knight is most active on  c6 , pressuring  d4 . There's no need to be afraid of walking into a pin. }
9. O-O{ is the mainline. After all, quickly getting the king to  g1  was one of the main points behind  Bb5+ . }( 9.d5 { is strongly met by }9...Qa5! { hitting the bishop and  c3  pawn. Check out this  in the main theoretical section of the course for all the details. } )
9. O-O
10. Be3{ A natural square for the bishop, reinforcing the  d4  pawn. }
10. Bg4{ The  c6  knight,  g7  bishop,  d8  queen and  g4  bishop all eye the  d4  pawn, placing White's center under serious pressure.      You can find further analysis in the main theoretical section  of the course . }
