8. Rb1{ It's now time to turn our attention to White's most popular 8th move and one of the most challenging variations in the Grünfeld - the  Modern Exchange  variation.     White removes the rook from the long diagonal, enabling a quick  d4 - d5  in many lines, and puts pressure on the  b7  pawn. Not only that, White now has the option of meeting ... Qa5  with  Rb5 . }
8. O-O
9. Be2{ A natural developing move, clearing the way for  O-O . }
9. Nc6{ This provocative and dynamic move is my recommendation. We welcome  d4 - d5  as this will only increase the scope of the  g7  bishop! }
10. d5{ Advancing in the center with  d5  was White's main idea behind 8.  Rb1 . }( 10.d5 { This advance is timely given that }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { gives White an easy, ready-made attack with  Qh6  and  h4 - h5 . } )
10. Ne5( { I know I'm repeating myself but I really want to drive the following point home. Do  NOT  go for }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { when Black's king will come under a vicious attack after  h4 - h5  and  Qh6 . } )
11. Nxe5{ is really the only way to continue. The alternatives below land White in hot water. }
11. Bxe5
12. Qd2{ is White's most popular and strongest continuation. Despite blocking the  d2  bishop, the queen defends  c3  and supports the  d5  pawn thus threatening to take over the center with  f2 - f4  and, if allowed,  e4 - e5 . }( 12.Qd2 { comes with the positional threat of taking over the entire center with }12...-- 13.f4 Bc7 14.O-O f5 15.e5+-  )
12. e6{ Black must undermine the  d5  pawn at once! }( 12...f5 13.f4 Bc7 14.e5+- { would be disastrous for Black. } )
13. f4{ The point behind  Qd2 , White gains space and drives back the  e5  bishop. }
{ Black now has to decide where to place the dark-squared bishop. If it heads for the queenside with }13. Bc7{ then  f4 - f5  going after Black's king is an idea in many lines. No need to panic though, White's 'attack' is far from dangerous! The text has the advantage of ruling out  c3 - c4  which would now blunder the queen to ... Ba5 . }( { In case of }13...Bg7 { , White will try to lock the bishop out of the game with  c3 - c4  and  e4 - e5 . This variation is fully playable and may be added in a future update to the course (let me know in the comments section if you'd like that!). } )
14. O-O
14. exd5
15. exd5
15. Ba5{ The bishop may look offside at first sight but stands rather well on  a5 , pressuring the  c3  pawn and, importantly, prevents  c3-c4 . }( {  In the main theoretical section  of the course, we analyze White's main options at this junctions:  }16.Ba3 {  ,  }16.f5 {  and  }16.d6 {  .  } )
