7. Bc4{ is the  Classical  variation of the Grünfeld - a favorite of several world champions including Botvinnik, Smyslov, Spassky and Karpov. By first bringing out the light-squared bishop, White intends to develop the knight to  e2  as opposed to  f3 . This means ... Bg4  won't pin the knight and will simply be met with  f2 - f3 . Moreover, the f-pawn is no longer obstructed and can make its way to  f4/f5  in certain variations. }
7. c5{ As usual, we undermine White's center at the earliest opportunity. }
8. Ne2
8. Nc6{ The knight pops out to its most natural square, further upping the pressure on the  d4  pawn. }
9. Be3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. b6{ was brought into the limelight by Grischuk against Aronian in the 2011 Candidates tournament. It rapidly grew in popularity since this top-level encounter and is now a mainstay in the repertoire of Grünfeld experts such as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi.     The main idea behind 10... b6  is to quickly develop the queenside with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8 . The  c4  bishop often finds itself a target and ends up having to retreat to  d3 , especially in the case of ... Na5 . }( { After }10...b6 { , White can win a pawn with }11.dxc5 { but at the cost of opening the  g7  bishop. While critical, this materialistic continuation fails to give White an opening advantage. } )
11. Rc1{ White gets the rook out of the long diagonal and places it on a useful, central square. Moreover, White pre-empts the opening of the c-file in case of ... cxd4   cxd4 . }
11. Bb7
12. d5{ gains space but opens up the  g7  bishop and gives Black a juicy central outpost for the  c6  knight. }( 12.Qd2 { transposes to the mainline . } )
12. Ne5
13. Bb3
13. c4
14. Bc2
14. e6{ stress tests White's center. Black was in great shape in the games ½-½  (49) Krasenkow,M (2612)-Troff,K  (2511) Cappelle la Grande 2016 and 0-1 (26) Turincio Garcia,S (2155)-Doshi,M  (2332) Chess.com 2020. }{     For further details, check out the main theoretical section  of the course.  }
