7. Qa4+{ is a move I've recommended a couple of times to White players looking to avoid big theoretical debates in the Grünfeld mainlines. The idea behind this move is to induce ... Bd7  or ... Nd7  in the hopes of proving these pieces are suboptimally placed. Moreover, White can often look to hinder Black's typical play based around the ... c5  break by dropping the queen back to  a3  or  b4 . }
7. Nd7{ is my preferred option. Black blocks the check and, in some lines, the knight can pop out to  b6  with a tempo on White's queen. After all, this is one of the main drawbacks of bringing out the queen so early! }( 7...Qd7 { is a reliable alternative but giving White the option of heading straight into an endgame is not in the spirit of the repertoire I'm proposing. } )
8. Nf3
8. O-O{ Black will look to break in the center with ... c5  or kick back the queen with ... Nb6  depending on how White continues. }
9. Bg5{ White hopes to provoke ... h6  and then return the bishop to  e3 , when Black will have to always worry about keeping the h-pawn protected. }
9. c5{ We can simply ignore the  g5  bishop as it's not really doing much. The typical ... c5  break is far more useful than ... h6 ! }
10. Rc1
10. a6( { Black prepares }11.-- b5! { with the tactical point that }12.Bxb5 { fails to }12...Nb6 { . Once ... b5  is in, the light-squared bishop can come out to  b7  and the queen will be developed to  c7  with a harmonious setup. }{     Please refer to the main theoretical section  of the course for further details.  } )
