5. Qb3{ was first played by Ragozin against Romanovsky in Leningrad 1932 and has been coined the  Russian  variation. White brings the queen out early on to put pressure on the  d5  pawn and induce ... dxc4  intending to later take over the center with  e2 - e4 . }
5. dxc4
6. Qxc4
6. O-O
7. e4{ White successfully establishes the ideal central pawn duo  e4  and  d4  without compromising the queenside structure. The knights are ideally placed on  f3  and  c3  supporting the central pawns in true classical fashion. The first player is, however, behind in development and the queen on  c4  is exposed, having come out into the game much earlier than normal. }
7. a6{ Black prepares ... b5  with tempo, immediately exploiting the exposed nature of White's queen. This continuation is aptly named the Hungarian variation in homage to the Hungarian players Barczay, Barcza and Ribli who all essayed 7...  a6  in their 1969 national championship. It's now achieved mainline status in large part due to the efforts of the likes of Kasparov, Svidler, Leko, Nepo and MVL. }
8. Be2{ If White could magically swap the position of his queen and bishop, he'd have a huge advantage. As it stands, the queen on  c4  is a big target and White simply doesn't have the time to shore up the center. }
8. b5{ Regardless of whether White drops the queen to  d3  or  b3 , we will strike in the center with ... c5 . }
9. Qb3( { Far more testing than }9.Qd3 { . } )
9. c5{ Black does best in immediately striking in the center with ... c5  before White has time to complete development. Sacrificing a pawn for dynamic play is the name of the game in the Grünfeld! }
10. dxc5
10. Be6{ This is the downside of tucking the queen back to  b3 , that is, Black now gets the bishop out with tempo. }
11. Qc2{ White's queen has been on quite the journey  d1🡒b3🡒c4🡒b3🡒c2 . That's 5 queen moves in the space of just 11 total moves! }
11. Nbd7{ The knight comes out to  d7  to target the  c5  pawn. }
12. Be3{ A logical, multipurpose move: White develops the bishop and covers the  c5  pawn. }( 12.c6 Nb8= { followed by ... Nxc6  will pick up the c-pawn. } )( 12.b4 { is no good due to }12...a5! { when White's queenside will collapse. } )
12. Rc8
13. Rd1{ White pins the  d7  knight in one last attempt to hold onto the  c5  pawn. }( 13.b4? { fails tactically to }13...Nxe4! 14.Nd4 Ndxc5! { Boom goes the dynamite! The point is that }15.bxc5 Bxd4-+ { is completely winning for Black. } )
13. Qa5{ Black steps out of the pin and renews the threat of ... Nxc5 . The queen is also excellently placed on  a5 , from where it pins the  c3  knight and thus indirectly pressures the  e4  pawn.      This position is analyzed in great detail in theoretical section  of the course.  }
