3. h4{ This move was tried by a few players throughout the 2000s. Veselin Topalov essayed it in the 2016 candidates, but it never got much traction possibly due to Topalov ending up at the bottom of the crosstable. Grischuk took notice though and two years later he played it whenever possible with White scoring some fine wins against several 2700+ players. }( { Note that }3...Bg7 4.Nc3 { This early h-pawn advance works pretty well against the standard Grunfeld move order with }4...d5 { as }5.h5! { gives White a turbocharged version of the 5.h4 variation not having spent a tempo on  Nf3 . As such, we're going to switch to a King's Indian-like setup where  h2 - h4  often turns out to be premature. }5...Nxh5 6.cxd5 e6 7.g4↑ { occurred in the high-profile game ½-½ (32) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2767) Jerusalem 2019 and is a position I'd rather avoid. } )
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ is an interesting, trendy move. The idea is to meet  e4  with ... e5 , not worrying much about  d4 - d5  which does displace the  c6  knight but weakens the central  e5  and  c5  squares as well as increase the scope of the  g7  bishop. }
5. d5{ As mentioned previously, White gains space and dislodges the  c6  knight but weakens the dark squares in the center. }
5. Ne5
6. e4
6. d6{ Once again,  f3 - f4  is harmless as Black can simply go ... Neg4  courtesy of White's early  h4 . }
7. Be2
7. c6{  h4-h5  is not an immediate threat so there's no need to play 7... h5  as in 0-1 (41) Fedoseev, V (2696)-Carlsen,M  (2847) Krasnaya Polyana 2021. Instead, it's more productive to chip away at White's center with ... c6 . }( 7...c6 8.h5?! { is premature. Black can simply take, not worrying about }8...Nxh5 9.Bxh5 gxh5 10.Qxh5? { with the king still on  e8 . Black is the only side attacking here with }10...Bg4 11.Qg5 Bf6-+ { which forces White's queen back. The  c4  pawn is also en prise. } )
8. Nf3{ has yet to be played but I consider it to be White's most natural move. }( 8.Nh3 { featured in 0-1 (71) Atakhan,A (2294)-Darini,P (2432) Teheran 2021. Black could have simply castled here }8...O-O { noting that }9.Nf4?! { gets hit by }9...b5! 10.cxb5 cxb5 11.Bxb5 Qa5↑ { Black has the initiative and is already threatening to win material with ... Nxe4 . White has to tread carefully to not lose immediately. } )
8. Nxf3+
9. Bxf3
9. Bd7{ is a useful developing move. Black should delay  O-O  until White does so since  h4 - h5  becomes harmless without the rook on  h1 . Another rule of thumb is to delay ... h5  until White has developed the dark-squared bishop such that  Bg5  can be met with ... h6 . }( { A sample line runs }10.O-O O-O 11.Bg5 h6 12.Be3 h5 13.Rc1 Bg4= { is very decent for Black. The queen is likely to come out to  b6  or  a5  and the  a8  rook to  c8 . } )
