2. Bg5{ The  Trompowsky  is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s. It is one of the most popular  d4  systems, not due to 2.  Bg5  being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.     White’s main idea is to double Black’s pawns with  Bxf6  and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s kingside structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once. }
2. c5{ is one of the most dynamic ways of meeting the Trompowsky. Black immediately undermines the  d4  pawn and opens up the  a5 - d8  diagonal. This enables a quick queen sortie to  a5  or  b6  in many lines. Black will look to make an argument that White has developed the  g5  bishop prematurely. }
3. Bxf6{ Taking on  f6  is most common and arguably best. After all,  Bg5 x f6  to spoil Black's kingside structure is one of White's main ideas in the Trompowsky. }
3. gxf6
4. d5{ is almost invariably played. White gains space and attempts to hinder Black's development. }( 4.dxc5 e6 5.Nf3 Bxc5 { Only Black can ever be better here thanks to the two bishops. } )
4. Qb6{ is a timely queen sortie as it forces White to play the awkward  Qc1 . White is in no position to sacrifice the  b2  pawn without the dark-squared bishop. }
5. Qc1
5. f5{ is an excellent move. Black stops  e2 - e4  and opens up the long diagonal for  Bg7 . The dark-squared bishop will be an absolute monster! }
6. g3{ is a solid continuation. White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop to ensure  d5  has enough protection and will play  c2 - c3  to blunt the long  h8 - a1  diagonal. }
6. Bg7
7. c3
7. d6{ Natural development gives Black a comfortable game. Next up are ... Nd7 - f6 , ... Bd7  and ... O-O-O . }
8. Bg2
8. Nd7
9. Nf3( 9.Nh3?! { is well met by }9...h5! { ensuring White has no time for  Nf4 +  h2 -h4 . }10.Nd2 Ne5 11.Qc2 Bd7 12.Nf4 h4⩱ { gave Black the upper hand in the game ½-½ (76) Alvarez Fernandez,E (2355) -Forcen Esteban,D (2536) Linares 2014. } )
9. Nf6
