3. Bg5{ The  Veresov  or  Richter-Veresov  variation is named after the German IM Kurt Richter and the Soviet Union GM Gavriil Veresov, who regularly played 2.  Nc3  3.  Bg5  for over a quarter of a century. Despite never being popular at the top level, several strong players have essayed this variation from time to time. Most notably, the soviet GM David Bronstein played the Veresov against GM Gavriil Veresov himself in 1959.     White's main intention is to expand in the center with  e2 - e4 . However, there is one big drawback behind developing the knight to  c3  which is that White can no longer break in the center with  c2 - c4 . As we’re about to see, White will also find it very hard to break with  e4 , meaning the knight frequently ends up being completely misplaced on  c3 . }
