1. c4{ The  English  opening was first essayed in tournament play by the 19th-century English master, Howard Staunton, in 1851. The opening didn't catch on immediately among Staunton's contemporaries and only started to garner attention in the twentieth century.     The English, a trademark hypermodern opening, diverges from the classical strategy of occupying the central  e4  and  d4  squares at the outset. Instead, it focuses on controlling and pressuring the center indirectly from the flanks. It is often used as a transpositional device to bypass established responses to 1.d4, such as the Nimzo-Indian and the Grünfeld defenses. }
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of the most principled replies to 1.c4. We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Naively developing in the same style as we would against 1.d4 2.c4 doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nf3
2. Nf6( { Black has a variety of options at his disposal to meet  2.Nf3 . We go for  2...Nf6  such that   }1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 { can be met with }2...c5 { , transposing to the text. } )
3. Nc3
3. Nc6
4. e3{ A solid continuation, preparing the  d4  break, which Sielecki and Hansen built their 1.  c4 /1.Nf3 Lifetime Repertoire around. The main drawback of this setup is that the  c1  bishop ends up being restricted by the  e3  pawn in many variations. }
4. e6{ This is Black's most popular and objectively strongest continuation. Black mirrors White's setup and likewise prepares to break in the center with ... d5 . }( 4...g6 5.d4 cxd4 6.exd4 d5 { transposing to the Panov variation of the Caro-Kann was Vigorito's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Symmetrical English. I refrained from recommending this since it requires learning a lot of theory and Black has a far harder task equalizing } )
5. d4
5. d5
6. cxd5
6. exd5{ Black can also opt for ... Nxd5 , but the IQP positions arising after the text are very comfortable. }
7. Be2{ is historically more popular than 7.  Bb5 . White wants to quickly complete kingside development and later post the bishop on  f3  to target the  d5  pawn. }
7. cxd4{ Black takes on  d4  before developing the dark-squared bishop so as to avoid having to move the bishop another time after  dxc5 . }
8. Nxd4
8. Bd6{ Once again, Black should develop the bishop to  d6  where it is far more active than on  e7 . }
9. O-O
9. O-O{ I see little need to memorize any more lines from hereon. Black has a standard IQP positions and can look to put pressure on the  d4  knight with ... Be5  next. }( {  (a)  For example, }10.Bf3 Be5 11.Nce2 Ne4= { is very comfortable for Black. } )( {  (b)  Alternatively, }10.b3 { preparing to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop is again met by }10...Be5 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.Bb2 Bf5 13.Rc1 Rc8= { Black has an excellent game with two very active bishops and plans of pushing ... c5  next. } )
