1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of the most principled replies to 1.c4. We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Naively developing in the same style as we would against 1.d4 2.c4 doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nf3
2. Nf6( { Black has a variety of options at his disposal to meet  2.Nf3 . We go for  2...Nf6  such that   }1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 { can be met with }2...c5 { , transposing to the text. } )
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nc6
5. g3{ White prioritizes the development of the  g2  bishop instead of  Nc3 . As a result, White ends up lacking control over the  d5  square in many lines. }
5. e5{ Black sends the  d4  knight packing. Normally, such a move would be a positional mistake due to the weakening of the  d5  square. However, White is in no position to exploit this with only one minor piece in the game. }
6. Nb5{ White would love to drop the knight in on  d6 . Naturally, we're not going to allow it! }( { Apart from the threat of }Nd6 { , White also prevents the immediate }6...d5? { break. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qxd5! Qxd5 9.Nc7++- { and White wins a piece. } )
6. Bb4+{ Black wants to play ... d6  to take control over this square. Logically, the bishop is first developed outside the pawn chain. }
7. N1c3{ is the most natural way of dealing with the check on  b4 . White develops the knight and keeps control over the  d6  square. }
7. d6{ Black must first stop  Nd6  before kicking back the  b5  knight with . ..a6. }
8. a3
8. Bxc3+
9. Nxc3{ is the only sensible response. Now, it's important to not give White enough time to lock down the  d5  square with  Bg2  and  Bg5 . }
9. Be6{ Black immediately goes after the  c4  pawn, which is very awkward to defend. Not only that, Black is also threatening to play ... d5 . }
10. Bg2{ White really has to sacrifice the  c4  pawn and speed up his development. }( {  (a)  }10.e4?! { leaves a gaping hole on  d4 . After }10...O-O 11.h3 b5! { Black won a nice miniature: }12.Be3 bxc4 13.Qa4 Nd4 14.O-O-O Qb6 15.Bxc4 Rab8 16.Rd2 Bxc4 17.Qxc4 Nb3+ { White resigned in 0-1  (17) Marra,E (2207)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2370) Sao Paulo 2014. } )( {  (b)  }10.b3?! d5! { and Black immediately takes over. } )
10. Bxc4
11. Bg5{ White is banking on the superior control over the  d5  square to compensate for the pawn deficit. }
11. O-O
12. Rc1
12. Rc8{ Black indirectly covers the  c4  bishop and wants to jump in with ... Nd4  followed by ... d5 . Black, who's currently a pawn up, is happy to give up the  b7  pawn to remove White's grip over the  d5  square and gain space in the center.     12 games to reach this position have been drawn, with Black winning once and never losing - a testament to the strength of Black's position. }
