1. c4{ The  English  opening was first essayed in tournament play by the 19th-century English master, Howard Staunton, in 1851. The opening didn't catch on immediately among Staunton's contemporaries and only started to garner attention in the twentieth century.     The English, a trademark hypermodern opening, diverges from the classical strategy of occupying the central  e4  and  d4  squares at the outset. Instead, it focuses on controlling and pressuring the center indirectly from the flanks. It is often used as a transpositional device to bypass established responses to 1.d4, such as the Nimzo-Indian and the Grünfeld defenses. }
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of the most principled replies to 1.c4. We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Naively developing in the same style as we would against 1.d4 2.c4 doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nf3
2. Nf6{ Black has a variety of options at his disposal to meet 2.  Nf3 . We go for 2... Nf6  such that 1.Nf3  Nf6  2.c4 can be met with 2... c5 , reaching the text. }
3. d4{ It's now time to turn our attention to 3.d4. This is arguably more testing than 3.Nc3 and 3.g3. }
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nc6
5. Nc3
5. e6
6. g3{ Fianchettoing the light-squared bishop is White's most popular and English-like continuation. The bishop is most active on the long diagonal where it's not blocked in by the  c4  pawn. }
6. Qb6{ White's play is rather slow and Black wastes no time activating the queen. The  d4  knight now has to find a new home. What is more, Black now has ideas of ...  Ne5  followed by ... Qc6  in many lines to target the  c4  pawn, which will be somewhat vulnerable once the  f1  bishop comes out to  g2 . }
7. Nb3{ White calmly retreats the knight in what is the most popular continuation. Black must act swiftly or risk being worse due to the structural weaknesses created by 5... e6 . }
7. Ne5{ Black immediately targets the  c4  pawn and clears the way for ...  Qc6 . }
8. e4{ White gains space in the center, protects the  c4  pawn and shuts down the long diagonal thus neutralizing the threat of ... Qc6 . }
8. Bb4{ The bishop comes out to its most active square and puts pressure on the  e4  pawn. }
9. Qe2{ White reinforces the  e4  pawn and is threatening to expand in the center with  f4  followed by  e5 . }
9. d6{ adequately covers the  e5  square such that  f2 - f4  cannot be followed up by  e4 - e5 . }
10. f4
10. Nc6( 10...Bxc3+ { is a mistake as after }11.bxc3 Nc6 { White has the annoying }12.Ba3± { targeting the weak pawn on  d6 . } )
11. Be3( 11.Bg2?! { is inaccurate on account of }11...e5! { when Black is threatening to jump in with ... Nd4  and is already for choice. } )
11. Bxc3+{ A nice intermediate move, compromising White's queenside structure before retreating the queen to safety. }
12. bxc3
12. Qc7
13. Bg2
13. e5{ After having given up the dark-squared bishop, Black naturally puts the central pawns on the dark-squares. This rule outs  e4 - e5  and shuts out the bishop on  g2 . Black will complete development with ... b6  followed by ... Ba6  and start targeting the weak, doubled c-pawns. 0-1 (32) Radjabov,T (2793) -Gelfand,B (2740) London 2013 }( {  (a)  }14.c5 { is a timely move to get rid of the  c4  pawn weakness. }14...b6! { ensures Black retains control over the  c5  square. }15.cxd6 Qxd6 16.O-O O-O = { with a dynamically balanced game. White's two bishops level out the compromised structure. }17.f5?! { was played in the game 0-1 (32) Radjabov,T (2793) -Gelfand,B (2740) London 2013. Now, Black could have got a big advantage with }17...Qa3! { threatening ... Ba6  when }18.Qb5 { is met by }18...Ba6! { anyhow. The point is that }19.Qxc6 Rac8 { traps the White queen! } )( {  (b)  }14.O-O { has also been tried. }14...b6 15.fxe5 Nxe5 16.Bg5 { White is trying to create pressure down the f-file. }16...Bg4 17.Qf2 Nfd7! { is a nice move. Black removes the  f6  knight from danger, thus neutralizing the pressure down the f-file, and is ready to castle on the next turn. The knight on  e5  is an absolute beast protecting the  f7  square, blocking in the  g2  bishop and eyeing the weak  c4  pawn. }18.Nd4 O-O 19.h3 Be6 { when Black picked up the  c4  pawn and went on to win in the correspondence game 0-1 (54) Kostanjsek,Z (2188)-Stronsky,V (2389) ICCF email 2012. } )
