1. Nf3{  1.Nf3 , referred to by some as the Knight's or Zukertort's opening, captures the essence of hypermodern chess strategy: control of the center from the wings, rather than immediate occupation. Named after Johannes Zukertort, a prominent player from the late 19th century, this opening is notable for its versatile and flexible nature.     It is frequently used as an 'information-seeking' move. If Black attempts to transpose into a variation that White deems unfavorable, White can reject this and pursue an independent line. Conversely, if Black steers towards a variation White is comfortable with, White can opt to follow along.      Many GMs use this opening move to steer clear of mainline 1.d4 variations like the Grünfeld where White has struggled to fight for an advantage.  Worry not, I’m proposing a practical response to 1.  Nf3  that avoids move order tricks and comfortably equalizes everywhere. }
1. Nf6
2. g3{ White starts by developing the bishop to  g2  and will only then decide whether to go for English likes with  c4 , head back into  d4  territory or opt for a King's Indian attack setup. }( 2.c4 c5 { is covered in the 1.c4  c5  2.Nf3 Nf6  chapter. } )
2. g6{ Black follows suit with ... Bg7  coming next. }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. O-O
4. O-O
5. d3
5. d5
6. Nbd2{ White goes for the standard King's Indian Attack setup, angling for the  e2 - e4  break. Despite the name of the opening, White will have exactly zero attacking chances as the  g7  fianchetto setup is virtually unbreakable. }
6. c5{ Black gains more space in the center and will bring the knight out to  c6  next, achieving a very harmonious setup. White is playing a King's Indian with an extra tempo, which is nowhere near enough to fight for an advantage. }
7. e4( 7.c3 Nc6 8.e4 dxe4 { or 8... e5  leads to very similar play as the mainline. } )
7. Nc6
8. Re1
8. dxe4{ Black has a pleasant choice at this junction. Taking on  e4  is simplest and leads to a comfortable position where Black will have no trouble bringing out his remaining forces. }( 8...e5 { is a good alternative to keep more tension in the position. }9.exd5 Nxd5 10.Nc4 f6= { has been seen in many GM encounters. Black is doing very well in this structure, planning to complete development with ...  Be6  and ... Qd7 . He'll then take a look around and start to prepare the ... f5  break with moves like ... Kg8  and ... Rae8 . } )
9. dxe4
9. Qc7{ This is the best square for the queen in this structure. Black steps out of the d-file, clearing the way for ... Rd8 , and prepares to expand in the center with ... e5 . }
10. c3
10. e5
11. Qc2
11. h6{ Black takes control over the  g5  square in preparation for ... Be6 . The  f8  rook will likely come to  d8  after which Black can start thinking about expanding on the queenside with ... b5 . Importantly, White can't easily prevent this with moves like  a2 - a4 , which will dramatically weaken the  b3  and  c4  squares Black can exploit with ... Na5 . All in all, I really like Black's prospects. }
