6. bxc3
6. Bg7( { We'll start our theoretical coverage with the absolute mainline characterized by the early bishop sortie }7.Bc4 { . } )
7. Bc4{ denotes the  Classical  variation of the Grünfeld - a favorite of several world champions including Botvinnik, Smyslov, Spassky and Karpov. By first bringing out the light-squared bishop, White intends to develop the knight to  e2  as opposed to  f3 . This means ... Bg4  won't pin the knight and will simply be met with  f2 - f3 . Moreover, the f-pawn is no longer obstructed and can make its way to  f4/f5  in certain variations. }
7. c5{ As usual, we undermine White's center at the earliest opportunity. }
8. Ne2
8. Nc6{ The knight pops out to its most natural square, further upping the pressure on the  d4  pawn. As a rule of thumb in this course, when there's a choice between putting pressure on White's centre or developing the kingside, we'll usually go for the former. }( { Black can also choose to start with }8...O-O { when }9.Be3 Nc6 { transposes to the text. } )
9. Be3
9. O-O
10. O-O{ White's setup is designed to maximally defend the  d4  pawn. In particular, this compact piece arrangement automatically neutralizes both ... Bg4  and ... Qa5  - two common ways of putting pressure on White's center. White has done a marvelous job of securing the  d4  pawn, but his pieces are not as active as they could be. }( 10.Rc1 { and }10.Rb1 { are White's main alternatives on move 10, which we'll address with the enterprising }10...Na5!? { . } )
10. b6{ was brought into the limelight by Grischuk against Aronian in the 2011 Candidates tournament. It rapidly grew in popularity since this top-level encounter and is now a mainstay in the repertoire of Grünfeld experts such as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi.     The main idea behind 10... b6  is to quickly develop the queenside with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8 . The  c4  bishop often finds itself a target and ends up having to retreat to  d3 , especially in the case of ... Na5 . }( { Alternatives include }10...cxd4 { , }{ developing the light-squared bishop with }10...Bg4 { or }10...Bd7 { as well as }10...Qc7 { and }10...Na5 { . All these require learning a substantial body of theory and are thus far less practical than }10...b6 { . } )
{ After 10... b6 , we will analyze the following options: }11. dxc5{ nets White a pawn and is the mainline. We'll see that this materialistic continuation fails to give White an opening advantage. }( { Alternatives include  (a)  }11.Qd2 { , which is second most common with 200+ games. } )( {  (b)  }11.Rc1 { is the third most played move with 180+ games. } )( {  (c)  Pawn moves such as }11.h4 { , }11.f4 { , }11.f3 { and }11.e5 { are far less common and featured in less than 100 OTB games. } )
