1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5{ The Grünfeld is named after the Austrian Chess player Ernst Franz Grünfeld, who defeated Alekhine in his first foray with this defense in Vienna 1922. Botvinnik, Fischer and Kasparov would then take it up with great results and, nowadays, this defense features in the repertoire of almost every single top chess player. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. e4{ White takes over the center and expels our knight from  d5 . }
5. Nxc3
6. bxc3
6. Bg7
7. Bc4{ denotes the Classical variation of the Grünfeld - a favorite of several world champions including Botvinnik, Smyslov, Spassky and Karpov. By first bringing out the light-squared bishop, White intends to develop the knight to  e2  as opposed to  f3 . This means ... Bg4  won't pin the knight and will simply be met with  f2 - f3 . Moreover, the f-pawn is no longer obstructed and can make its way to  f4/f5  in certain variations. }
7. c5{ As usual, we undermine White's center at the earliest opportunity. }
8. Ne2
8. Nc6{ The knight pops out to its most natural square, further upping the pressure on the  d4  pawn. }
9. Be3
9. O-O
10. Rc1{ A logical move, getting the rook out of the long diagonal and placing it on a file that is likely to be opened up after exchanging on  d4 . White also delays castling, keeping open the option of  h4 - h5  later on. }( 10.O-O { tranposes to the 9.  O-O   Nc6  10.  Be3  variation. } )
10. Na5{ Black immediately goes for active play while White's king is still in the center. }( 10...cxd4 11.cxd4 Qa5+ { was extensively analyzed by Avrukh in the book  GM Repertoire: The Grünfeld . The renowned Israeli analyst made a convincing case that Black is fine in this variation. I prefer 10... Na5  as it avoids reams of theory and gives Black at least equal chances in all the resulting variations. } )
11. Bd3{ White naturally preserves the light-squared bishop. }
11. b6
12. dxc5{ has yet to figure in my database, but there's instructive value in considering it. }
12. Be6{ This is the entire point: getting the knight to  c4  is more important than a measly pawn. }
13. c4( 13.cxb6?! axb6 14.c4 Rc8⩱ { and Black will recover the c-pawn with interest. } )
13. bxc5
14. Bxc5
14. Rc8{ Black will get the c-pawn back and it's White that needs to start thinking about equalizing as the following sample line illustrates. }( 15.Bxa7 Nxc4 16.Bxc4 Rxc4 17.Qxd8 Rxd8 { The  e4  pawn is hanging so White has no time to castle. }18.Rxc4 Bxc4 19.Be3 Rb8 { White will find it very hard to complete development in the face of Black's powerful two bishops and rook. } )
