10. b6{ was brought into the limelight by Grischuk against Aronian in the 2011 Candidates tournament. It rapidly grew in popularity since this top-level encounter and is now a mainstay in the repertoire of Grünfeld experts such as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi.     The main idea behind 10... b6  is to quickly develop the queenside with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8 . The  c4  bishop often finds itself a target and ends up having to retreat to  d3 , especially in the case of ... Na5 . }( { After }10...b6 { , White can win a pawn with }11.dxc5 { but at the cost of opening the  g7  bishop. While critical, this materialistic continuation fails to give White an opening advantage. } )
11. h4
11. e6{ Without a rook on  h1 , Black is able to get her majesty to  h4  just in time. }
12. h5( 12.Bg5 { was played twice by Korobov against Ding and Wei Yi. I quite like the novel }12...Bf6 { with the point that exchanging the dark-squared bishops with }13.Bxf6?! { is dubious as after }13...Qxf6 14.h5 Rd8 15.Bb5 Bb7 { White's h-pawn is going nowhere and the  d4  pawn is very vulnerable. } )
12. Qh4{ Effectively stops  h6  when it's not clear what White has accomplished. Meanwhile, the  e4  pawn is hanging and ... cxd4 , ... Rd8 , ... Bb7  are coming to pressure White's center. Two sample continuations are: }( {  (a)  }13.Qc1 cxd4 14.cxd4 { . A nifty idea played by Praggnanandhaa against Giri, who quickly went astray after }14...Qxe4 15.Rd1 Na5?! { . Instead, Black should continue developing the queenside with }{   }14...Bb7! { not fearing }15.h6 { as after }15...Bf6 { Black will get ... g5  in and pick up the  h6  pawn.  Note:  I analyze this position in much more detail in the upcoming alternative  variation, which you can opt to train. } )( {  (b)  More common is   }13.hxg6 hxg6 14.f3 cxd4 15.cxd4 Rd8 { with typical play against the  d4  pawn. In the game ½-½ }{ (58) }{ Timofeev,A }{ (2600) }{ -Kurnosov,I }{ (2645) }{ Khanty-Mansiysk 2012, White immediately went astray with }16.Bb5? { when Black could have pounced with }16...Nxd4! 17.Nxd4 Qh8!∓ { a strong retreating move that both players must have missed. The  d4  knight will drop on the next turn and, as a result, Black will emerge with an extra pawn. } )
