10. b6{ was brought into the limelight by Grischuk against Aronian in the 2011 Candidates tournament. It rapidly grew in popularity since this top-level encounter and is now a mainstay in the repertoire of Grünfeld experts such as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi.     The main idea behind 10... b6  is to quickly develop the queenside with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8 . The  c4  bishop often finds itself a target and ends up having to retreat to  d3 , especially in the case of ... Na5 . }( { After }10...b6 { , White can win a pawn with }11.dxc5 { but at the cost of opening the  g7  bishop. While critical, this materialistic continuation fails to give White an opening advantage. } )
11. Rc1{ White gets the rook out of the long diagonal and places it on a useful, central square. Moreover, White pre-empts the opening of the c-file in case of ... cxd4   cxd4 . }
11. Bb7
12. Bb5( { is a very serious alternative to the mainline with }12.Qd2 { . } ){ White steps out of ... Na5  tempos and, by vacating the  c4  square, clears the way for a central push with  d5  followed by  c4 . }
12. Rc8{ is the usual square for the queenside rook in this variation. Black isn't worried about the immediate  d4 - d5 . }
13. Qd2( { Given }13.d5 { doesn't yield anything, White improves the queen's position and prepares to bring the  f1  rook into the game. } )
13. e6
14. Rfd1
14. cxd4( 14...Na5 { is imprecise as it runs into }15.Bg5 { when the desirable }15...Qd6 16.e5 Qd5 { is refuted by }17.Nf4 { since Black's queen gets trapped after }17...Qe4 18.f3 Qf5 19.h4+- { . There's no good way to prevent  Bd3  or  g4 , winning the queen on  f5 . }( { Including   }14...cxd4 15.cxd4 { and only then playing }15...Na5 { ensures that }16.Bg5 { can be met with }16...Qd6 { when }17.e5?! { merely gives away the  d5  square allowing }17...Qd5 { . With ... cxd4   cxd4  included, }18.Nf4?? { simply blunders the  b5  bishop, i.e. }Qxb5-+ { wins on the spot. } ) )
15. cxd4
15. Na5{ Taking on  d4  followed by ... Na5  is very thematic (even if here it does not come with a tempo on the  c4  bishop). Black opens up the light-squared bishop and prepares to exchange a pair of major pieces down the c-file. This will leave White unable to fully cover the center and all points of entry for Black's pieces (for example the c-file and the  c4  square). }
16. f3
16. Rxc1{ With the  e4  pawn protected, Black shifts his focus to the  d4  pawn. Step 1 is to remove one defender of the  d4  pawn, namely the  d1  rook before going ... a6  and ... Nc6 . }
17. Rxc1
17. a6
18. Bd3
18. Nc6{ Black had no issues in the games ½-½ }{ (70) }{ Sjugirov,S }{ (2663) }{ -Preotu,R }{ (2487) }{ 2021 and ½-½ }{ (48) }{ Nepomniachtchi,I }{ (2792) }{ -Vachier Lagrave,M }{ (2757) }{ Saint Louis 2022. ... Qd7  and ... Rd8  are on the agenda with excellent play against the  d4  pawn. }
