7. Bc4{ denotes the Classical variation of the Grünfeld - a favorite of several world champions including Botvinnik, Smyslov, Spassky and Karpov. By first bringing out the light-squared bishop, White intends to develop the knight to  e2  as opposed to  f3 . This means ... Bg4  won't pin the knight and will simply be met with  f2 - f3 . Moreover, the f-pawn is no longer obstructed and can make its way to  f4/f5  in certain variations. }
7. c5{ As usual, we undermine White's center at the earliest opportunity. }
8. Ne2
8. Nc6{ The knight pops out to its most natural square, further upping the pressure on the  d4  pawn. }
9. Be3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. b6{ was brought into the limelight by Grischuk against Aronian in the 2011 Candidates tournament. It rapidly grew in popularity since this top-level encounter and is now a mainstay in the repertoire of Grünfeld experts such as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ian Nepomniachtchi.     The main idea behind 10... b6  is to quickly develop the queenside with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8 . The  c4  bishop often finds itself a target and ends up having to retreat to  d3 , especially in the case of ... Na5 . }( { After }10...b6 { , White can win a pawn with }11.dxc5 { but at the cost of opening the  g7  bishop. While critical, this materialistic continuation fails to give White an opening advantage. } )
11. dxc5{ Capturing the  c5  pawn is arguably the most critical continuation. }
11. Qc7{ Exclam, Black ignores the  c5  pawn and prioritizes rapid development. White is welcome to take on  b6 ! }
12. Nd4{ This is the main idea behind  dxc5 . White is threatening to win material with  Nxc6  followed by  Bd5 . Not only that, White's knight can also jump to  b5  to harass our queen. }( { The alternative knight jump }12.Nf4 { is harmless. Simply }12...e6!= { and White's knight is going nowhere useful. } )( { Similarly, }12.Bf4 Be5! 13.Qc1 Bb7= { is nothing for White. The first player is more than welcome to take on  e5  and activate our knight. } )
12. Ne5{ Not only stops  Nxc6  but also comes with a tempo on White's bishop. In many lines, Black's knight will find its way to  g4  with threats on  h2  and  e3 . }
13. Nb5{ White does best in first forcing the queen back before moving the light-squared bishop. }
13. Qb8
14. Be2{ This is the best square for the bishop from where it takes control over the  g4  square, preventing the ... Ng4  like ideas that we saw in the previous variations. White is now planning  f2 - f4  to kick back the  e5  knight. }
14. bxc5{ A strong novelty way back in 2011, when Grischuk completely revitalized the entire 10...  b6  system! }
15. Rb1{ A natural move, lining up the rook against the queen on  b8 . }
15. a6{ White has no good discovered attacks at the moment so this is the perfect time to force the knight back! }
16. Na3( 16.Nd4 { allows Black to kick back all of White's forces with tempi: }16...Qc7 17.Nb3 Rd8 18.Qc2 c4= { likely followed by ... Nd3  or ... Bg4  was very comfortable for Black in 0-1 }{ (70) }{ Ganguly,S }{ (2619) }{ -Giri,A }{ (2715) }{ Leon 2012. } )
16. Qc7
17. f4{ White would love us to drop the knight back to  c6  when  Nc4  would come. }
17. Rd8{ An important move, forcing the queen away from the  d1  square to enable .. }
18. Qc2
18. Ng4
19. Bxg4( { There's no real time for }19.Bc1 { as after }19...c4! { The queen is joining the action with ... Qc5 +, for example }20.Bxc4 Qc5 21.Kh1 Bd7 22.h3 Nf6= { with the idea ... Bc6  when White can hardly move. The  c1  bishop is tied down to the  a3  knight which is in turn tied down to the  c4  bishop! } )
19. Bxg4{ Optically, Black seems to have no problems with a symmetric pawn structure and the pair of bishops. There's, however, one tricky idea Karjakin came up with that we need to know how to handle. }
