8. Bb5+{ has been played in several top-level encounters. Anand essayed it against Gelfand in game 1 of the 2012 World Championship so it certainly deserves some attention.     What's the point behind this early bishop sortie? First and foremost, White clears the way for a quick  O-O  with tempo. Moreover, White hopes to hinder Black's development and, in case of ... Nc6 , has the extra option of easing the pressure on the  d4  pawn with  Bxc6  while damaging Black's structure.     It's not all great though as the bishop on  b5  can easily find itself exposed to moves like ... Qa5 . }
8. Nc6{ This is Black's most ambitious and strongest continuation. Black's knight is most active on  c6 , pressuring  d4 . There's no need to be afraid of walking into a pin as we're about to see. }
9. d5{ Undermining the  c6  knight is the first move to check. }
9. Qa5{ is practically necessary, simultaneously hitting the  b5  bishop and  c3  pawn. }
10. Rb1
10. Bxc3+( { Gelfand opted for }10...a6 { and easily drew against Anand, but I prefer grabbing the  c3  pawn. I couldn't find full equality for Black after }11.Bxc6 bxc6 12.O-O O-O 13.dxc6⩲ { . } )
11. Bd2
11. a6{ Black must now break the pin. }
12. Bxc6+( 12.Ba4 Bxd2+ { is a timely moment to take on  d2  as White's queen needs to keep in touch with the  a4  bishop. As such, White is forced to play }13.Nxd2 { when }13...b5 { breaking the pin solves all of Black's problems. }14.dxc6 bxa4 15.O-O Be6= { stops  Nc4  and takes aim at the weak  a2  pawn. Black plans to follow up with ... O-O  and ... Rc8  and had a good game in ½-½ }{ (27) }{ David,A }{ (2414) }{ -Erdos,V }{ (2622) }{ Baile Govora 2017.     Note:  you can opt to train this clickable variation in the upcoming  alternative trainable line. } )
