11. Nxe5( 11.O-O { is well met by }11...a6 { . After }12.Be2 Nxf3+ 13.Bxf3 b5= { Black will smoothly complete development with ... Qd6  and ... Bd7 . The bishop on  f3  is awkwardly placed, preventing White from expanding on the kingside with  f2 - f4 .      Note:  this clickable line was given as a trainable exercise in the typical middlegame themes chapter. Click here  for a direct link. } )
11. Bxe5
12. O-O{ White is finally ready to expand in the center with  f2 - f4 , which we can anticipate by taking on  c3 . }( 12.Qd2 { can be met with both }12...a6 { or the typical }12...e6 { to undermine the  d5  pawn. Following }13.f4 Bc7 14.Bc4 a6 15.a4 b5! { works wonders. }16.axb5 axb5 17.Bxb5 exd5 18.Bc6! Ra6 19.Bxd5 Rd6 20.O-O Bf5! { and White's center collapsed in the correspondence game ½-½ }{ (26) }{ Nyvlt,Z }{ (2426) }{ -Walczak,P }{ (2459) }{ ICCF email 2011. } )( { Worse is   }18.exd5?! { , which occurred in the game ½-½ }{ (25) }{ Slavin,A }{ (2397) }{ -Hawkins,J }{ (2511) }{ England 2013 when Black could have got a huge advantage with }18...Bf5! 19.Rb2 c4 { White's lack of development comes to bite him. The  e1  king is stranded in the center and ... Bb6  is coming to cut it off while }20.O-O Bd3 21.Re1 Qxd5-+ { sees Black restore material equality with a dominant position. } )
12. Bxc3
13. Be3
13. b6{ protects the  c5  pawn and simply wants to finish development with ... Bd7 , when Black would effectively be up a pawn. }( { As such, White must act quickly. A sample line runs }14.Qc2 Bg7 15.Bc6 Rb8 16.Bf4 { which nets White an exchange. Black already has one pawn and will emerge with an unopposed, monster dark-squared bishop that'll provide more than enough compensation. }16...e5 17.dxe6 Bxe6 18.Bxb8 Qxb8 19.f4 { This position was reached in the game ½-½ (34) Akobian,V (2614)-Grandelius,N (2661) Krasnaya Polyana 2021, where Black played 19... Qd6 . I prefer the stutter-step }19...Qc8 { which still hits the bishop and allows Black to meet }20.Bb5 { with }20...a6= { , } )( { and   }20.Ba4 { with }20...Qa6= { . I'd already take Black with the powerful pair of bishops, passed c-pawn and a juicy target on  a2 . } ){  Note:  this sample continuation is given as an alternative  line that higher-rated/advanced players can opt to train. }( 14.Bc6 Rb8 15.Bf4 e5 16.dxe6 Bxe6= { leads to very similar play. } )
