7. Nf3{ is one of the main tabiyas in the Grünfeld. White has the 'ideal' center, which Black will now look to undermine with moves like ... c5 , ... Nc6 , and ... Bg4 . }
7. c5{ Black should waste no time in undermining White's center. }
8. Bb5+{ has been played in several top-level encounters. Anand essayed it against Gelfand in game 1 of the 2012 World Championship so it certainly deserves some attention.     What's the point behind this early bishop sortie? First and foremost, White clears the way for a quick  O-O  with tempo. Moreover, White hopes to hinder Black's development and, in case of ... Nc6 , has the extra option of easing the pressure on the  d4  pawn with  Bxc6  while damaging Black's structure.     It's not all great though as the bishop on  b5  can easily find itself exposed to moves like ... Qa5 . }
8. Nc6{ This is Black's most ambitious and strongest continuation. Black's knight is most active on  c6 , pressuring  d4 . There's no need to be afraid of walking into a pin as we're about to see. }
9. Rb1{ is the latest wrinkle in the  8.  Bb5 +  variation. Combining ideas from the 7.  Nf3  8.  Rb1  variation, White protects the  b5  bishop and removes the rook from the long diagonal so as to advance  d4 - d5  without having to worry about ... Bxc3 . }
9. O-O
10. d5{ With our king safely on  g8 , this move loses its bite as the  c6  knight is free to move up to  e5 . }
10. Ne5
11. Nxe5( 11.O-O { is well met by }11...a6 { After }12.Be2 Nxf3+ 13.Bxf3 b5= { Black will smoothly complete development with ... Qd6  and ... Bd7 . The bishop on  f3  is awkwardly placed, preventing White from expanding on the kingside with  f2 - f4 . } )
11. Bxe5
12. O-O{ White is finally ready to expand in the center with  f2 - f4 , which we can anticipate by taking on  c3 . }
12. Bxc3
13. Be3
13. b6{ protects the  c5  pawn and simply wants to finish development with ... Bd7 , when Black would effectively be up a pawn. }
14. Qc2
14. Bg7
15. Bc6
15. Rb8
16. Bf4{ nets White an exchange. However, Black already has an extra pawn and will emerge with an unopposed, monster dark-squared bishop that'll provide more than enough compensation. }
16. e5
17. dxe6
17. Bxe6
18. Bxb8
18. Qxb8
19. f4
{ This position was reached in the game ½-½ }{ (34) }{ Akobian,V }{ (2614) }{ -Grandelius,N }{ (2661) }{ Krasnaya Polyana 2021, where Black played 19... Qd6 . I prefer the stutter-step }19. Qc8( { which still hits the bishop and allows Black to meet }20.Bb5 { with }20...a6 { and   }20.Ba4 { with }20...Qa6 { . I'd already take Black with the powerful pair of bishops, passed c-pawn and a juicy target on  a2 . } )
