7. c5
8. Rb1{ It's now time to turn our attention to White's most popular 8th move and one of the most challenging variations in the Grünfeld - the  Modern Exchange  variation. White removes the rook from the long diagonal, enabling a quick  d4 - d5  in many lines, and puts pressure on the  b7  pawn. Not only that, White now has the option of meeting ... Qa5  with  Rb5 . }
8. O-O( { It's important to start with }8...O-O { here as }8...Nc6?! { runs into the disruptive check }9.d5 Ne5 10.Bb5+± { . } )
9. Be2{ A natural developing move, clearing the way for  O-O . }( 9.Be3 { is illogical on account of }9...Qa5 { If White wanted to go  Be3 , there's no reason to first play  Rb1 . } )( 9.Qd2 { is a better alternative. White protects the  c3  pawn in order to push  d5 . Black should welcome this advance as after }9...Nc6 10.d5 Na5! 11.Be2 e6= { gives Black good play against White's center. The bishop on  c1  is certainly unhappy with the position of White's queen. } )
9. Nc6{ This provocative and dynamic move is my recommendation. We welcome  d4 - d5  as this will only increase the scope of the  g7  bishop! }( {  (a)  }9...cxd4 { is the most popular continuation, leading to a complicated position after }10.cxd4 Qa5+ 11.Bd2 Qxa2 12.O-O { =∞ }{ 2700+ GMs and correspondence players frequently go for this line with Black having memorized practically every continuation all the way to a draw. White has full compensation for the pawn and is risking very little in most lines. Conversely, Black needs to be rather accurate to maintain the balance, which requires learning (and remembering!) many forced lines - certainly  not  what this course is about! } )( {   }11.Qd2 Qxd2+ 12.Bxd2 { While practice has shown Black is fine in this game, landing straight in an endgame as early as move 12 is not what we signed up for! } )( {  (b)  }9...b6!? 10.O-O Bb7 { is playable. However, I couldn't fully equalize with Black after }11.d5 Bxc3 12.h4! { . } )
