8. O-O( { It's important to start with }8...O-O { here as }8...Nc6?! { runs into the disruptive check }9.d5 Ne5 10.Bb5+± { . } )
9. Be2{ A natural developing move, clearing the way for  O-O . }( {  (a)  }9.Be3 { is illogical on account of }9...Qa5 { . If White wanted to go  Be3 , there's no reason to first play  Rb1 . } )( {  (b)  }9.Qd2 { is a better alternative. White protects the  c3  pawn in order to push  d5 . Black should welcome this advance as after }9...Nc6 10.d5 Na5! 11.Be2 e6= { gives Black good play against White's center. The bishop on  c1  is certainly unhappy with the position of White's queen. } )
