13. Bxd4{ There's still quite a lot of play left in this middlegame. If White is not careful, the bishop on  f3  can find itself out of the game following the exchange of dark-squared bishops. }( { Why take with the bishop you may ask? The reason is that after both }14.Bxd4 Nxd4 15.Rxb7 Qd6 { and   }14.Bh6 Bg7 15.Bxg7 Kxg7 16.Rxb7 Rb8 { as in the game ½-½ }{ (40) }{ Sarana,A }{ (2651) }{ -Savchenko,B }{ (2581) }{ Moscow 2019, Black can make a good case that the knight is superior to White's light-squared bishop. Comparatively }{   }13...Nxd4 14.Rxb7 Qd6 15.Qa4 Nxf3 16.gxf3 Be5 17.Rd1 Qf6 18.Kg2 Qh4 19.h3 { while objectively fine, makes it harder to play for the full point with Black. } )
