12. Qd2{ is White's most popular and strongest continuation. Despite blocking the  d2  bishop, the queen defends  c3  and supports the  d5  pawn thus threatening to take over the center with  f2 - f4  and, if allowed,  e4 - e5 . }( 12.Qd2 { comes with the positional threat of taking over the entire center with }12...-- 13.f4 Bc7 14.O-O f5 15.e5+-  )( {  (a)  }12.Bd2 { is an inferior way of protecting the  c3  pawn since it blocks the White queen, which no longer defends the  d5 . This allows Black to strike with }12...f5! 13.exf5 Bxf5= { hitting the  b1  rook. In case of  Rxb7 , ... Qxd5  gives Black at least equal chances. } )( {  (b)  }12.Rb3 { White hopes to play  c3 - c4  and then activate the rook along the 3rd rank. We're not going to allow any of this! }12...c4 13.Bxc4 { is a nice tactical solution. }13...Qc7 14.Be2 { 14.  Qe2  would have run into 14...  Bg4 ! }14...Bxc3+= { restores material equality with good prospects. } )( {  (c)  }12.c4 { is answered by }12...Qa5+ { picking up the  a2  pawn. }13.Bd2 Qxa2⩱ { I fail to see sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. }( {  (d)  }12.Qc2 e6 13.f4 Bg7 14.dxe6 Bxe6= { is fully equal. There's no need to be afraid of }15.Rxb7 { as after }15...Qa5 { Black will get the pawn back, for example }16.e5 Rab8 17.Rxb8 Rxb8 18.O-O Bxa2 19.Be3 Be6 20.Bf3 f6 { and a draw was agreed in ½-½ }{ (20) }{ Degerhammar,R }{ (2500) }{ -Cerrato, R }{ (2470) }{ ICCF email 2015. } ) )
12. e6{ Black must undermine the  d5  pawn at once! }( 12...f5 13.f4 Bc7 14.e5+- { would be disastrous for Black. } )
13. f4{ The point behind  Qd2 , White gains space and drives back the  e5  bishop. }( 13.O-O exd5 14.exd5 Qd6= { leads to a better version of the mainline for Black as the bishop was allowed to stay on  e5 . } )( 13.c4 { or }13.Bc4 { are no good on account of }13...Qh4!  )
{ Black now has to decide where to place the dark-squared bishop. }13. Bc7{ A consequence of heading to the queenside with the bishop is that  f4 - f5  to go after Black's king becomes an idea in many lines. No need to panic though, White's 'attack' is far from dangerous! The text has the advantage of ruling out  c3 - c4  which would now blunder the queen to ... Ba5 . }( { In case of }13...Bg7 { , White will try to lock the bishop out of the game with  c3 - c4  and  e4 - e5 . This variation is fully playable and may be added in a future update to the course. } )
14. O-O{ White tucks the king away and is threatening  c2 - c4  (now that ... Ba5  is no longer a threat). The text is over 10x more popular than the alternatives below: }( {  (a)  }14.Bc4 { is met by }14...a6 { with the idea ... b5 . Remarkably, after }15.a4 { Black plays }15...b5! { anyhow! Following }16.axb5 axb5 17.Bxb5 exd5 18.Bc6 Ra6 19.Bxd5 Rd6 20.O-O Bf5! { with dynamic play in the correspondence game ½-½ (33) Gunkel,W (2353)-Boles,R (2102) ICCF email 2015. } )( {  (b)  }14.dxe6 Bxe6 15.Rxb7 Bb6 { comes with the threat of ... Qc8 , trapping the rook. This forces }16.Qxd8 Rfxd8 17.O-O c4+ 18.Kh1 Re8! { as seen in the correspondence game Baciak,M }{ (2179) }{ -Sindelar,F }{ (1833) }{ ICCF email 2017. Black's last move, lining up the rook against the  e4  pawn and  e2  bishop, is quite clever. It comes with the immediate threat of ... Bc8  when I'd already take Black. } )
14. exd5
15. exd5
15. Ba5{ The bishop may look offside at first sight but stands rather well on  a5 , pressuring the  c3  pawn and, importantly, preventing  c3 - c4 . }
16. Ba3{ White hits the  c5  pawn in order to provoke ... b6 . The first player will then try to make the case that the  a5  bishop is misplaced. However, the  a3  bishop is hardly impressive! }
16. b6
17. Rbd1( 17.Bb5 { stopping ... Re8  and intending to anchor the bishop on  c6  is well met by }17...Qd6 18.Bc6 Bf5! 19.Rbd1 Rac8= { when Black can fight for the e-file with ...  Rc7 - e7 . } )
17. Qd6{ firmly blocks the d-pawn. Black will complete development with ... Bf5  and then bring the rooks to the central files. }( { A sample line goes }18.Bb2 Bf5 19.Qc1 Rae8 20.Bb5 Re7 21.c4 f6= { Black controls the e-file meaning White has no hopes for an edge. } )
