8. Rb1{ It's now time to turn our attention to White's most popular 8th move and one of the most challenging variations in the Grünfeld - the modern exchange variation. White removes the rook from the long diagonal, enabling a quick  d4 - d5  in many lines, and puts pressure on the  b7  pawn. Not only that, White now has the option of meeting ... Qa5  with  Rb5 . }
8. O-O( { It's important to start with }8...O-O { here as }8...Nc6?! { runs into the disruptive check }9.d5 Ne5 10.Bb5+± { . } )
9. Be2{ A natural developing move, clearing the way for  O-O . }
9. Nc6{ This provocative and dynamic move is my recommendation. We welcome  d4 - d5  as this will only increase the scope of the  g7  bishop! }
10. d5( { Advancing in the center with  d5  was White's main idea behind  8.Rb1.  The }10.d5 { advance is timely given that }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { gives White an easy, ready-made attack with  Qh6  and  h4 - h5 . } )
10. Ne5( { I know I'm repeating myself but I really want to drive the following point home. Do  NOT  go for }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { when Black's king will come under a vicious attack after  h4 - h5  and  Qh6 . } )
11. Nxe5{ is really the only way to continue. The alternatives below land White in hot water. }
11. Bxe5
