14. exd5
15. exd5
15. Ba5{ The bishop may look offside at first sight but stands rather well on  a5 , pressuring the  c3  pawn and, importantly, preventing  c3 - c4 . }
16. f5{ comes with the deadly threat of  f6  and  Qh6 , so Black has no option but to take on  f5 . }
16. Bxf5
17. Rxb7{ White traded the f-pawn for the  b7  pawn and is counting on the potentially disruptive power of the rook on the 7th rank. Black is, however, extremely active and practice has shown he has at least equal chances. }( 17.Rxf5? { is far too optimistic. The  d8  queen controls the  g5  square so we can simply take. }17...gxf5 18.Rxb7 Qf6-+ { when White does not have a semblance of an attack. } )
17. Qd6{ The usual square for our queen in this variation, firmly blocking the d-pawn while connecting the rooks. }
18. Bc4{ White reinforces the  d5  pawn thus liberating the queen from this task. }( 18.Rb5 Bc7 19.g3 { has been tried. Here, I like }19...Rab8 { keeping as much life in the position as possible. }20.Ba3 Rfd8 21.Rxb8 Rxb8 22.c4 Qe7= { On a good day, Black can hope to activate the  e7  bishop with ... Be5 - d4 . } )( { (   }19...c4 { leads to a repetition after }20.Rxf5! gxf5 21.Ba3! Qxa3 22.Qg5+= { with a perpetual. }{ ) } )
18. Rfb8{ Black does best in neutralizing White's active rook. }
19. Rxb8+( 19.Rb3 Rxb3 20.axb3 Qe5= { Black is planning ... Re8  and can rapidly develop a strong initiative. } )
19. Rxb8{ Black is very active and can look to further improve his pieces with ... Qe5  and ... Rb1 . This is all you really need to know.     I leave you with a couple of sample continuations, which you can opt to train in the upcoming alternative  variations. }( {  (a)  }20.Qg5 { threatens the rather obvious  Rxf5 . }20...Bxc3 { Black can go ahead and capture the  c3  pawn, after which the bishop will be redeployed to  d4 . }21.Rxf5 Bd4+ 22.Kh1 Rb4 23.Bd3 f6 24.Qg4 Be5 25.Bc4 Bd4= { with a repetition. } )( {  (b)  }20.Qe1 { White drops the queen back, threatening  Bf4  which Black can put a stop to with }20...Rb1= { I'd definitely take Black here. We can look to target White's kingside with ... Bc7  on the next turn. } )
