14. O-O{ White tucks the king away and is threatening  c2 - c4  (now that ... Ba5  is no longer a threat). The text is over 10x more popular than the alternatives below: }( {  (a)  }14.Bc4 { is well met by }14...a6 { with the idea ... b5 . Remarkably, after }15.a4 { Black plays }15...b5! { anyhow! Following }16.axb5 axb5 17.Bxb5 exd5 18.Bc6 Ra6 19.Bxd5 Rd6 20.O-O Bf5! { with dynamic play in the correspondence game ½-½ (33) Gunkel,W (2353)-Boles,R (2102) ICCF email 2015. } )( {  (b)  }14.dxe6 Bxe6 15.Rxb7 Bb6 { comes with the threat of ... Qc8 , trapping the rook. This forces }16.Qxd8 Rfxd8 17.O-O c4+ 18.Kh1 Re8! { as seen in the correspondence game Baciak,M }{ (2179) }{ -Sindelar,F }{ (1833) }{ ICCF email 2017. Black's last move, lining up the rook against the  e4  pawn and  e2  bishop, is quite clever. It comes with the immediate threat of ... Bc8  when I'd already take Black. } )
14. exd5
15. exd5
15. Ba5{ The bishop may look offside at first sight but stands rather well on  a5 , pressuring the  c3  pawn and, importantly, preventing  c3 - c4 . }
16. f5{ comes with the deadly threat of  f6  and  Qh6 , so Black has no option but to take on  f5 . }
16. Bxf5
17. Rxb7{ White traded the f-pawn for the  b7  pawn and is counting on the potentially disruptive power of the rook on the 7th rank. Black is, however, extremely active and practice has shown he has at least equal chances. }( 17.Rxf5? { is far too optimistic. The  d8  queen controls the  g5  square so we can simply take. }17...gxf5?! 18.Rxb7 Qf6-+ { when White does not have a semblance of an attack. } )
17. Qd6{ The usual square for our queen in this variation, firmly blocking the d-pawn while connecting the rooks. }
18. Bc4( 18.Rb5 Bc7 19.g3 { has been tried. Here, I like }19...Rab8 { keeping as much life in the position as possible. }( 19...c4 { leads to a repetition after }20.Rxf5! gxf5 21.Ba3! Qxa3 22.Qg5+= { with a perpetual. } )20.Ba3 Rfd8 21.Rxb8 Rxb8 22.c4 Qe7= { On a good day, Black can hope to activate the  e7  bishop with ... Be5 - d4 . } )
18. Rfb8{ Black does best in neutralizing White's active rook. }
19. Rxb8+( 19.Rb3 Rxb3 20.axb3 Qe5= { Black is planning ... Re8  and can rapidly develop a strong initiative. } )
19. Rxb8{ Black is very active and can look to further improve his pieces with ... Qe5  and ... Rb1 . }
20. Qe1{ White drops the queen back, threatening  Bf4 . }
20. Rb1{ Pins the bishop, thus stopping  Bf4 . I'd definitely take Black here. We can look to target White's queenside with ... Bc7  on the next turn. }
