7. c5
8. Rb1{ It's now time to turn our attention to White's most popular 8th move and one of the most challenging variations in the Grünfeld - the modern exchange variation. White removes the rook from the long diagonal, enabling a quick  d4 - d5  in many lines, and puts pressure on the  b7  pawn. Not only that, White now has the option of meeting ... Qa5  with  Rb5 . }
8. O-O( { It's important to start with }8...O-O { here as }8...Nc6?! { runs into the disruptive check }9.d5 Ne5 10.Bb5+± { . } )
9. Be2{ A natural developing move, clearing the way for  O-O . }
9. Nc6{ This provocative and dynamic move is my recommendation. We welcome  d4 - d5  as this will only increase the scope of the  g7  bishop! }
10. d5( { Advancing in the center with  d5  was White's main idea behind  8.Rb1.  The }10.d5 { advance is timely given that }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { gives White an easy, ready-made attack with  Qh6  and  h4 - h5 . } )
10. Ne5( { I know I'm repeating myself but I really want to drive the following point home. Do  NOT  go for }10...Bxc3+? 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2→ { when Black's king will come under a vicious attack after  h4 - h5  and  Qh6 . } )
11. Nxe5{ is really the only way to continue. The alternatives below land White in hot water. }
11. Bxe5
12. Qd2{ is White's most popular and strongest continuation. Despite blocking the  d2  bishop, the queen defends  c3  and supports the  d5  pawn thus threatening to take over the center with  f2 - f4  and, if allowed,  e4 - e5 . }( 12.Qd2 { comes with the positional threat of taking over the entire center with }12...-- 13.f4 Bc7 14.O-O f5 15.e5+-  )( {  (a)  }12.Bd2 { is an inferior way of protecting the  c3  pawn since it blocks the White queen, which no longer defends the  d5 . This allows Black to strike with }12...f5! 13.exf5 Bxf5= { hitting the  b1  rook. In case of  Rxb7 , ... Qxd5  gives Black at least equal chances. } )( {  (b)  }12.Rb3 { White hopes to play  c3 - c4  and then activate the rook along the 3rd rank. We're not going to allow any of this! }12...c4 13.Bxc4 { is a nice tactical solution. }13...Qc7 14.Be2 { 14.  Qe2  would have run into 14...  Bg4 ! }14...Bxc3+= { restores material equality with good prospects. } )( {  (c)  }12.c4 { is answered by }12...Qa5+ { picking up the  a2  pawn. }13.Bd2 Qxa2⩱ { I fail to see sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. }( {  (d)  }12.Qc2 e6 13.f4 Bg7 14.dxe6 Bxe6= { is fully equal. There's no need to be afraid of }15.Rxb7 { as after }15...Qa5 { Black will get the pawn back, for example }16.e5 Rab8 17.Rxb8 Rxb8 18.O-O Bxa2 19.Be3 Be6 20.Bf3 f6 { and a draw was agreed in ½-½ }{ (20) }{ Degerhammar,R }{ (2500) }{ -Cerrato, R }{ (2470) }{ ICCF email 2015. } ) )
12. e6{ Black must undermine the  d5  pawn at once! }( 12...f5 13.f4 Bc7 14.e5+- { would be disastrous for Black. } )
13. f4{ The point behind  Qd2 , White gains space and drives back the  e5  bishop. }( 13.O-O exd5 14.exd5 Qd6= { leads to a better version of the mainline for Black as the bishop was allowed to stay on  e5 . } )( 13.c4 { or }13.Bc4 { are no good on account of }13...Qh4!  )
{ Black now has to decide where to place the dark-squared bishop. }13. Bc7{ A consequence of heading to the queenside with the bishop is that  f4 - f5  to go after Black's king becomes an idea in many lines. No need to panic though, White's 'attack' is far from dangerous! The text has the advantage of ruling out  c3 - c4  which would now blunder the queen to ... Ba5 . }( { In case of }13...Bg7 { , White will try to lock the bishop out of the game with  c3 - c4  and  e4 - e5 . This variation is fully playable and may be added in a future update to the course (let me know in the comments section if you'd like that!) } )
14. O-O{ White tucks the king away and is threatening  c2 - c4  (now that ... Ba5  is no longer a threat). The text is over 10x more popular than the alternatives below: }( {  (a)  }14.Bc4 { is met by }14...a6 { with the idea ... b5 . Remarkably, after }15.a4 { Black plays }15...b5! { anyhow! Following }16.axb5 axb5 17.Bxb5 exd5 18.Bc6 Ra6 19.Bxd5 Rd6 20.O-O Bf5! { with dynamic play in the correspondence game ½-½ (33) Gunkel,W (2353)-Boles,R (2102) ICCF email 2015. } )( {  (b)  }14.dxe6 Bxe6 15.Rxb7 Bb6 { comes with the threat of ... Qc8 , trapping the rook. This forces }16.Qxd8 Rfxd8 17.O-O c4+ 18.Kh1 Re8! { as seen in the correspondence game Baciak,M }{ (2179) }{ -Sindelar,F }{ (1833) }{ ICCF email 2017. Black's last move, lining up the rook against the  e4  pawn and  e2  bishop, is quite clever. It comes with the immediate threat of ... Bc8  when I'd already take Black. } )
14. exd5
15. exd5
15. Ba5{ The bishop may look offside at first sight but stands rather well on  a5 , pressuring the  c3  pawn and, importantly, preventing  c3 - c4 . }
16. d6{ Pushing the pawn forward is White's most ambitious continuation. While the  d6  pawn is strong and restricts Black's pieces, it can also become a target on top of the already weak  a2  and  c3  pawns. }
16. Rb8{ Black protects the  b7  pawn in order to develop the light-squared bishop. The text is stronger than ... b6 , which restricts the dark-squared bishop and leaves Black's rook exposed on  a8 . Not only that, by playing ... Rb8 , Black can play ... b5  in certain variations. }
17. Ba3
17. Bf5{ The bishop comes out to  f5  with tempo. }
18. Rbd1( 18.Rb5 { is answered with }18...a6! 19.Rxc5 Bb6 { which picks up the exchange. The onus is on White to maintain the balance. } )
18. Qf6{ is the simplest solution. This move, first played by Ftacnik versus Mikhalevski way back in 2006, forces a lot of material off the board leaving White with no hopes for an advantage. }( 18...Rc8!? { has been played by several top players, but I see no need to enter the complications after }19.g4! Bd7 20.f5∞  )
19. Bxc5( 19.Rf3 b6 20.Bb2 Rbe8 { with ... Re4  coming favors Black. } )
19. Bxc3
20. Qd5{ keeps more material on the board but is nothing to lose sleep over. }
20. b6
21. Ba3( 21.Bd4 Bxd4+ 22.Qxd4 Qxd4+ 23.Rxd4 b5= { was totally fine for Black in both the original Ftacnik game ½-½  (34) Mikhalevski,V (2571)-Ftacnik,L  (2579) Bellevue 2006 and the more recent correspondence game ½-½ (24) Palladino,M (2304) -Kogelov,G (2260) ICCF email 2021. } )
21. Be6
22. Qf3
22. Bd7{ firmly blocks the d-pawn. Black had no problems in the game ½-½ (27) Osorio Barahona,J (2402)-Haugen,A (2405) ICCF email 2021. Black would love to get in ... Bd4+  and ... Rfe8 - e3 . }( { Note that }23.f5 { is well met by }23...gxf5 { when White can restore material equality but no more. For example, }24.Bd3 Rfd8 25.Bxf5 { leads to a completely level endgame after }Bd4+ 26.Kh1 Bxf5 27.Qxf5 Qxf5 28.Rxf5 Bc5 29.Bxc5 bxc5 30.Rxc5 Rxd6! { with full equality. The rook is immune to capture as }31.Rxd6?? Rb1 32.Rd1 Rxd1 { is checkmate! } )( { (Black should naturally avoid   }23...Bxf5?? 24.g4+- { .) } )
