10. Nd7{ I've found this move to offer Black the best balance between objectivity and practicality. After careful analysis, I concluded that Black is objectively fine everywhere, does not need to remember hundreds of lines, and still has good chances of playing for an advantage should White go wrong. What more can one ask for with the Black pieces?     From  d7 , the knight is not exposed to  d4 - d5 , supports the ... e5  break and can head to  f6  to pressure the  e4  pawn. }{    Let me briefly discuss Black's alternatives: }( {  (a)  }10...Bg4 11.d5 b5 { is a sharp and trendy line but one that requires learning tons of theory. If you'd like to explore this option, check out Svidler's Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable whose analysis of this position stretches all the way past move 40! } )( {  (b)  }10...Rd8 { is very popular and certainly playable but I never found full equality for Black after }11.d5 e6 12.Bg5 f6 13.Be3 Nc6 14.h4⩲ { or }14.Bd3⩲  )( {  (c)  }10...Nc6 { would play right into White's hands. With the  c3  pawn firmly defended, White can simply push forward with }11.d5 { . After }11...Ne5 12.Nxe5 Bxe5 13.h4+- { Black has zero pressure on White's center and is about to be the subject of a vicious kingside attack. } )
