13. e6{ A thematic follow-up to ... Rd8 , immediately undermining White's center. }( 13...c4 { as recommended by Kovalchuk in  Playing the Grünfeld  is also playable. However, I wasn't a huge fan of Black's position in the following relatively forced continuation: }14.Bb1 e6 15.O-O exd5 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.e5 Ne4 18.Qf4 Nc5 { Kovalchuk only considers the immediate 18.  Ng5  but I found }19.h4→ { with ideas of  Qf6 + and  h5  to be far more dangerous. } )
14. O-O{ Alternatives, which have yet to be played at the time I'm writing this, are given below as clickable lines: }( {  (a)  }14.c4Ν { heading for an endgame is certainly not what White was envisioning when he played 11.  Bh6 . }14...Qxd2+ 15.Bxd2 exd5 16.cxd5 Nxe4! { is a nice tactical solution, exploiting the fact that White's king is still on  e1 . After }17.Bxe4 Re8= { Black will regain the sacrificed piece and easily complete development with ... Bf5 . } )( {  (a1)  Note that   }16.exd5 { runs into }16...b5⇆  )( {  (b1)  }14.Bxg7Ν { has yet to be played. }14...Kxg7 15.O-O exd5 16.e5 Nh5 17.Qg5 Rf8 { intending to meet  g4  with ... f6  is fine for Black. The engine's top line leads to a perpetual after }18.g4 f6 19.exf6+ Nxf6 20.Ne5 Qd8 { Black is threatening ... Nxg4  so White has to bail out with }21.Nxg6 hxg6 22.Qxg6+ Kh8 23.Qh6+ Kg8 24.Qg6+ Kh8=  )( {  (b2)  The endgame after   }15.c4 { is once again harmless. After }15...Qxd2+ 16.Kxd2 { Black has the powerful Benko-like strike 16... b5 ! }16...b5! { with good counterplay. Two sample continuations are: }( {  (b21)  }17.cxb5 a6 18.b6 exd5 19.e5 Nd7⩱ { Black will regain the b-pawn and end up with two powerful connected passed-pawns in the center of the board. } )( {  (b22)  }17.e5 { is a better move. White is hoping to get a protected passed pawn on  d6 , but we won't allow it. }17...Ng4 18.d6 Bb7 { Black immediately targets the  f3  knight, which is currently the sole defender of the  e5  pawn. In case of }19.Rhe1 { then }19...f6! { tears down White's central construction. } ) )
14. exd5{ is an OTB novelty but I won't pretend to have come up with it on my own :) This move has featured in several strong engine vs engine matches. }
15. e5
15. Nh5
16. h3
16. Bh8{ Black avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with a complex (and objectively balanced) game ahead. Black can look to target the  e5  pawn with ... Re8  and ... Qc7  next. In case of  g2 - g4 , the  h5  knight can find its way back into the game with ... Ng7 - e6 . }
