8. Be3{ White reinforces the  d4  pawn and typically follows up with  Qd2  and/or  Rc1 , securing the  c3  pawn and thus enabling a quick  d4 - d5 . This setup has been played by a long list of top GMs. I'll single out Kramnik and Carlsen, who've racked up quite a score with this system. }
8. Qa5{ is an important move to remember, Black must put pressure on the  c3  pawn right away! }
9. Qd2{ Natural and, unsurprisingly, the mainline. White protects the  c3  pawn and is ready to follow-up with  Rc1 . }
9. O-O
10. Rc1
10. Nd7{ I've found this move to offer Black the best balance between objectivity and practicality. After careful analysis, I concluded that Black is objectively fine everywhere, does not need to remember hundreds of lines, and still has good chances of playing for an advantage should White go wrong. What more can one ask for with the Black pieces? From  d7 , the knight is not exposed to  d4 - d5 , supports the ... e5  break and can head to  f6  to pressure the  e4  pawn. IM Andras Toth failed to consider this option in the Chessable course  The Beginner's 1.  d4  Repertoire . }
11. d5{ In direct contrast to attacking on the kingside with 11.  Bh6 , White focuses on making headway in the center with  d4 - d5  intending to quickly reinforce the center with  c3 - c4 . }
11. Nf6{ As usual, we attack  e4  at the earliest opportunity. }
12. c4( 12.Bd3 { is strongly met by }12...c4! { with the point that after }13.Bb1 e6 { White is unable to reinforce the d-pawn with  c3 - c4 . Note that }13.Bxc4? { blunders }13...Nxe4 { . } )( 12.e5 Nd7 13.Bh6 { cannot be recommended. After }13...Nxe5 14.Nxe5 Bxe5 15.Bxf8 Kxf8 { Black's two bishops proved too strong in the games 0-1 }{ (36) }{ Sarkar,J }{ (2428) }{ -Gledura,B }{ (2589) }{ Caleta 2017 and 0-1 }{ (38) }{ Bellaiche,A }{ (2485) }{ -Narayanan,S }{ (2573) }{ Moscow 2018. Better is }{   }13.Bf4 Qc7 14.e6 { , which featured in the correspondence game ½-½ }{ (20) }{ Susla,V }{ (2291) }{ -Khanas,V }{ (2340) }{ LSS email 2015. Play continued }14...Ne5 15.exf7+ Rxf7 16.Bxe5 Bxe5 17.Nxe5 Qxe5+ 18.Be2 e6 19.d6 Bd7 20.O-O Rd8= { when a draw was agreed. Black could have certainly played on. } )
12. Qxd2+
13. Nxd2
13. b6{ Some may call this an endgame, but I believe the term queenless middlegame is more precise here as there's still plenty of life in this position! Over the coming moves, Black will look to undermine White's center with moves like ... e6 , ... Ng4/Nd7 , and ... f5 . }
14. h3{ is one way to prevent ... Ng4 . }( 14.Be2 { fails to stop }14...Ng4 15.Bg5 f6 16.Bh4 { featured in the game ½-½ (19) Byrne,M (2276)-Shulman,B (2433) ICCF email 2018. Here I like the novel }16...g5Ν 17.Bg3 f5! { with excellent play.      Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. } )
