8. Be3{ White reinforces the  d4  pawn and typically follows up with  Qd2  and/or  Rc1 , securing the  c3  pawn and thus enabling a quick  d4 - d5 . This setup has been played by a long list of top GMs. I'll single out Kramnik and Carlsen, who've racked up quite a score with this system. }
8. Qa5{ is an important move to remember, Black must put pressure on the  c3  pawn right away! }
9. Qd2{ Natural and, unsurprisingly, the mainline. White protects the  c3  pawn and is ready to follow-up with  Rc1 . }
9. O-O
10. Rc1
10. Nd7{ I've found this move to offer Black the best balance between objectivity and practicality. After careful analysis, I concluded that Black is objectively fine everywhere, does not need to remember hundreds of lines, and still has good chances of playing for an advantage should White go wrong. What more can one ask for with the Black pieces?     From  d7 , the knight is not exposed to  d4 - d5 , supports the ... e5  break and can head to  f6  to pressure the  e4  pawn. IM Andras Toth failed to consider this option in the Chessable course  The Beginner's 1.  d4  Repertoire . White has a large array of options at this junction. }
