7. Qa4+{ is a move I've recommended a couple of times to White players looking to avoid big theoretical debates in the Grünfeld mainlines. The idea behind this move is to induce ... Bd7  or ... Nd7  in the hopes of proving these pieces are suboptimally placed. Moreover, White can often look to hinder Black's typical play based around the ... c5  break by dropping the queen back to  a3  or  b4 . }
7. Nd7{ is my preferred option. Black blocks the check and, in some lines, the knight can pop out to  b6  with a tempo on White's queen. After all, this is one of the main drawbacks of bringing out the queen so early! }( 7...Qd7 { is a reliable alternative but giving White the option of heading straight into an endgame is not in the spirit of the repertoire I'm proposing. } )
8. Nf3( 8.Be3 { intending a quick  Rd1  is answered by }8...c5 9.Rd1 O-O 10.Bd3 Nb6! { Black should first play ... Nb6  before taking on  d4  so as not to allow White to post the queen up on  b4 . }11.Qa3 cxd4 12.cxd4 Qd6 { A timely queen sortie with the point that after }13.Qxd6 exd6 { Black has a very comfortable endgame with the ideas of ... Re8  and ... d5 . } )( 8.Qa3 O-O 9.Nf3 { transposes. } )
8. O-O{ Black will look to break in the center with ... c5  or kick back White's queen with ... Nb6  depending on how the first player proceeds. }
9. Bg5{ White hopes to provoke ...  h6  and then return the bishop to  e3 , when Black will have to always worry about keeping the h-pawn protected. }( 9.Qa3 { is rarely played. It has the advantage of stepping out of ... Nb6 , but spending yet another tempo moving the queen is not the way to play for an edge. }9...c5 10.Be2 b6= { Black protects  c5  and will play ... Bb7  next with a good game. } )( {   }10.h4 { was seen in a couple of games. The simplest is }cxd4 11.cxd4 Nb6Ν { putting pressure on the  d4  pawn. Best play by both sides continues }12.Bg5 Qd6 13.Bxe7 Qxa3 14.Bxa3 Rd8 { when there's no saving the  d4  pawn, for example }15.Be2 Bg4 16.Rb1 Bxf3 17.gxf3 Bxd4= { gives Black good play. } )
9. c5{ We can simply ignore the  g5  bishop as it's not really doing much. The typical ... c5  break is far more useful than ... h6 ! }
10. Rc1( 10.Rd1 { lines up the rook against the  d8  queen but we can simply step out of the d-file with }10...Qc7 { likely followed by ... a6  and ... b5  with a good game. } )( 10.Qa3 Nf6! 11.e5 Ne4 { gives Black a very easy game. } )
10. a6( { Black prepares }11.-- b5! { with the tactical point that }12.Bxb5 { fails to }12...Nb6 { . Once ... b5  is in, the light-squared bishop can come out to  b7  and the queen will be developed to  c7  with a harmonious setup. }( 11.Qa3 { is well met by }11...Qc7 12.Be2 b5! { is possible even with White's queen on }a3 { . The point is that after }13.Bxb5 axb5 14.Qxa8 Bb7 15.Qa3 h6! 16.Bxe7 Ra8 17.Qb2 Re8! { Black succeeded in driving White's queen back and now returns to  e8  to pick up the  e4  pawn with excellent compensation. } )( { The simple   }11...b6 { preparing ... Bb7  is also fully playable. For example, }12.Bd3 Bb7 13.O-O b5 14.Qb2 Qc7= { was very comfortable for Black in the correspondence game ½-½ }{ (44) }{ Laurenc,P }{ (2415) }{ -Siefring,C }{ (2519) }{ ICCF email 2014. } ) )
