7. Bb5+{ Just like in the 7.  Qa4 + variation, White hopes to provoke ... Bd7  or ... Nd7  in an attempt to hinder the ... c5  break. We're not going to be so cooperative in this case! }
7. c6{ This move makes less sense against 7.  Qa4  (as Black will then have to spend another tempo going ... c5 ), but is certainly logical versus  7.  Bb5 +  given it knocks back the bishop with tempo! }
8. Ba4
8. O-O{ A clever move order, Black holds back ... b5  until White has committed the knight to  e2 . Should White go  Nf3 , then Black can shift gears with ... Bg4  }
9. Ne2( 9.Nf3 { is 20 times less common than placing the knight on  e2 . }9...Bg4 { We're going straight after White's  d4 -pawn with ... Bg4  and ... c5  on the next turn. }10.O-O c5 11.Be3 Nc6 { is very similar to this  line in the 7.  Nf3  8.  Bb5  chapter, in fact should White play }12.Bxc6 bxc6 13.Rc1 Qa5= { we get a direct transposition. } )
9. b5{ Black should seize the opportunity to expand on the queenside with tempo. White may have succeeded in initially delaying ... c5 , but not for long! }
10. Bb3( 10.Bc2 { is way too passive. The immediate 10... c5  or the novel }10...b4Ν 11.cxb4 a5 { with the idea }12.bxa5?! c5∓ { successfully eliminates White's center. Black can up the pressure on the  d4  pawn with ...  Nc6  next and will recoup the sacrificed material in no time. } )
10. Bb7{ Black is ready to play ... c5  on the next turn! The fianchettoed bishops will then cut straight across the entire board. }( 10...a5!? { is another reliable option. } )
11. O-O
11. c5
12. d5( 12.f3 { does not alter Black's plan of expanding on the queenside with }12...a5 { intending ... b4 . } )
12. a5{ White blunted the  b7  bishop with  d5  albeit only temporarily. It'll come to life after ... Ba6  and ... b4  while the  b8  knight will pop out to  d7 . The eval bar is already tipping in Black's favor! }( 10...Nd7 { followed by ... Nb6  also fine gave Black good play in the game ½-½ }{ (30) }{ Dorfman,J }{ (2583) }{ -Edouard,R }{ (2620) }{ Belfort 2010. } )
