7. Bg5{ I've never thought too much of this early dark-squared bishop sortie. Nevertheless, Mamedyarov has won many blitz games with White in this line so it certainly warrants some attention. With  Bg5 , White clears the way for  Rc1  and hinders ... Qa5  due to the pressure on  e7 . However, this move fails to reinforce White's center which will be targeted with ... c5 . }
7. c5( 7...h6 { is to be avoided as after }8.Be3 { White gets an improved version of the mainline  Be3  systems due to the weakness on  h6 . } )
8. Rc1( { is the only way to deal with the pressure on  d4 . Black can't take everything on  d4  as the  c8  bishop will hang at the end of all the trades: }8...cxd4 9.cxd4 Bxd4?? 10.Rxc8! { wins White material. The two bishops are far stronger than the rook. } )( 8.Nf3?! Bg4 { is very unpleasant. } )( 8.d5?? { blunders }8...Bxc3+-+ { . } )
8. O-O{ Black castles and indirectly defends the  c8  bishop, renewing the threat of ...  cxd4 . }( 8...Qa5 { is also playable, but I find White's bishop stands well on  g5  after the sample continuation }9.Qd2 O-O 10.Nf3 cxd4 11.cxd4 Qxd2+ 12.Kxd2 { Here, the bishop on  g5  is well-placed to put pressure on  e7  and hinder ... Rd8 . I see no need to bring the queen out to  a5  so early, which leaves  e7  vulnerable and makes 7.  Bg5  a much more sensible move than it should be! } )
9. Nf3( 9.d5 { Having played  Rc1 , White can now push the d-pawn. }9...Qd6 { I really like this move, firmly blocking the d-pawn ahead of breaking with ... e6 . This move also carries the immediate threat of ... Qe5  and let's not forget about the typical ... f5  break as well! }10.Nf3 Bg4 { transposes to the text. } )( { (   }10.Be2 e6! { followed by ...  exd5  and ... Bf5  is 'no problemo' for Black. }{ ) } )
9. Bg4{ is our standard reaction to  Nf3 . Black pins the knight and puts more pressure on the  d4  pawn, forcing White to advance it. }
10. d5
10. Qd6{ Black brings the queen out, which enables ... e6  by stepping out the pin along the  h4 - d8  diagonal. ... Nd7  is also on the agenda. }
11. Be2
11. Bxf3
12. Bxf3
12. b5{ was the point behind ...  Bxf3 . Black discourages  c4  and is ready to play it himself, creating a fantastic outpost for the  b8  knight on  c5 . }( {  (a)  }13.c4 bxc4 14.Rxc4 Nd7 { gives Black full control over the dark squares. White had to reckon with moves like  ... Nb6 /e5  and ... Bd4  in the correspondence game ½-½ }{ (25) }{ Elias,H }{ (2308) }{ -Koelewijn,A }{ (2320) }{ ICCF email 2018. } )( {  (b)  }13.O-O { is a better move. }13...c4 14.Be2 { clears the way for  f2 - f4  and  e4 - e5 . Black can respond with }14...Nd7 15.f4 f6! { which rules out  e5  altogether. Next up is ... Nc5  with fantastic play. } )( { (  }14.a4 a6 15.Rb1 Bxc3 16.axb5 axb5 17.Rxb5 Be5 { left Black with a passed c-pawn and the better chances in the correspondence game Garau,B }{ (2154) }{ -Damarez,P }{ (1834) }{ ICCF email 2013.) } )
