12. bxc6{ We've reached what practice has shown to be a balanced endgame. Black's two bishops offer enough compensation for the weak c-pawn. The  c8  bishop will pop out to  e6 , pressuring the  a2  pawn, and can later be anchored on  d5 , from where it attacks the  g2  pawn and covers  c6 .    Here are a couple of sample lines: }( {  (a)  First and foremost, one should note that }13.Rxc6?? { blunders }13...Bb7 14.Rc1 Bxg2-+ { . } )( {  (b)  }13.Nf3 Be6 14.a3 Bd5= { anchors the bishop and bolsters the  c6  pawn with a completely fine game. } )( {  (c)  Similarly }13.Ne2 a5 14.O-O Be6 { solves all of Black's problems. The  a2  pawn is hanging and if White defends it with }15.a3 { then }15...Bd5= { once again more than adequately defends  c6 . } )( {  (d)  }13.h4 { with the idea  h5  to target the bishop on  h6  is an interesting try by the strong English GM and renowned commentator David Howell. }13...Be6 14.h5 g5! 15.Ne2 Bxa2 16.Rxc6 Be6= { and Black had no problems in 1-0 }{ (86) }{ Howell,D }{ (2646) }{ -Grandelius,N }{ (2672) }{ London 2022. } )( {  (e)  Note that }15.a3 { would once again be met with }15...Bd5 { when }16.f3 { hoping to get  e4  in and kick the bishop from its porch on  d5  can be easily stopped with }16...f5= { . } )
