5. c5{ This enterprising move was brought into the limelight by Russian GM Mikhail Antipov in 2019. It would take two years for the world's elite to take notice, with notable names like Dubov, Giri, Firouzja, and Carlsen essaying throughout 2021. I only expect it to grow in popularity over the coming years and perhaps one day even overtake 5... Bg7  and 5... Nb6 , it's that good! }
6. e4{ is White's most popular continuation. After all, one of the main ideas behind 5.Bd2 is to follow-up with  e4 . }
6. Nxc3
7. Bxc3
7. cxd4
8. Bxd4{ is the only serious try for an advantage. White is hoping to provoke ...  f6  which would dramatically weaken Black's kingside. }
8. e5{ Thankfully, there's no need for ... f6 . This strong central counter solves all of Black's problems. }
9. Bc3{ is another other option. White drops the bishop back, preventing ... Bb4+ , and hopes to bag the  e5  pawn under better conditions. }( 9.Bb5 Bd7 10.Bxd7 Nxd7= { is completely harmless. } )
9. Qxd1+
10. Rxd1
10. Nc6
11. Bb5
11. Bd7{ Black has little to worry about in this endgame. If White takes on  c6 , Black will end up regaining the  e4  pawn. Otherwise, ... f6  is coming on the next turn when Black will most likely complete development with ... Be7  and ... O-O-O . }( {  (a)  }12.Bxc6?! Bxc6 13.Bxe5 Bb4+ 14.Bc3 Bxc3+ 15.bxc3 Bxe4⩱ { is better for Black. White's queenside structure is compromised and the bishop is far stronger than the  g1  knight. } )( {  (b)  Best play by both sides continues }12.f4 f6 13.Nf3 Be7 { not worrying about }14.Bxc6 Bxc6 { as after }15.fxe5 O-O 16.exf6 Bxf6 17.e5 Rae8 { the  e5  pawn will soon drop. For example }18.O-O Bxf3 19.Rxf3 Bxe5 20.Bxe5 Rxe5 21.Rd7 Rxf3 22.gxf3 Rb5= { with a dead equal endgame. } )( {   }14.g3 { as seen in ½-½  (37) Erigaisi,A (2626)-Puranik,A (2568) Plovdiv 2021 is well met by }14...O-O-O = { . } )
