{ This chapter is primarily dedicated to }5. Na4{ The  Nadanian  variation, named after the Armenian IM Ashot Nadanian who first played in 1996.   Nadanian 'should be congratulated for seeing what everyone has seen, and thinking what nobody had thought' - Jonathan Rowson  White voluntarily moves the knight to the edge of the board in order to prevent ...  Nxc3  and hinder the ... c5  break. The first player is planning  e4  next to kick back the  d5  knight. }( { We then consider a close cousin to Nadanian's  5.Na4  variation, namely  }4.Nf3 Bg7 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Na4 { played in 300+ OTB games. }( 6.Qb3 { and }6.Qa4+ { are both shown to be completely harmless in this chapter. } ) )( { Finally }5.g3 { is also addressed. } )
