5. e5{ is the most dynamic response. Black sacrifices a pawn to open up the game, which is very logical when you consider that White has moved the same minor piece twice. }( 5...Bf5?! { fails to prevent  e2 - e4  on account of }6.f3!  )( 5...Bg7 { and }5...Nf6 { are two other good options. } )
6. dxe5( 6.e4 { is seldom seen and for good reason. }6...Nb6 7.Nxb6 axb6 { Black's rook on  a8  couldn't be happier with this exchange! }8.d5 { This position was reached in the games 1-0 (56) Lysyj,I (2576)-Sasikiran,K (2700) Moscow 2007 and 1-0 (58) Xiong,J (2684)-Yashmetov,M  (2305) Chess.com INT 2019. Here I like the novel }8...Qh4↑ { attacking the  e4  pawn and intending ... Bc5  to target the  f2  pawn. }8...f5 9.Bd3 fxe4 10.Bxe4 Bb4 11.Bd2 Qh4 { is another excellent option. } )( { (   }7.Be3 Bb4+ 8.Nc3 exd4 9.Qxd4 Qxd4 10.Bxd4 O-O { followed by ... Nc6  offers Black a good game. }{ ) } ){  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. }
6. Nc6{ A logical move, Black develops the knight and targets the  e5  pawn. }
7. f4{ White tries to preserve the extra pawn at all costs. Note that White hasn't developed a single piece apart from the knight on  a4 , which is doing absolutely nothing! Unsurprisingly, Black can already take over the initiative. }
7. Bf5{ Black is now threatening a deadly knight incursion with ... Ncb4 . }
8. a3
8. g5{ A strong move, immediately undermining White's central construction. }
9. e3
9. gxf4
10. exf4
10. Qd7{ clears the way for ... O-O-O , which Black will likely follow up with ... Qe8 . We're way past compensation here, the only question is how big Black's advantage is. }
