3. d5{ This chapter is devoted to }
4. Bg5{ White develops the bishop with the rather obvious threat of picking up the  d5  pawn after  Bxf6 . }( 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bg5 { is covered via the 4.  Bg5   Bg7  5.  Nf3  move order. } )
4. Bg7{ Turns out Black can simply ignore White's plan and instead prioritize development. The main point is that the  d4  pawn will come under heavy hire should White grab the  d5  pawn. }( 4....Ne4 { is Black's most popular move and requires learning far more theory. The text is more practical and gives Black more chances of playing for the full point. } )
5. Bxf6{ Taking the knight followed by  cxd5  is certainly the critical test. This move featured in 1000+ OTB games. }( {  (a)  }5.Nf3 Ne4 { Black lunges into the center taking advantage of the fact that  Nxe4  loses material. White must now decide where to place the bishop or whether to let Black exchange it off. Here, we will mainly focus our attention on: } )( {  (a1)    }6.cxd5 { seen in 6000+ OTB games. }( {  (a2)    }6.Bh4 { played in 2000+ games. } )( {  (a3)    }6.Bf4 { essayed in 1500+ games. } )( {  (a4)    Note that }6.Nxe4? { drops the  d4  pawn after }6...dxe4-+  ) )( {  (b)  }5.e3 { is rare and answered by }5...c5! { intending to meet }6.Nf3 { with }6...cxd4 { . Note that }6.dxc5 { is strongly answered by }6...Ne4! 7.Nxe4 dxe4 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.O-O-O+ Ke8 10.Ne2 Bd7= { After ... Na6xc5 , Black will emerge with the superior pawn structure. } )
