13. Qxa5{ This is White's by far most common and best continuation, keeping the king in the center. }( 13.O-O { is inaccurate. White's king would much rather be in the center in the upcoming endgame. Not only that, but after }13...Qxd2 14.Nxd2 { White has lost control over the  e5  square, thus allowing }14...e5! { which opens up the  g7  bishop and gives Black a very comfortable endgame. The 2 vs 1 on the queenside is a long term trump. } )
13. Nxa5
14. Bd3{ White improves the position of the bishop and vacates the  e2  square to connect the rooks with  Ke2 . }
14. Be6{ The bishop is perfectly placed on  e6 . It aims at the weak pawn on  a2  and increases Black's control over the key  c4  square. ... Rfc8  to take control over the c-file is coming next. }
15. Ke2
15. Rfc8{ All of Black's pieces are well placed. Black can now look to expand on the kingside with ... h6 +... g5 , knocking back White's bishop and threatening ... g4  in certain lines. Long term, the second player can look to make use of the 2 vs 1 queenside majority. }( { A sample line runs }16.Rhc1 h6Ν { improving over the game 1-0 (40) Thybo,J (2590) -Antipov,M (2615) Warsaw 2021 where Black played 16... a6 . This novel move was  not  considered by Egor Lashkin in the modern-chess.com database  Challenge the Gruenfeld with Bg5 . Black is now threatening ... g5  and if }17.h4 { then }17...Rxc1 18.Rxc1 Bxa2 { gives Black a passer on the queenside. }19.Rc7 Nc6 20.Rxb7 a5= { sets the a-pawn in motion. I'd definitely take Black here even if the position is objectively balanced. } )
