[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bg5{ White develops the bishop and threatens to win the  d5  pawn with  Bxf6 . }
4. Bg7{ Turns out Black can simply ignore White's plan and instead prioritize development. The main point is that the  d4  will come under heavy hire should White grab the  d5  pawn. }
5. Nf3( { This position can also arise via the   }4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bg5 { move order. } )
5. Ne4{ Black lunges into the center taking advantage of the fact that  Nxe4  loses material. White must now decide where to place the bishop or whether to let Black exchange it off. }
6. cxd5{ is two times more popular than retreating the  g5  bishop. White heads for a Carlsbad structure and hopes to claim the  g7  bishop will be misplaced. However, this comes at the price of handing Black the bishop pair. }
6. Nxg5
7. Nxg5
7. e6{ with a double attack on the  g5  knight and the  d5  pawn ensures Black will restore material equality. }
8. Nf3
8. exd5
9. e3
9. O-O{ is a position that resembles the exchange variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. In these Carlsbad like structures, Black's bishop is usually best placed on  d6  from where it eyes both sides of the board. As such, Black's bishop on  g7  is slightly misplaced. To compensate, Black has the bishop pair which can become a strong asset should the position open up. }
10. Be2( 10.b4 { immediately starting a minority attack has also been seen. }10...c6 11.Be2 Be6 12.O-O Nd7= { Black has a sound position and is likely to follow up with ... Re8  and ...  Bf8 - d6 . Another idea is ... a5 , intending to meet  b5  with ... c5 . Also look out for an opportune ... b5  followed by ...  Nd7 - b6 - c4 .      Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the upcoming  alternative trainable variation. } )
10. c6{ We're not going for ... c5  in this structure as Black's d-pawn would become very vulnerable after  dxc5 . }
11. O-O
11. a5{ makes it harder for White to start the typical minority attack with  b4 - b5 . }
12. a3
12. Re8{ is the typical square for the  f8  rook, taking control over the half-open e-file. This move also clears the way for ...  Bf8 - d6  to reroute the bishop to its ideal post in this structure. }
13. b4{ is premature on account of 13... b5  - a typical motif in this structure! }
13. b5{ Black stops the  b4  pawn in its tracks and clamps down on the  c4  square, which is an ideal outpost for the  c4  knight. Not only that, the  b4  pawn is now weak and can be targeted with ...  Qd6  and ... Bf8 . }
