10. f3( 10.Be2 Bxe2 11.Qxe2 Qxc5 12.Qxc4 Qxc4 13.Nxc4 Nc6 { and Black's the only one playing for an advantage here. The  e4  pawn is merely a target here. } )
10. Be6
11. Nxc4{ If White wants to capture the  c4  pawn, this is the way to do it. }
11. Qxc5
12. Be3
12. Qc8
13. Na5
13. Nc6{ Black completes development and plugs the c-file, neutralizing any x-rays by the rook on  c1 . }( { A sample line goes }14.Nxc6 Qxc6 15.Nb5 Qd7 16.Nc7 Rac8 17.Qxd7 Nxd7 18.Nxe6 fxe6= { Despite the doubled e-pawns, Black has little to fear here. White is far behind in development and will have to give up control over the c-file. } )
