4. Bf4{ is one of the most solid variations in the Grünfeld. White develops the bishop outside the pawn chain before bolstering the  d4  pawn with  e2 - e3 . The bishop is also well placed on  f4 , fighting for the critical  e5  square and keeping tabs on the  c7  pawn. }
4. Bg7
5. e3{ is White's most flexible move.  e3  is surely part of White's setup while it's not clear whether the  g1  knight belongs on  f3  or  e2 . }
5. O-O( 5...c5 { is a good alternative. I am, however, not too fond of the positions arising after }6.dxc5 Qa5 7.Rc1 dxc4 8.Bxc4 O-O 9.Nge2 { The symmetric nature of this position means that, even if objectively fine, Black's winning chances are very limited. White is essentially playing for two results in the vast majority of these lines. } )
6. Rc1{ is the mainline and a very logical move. White anticipates the long diagonal is likely to open up and pre-emptively reinforces the  c3  knight. The rook on  c1  simultaneously discourages the ... c5  break and indirectly aims at the  c7  pawn. }
6. Be6{ exploits the main drawback of holding back the  g1  knight, that is  Nf3 - g5  is not in the position. The pressure on the  c4  pawn forces White to clarify the central tension. }( 6...c5 { and }6...c6 { are more popular and involve learning way more theory, which I found unnecessary. } )
7. Qb3{ attempts to exploit the drawback of ... Be6 , namely the undefended  b7  pawn. The downside of this move is that White's kingside is still undeveloped. }( 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Nxd5 Qxd5= { is toothless. The  c7  pawn is hanging but so is White's queenside! } )
7. c5{ Black ignores the  b7  pawn and goes for active play. White is more than welcome to take on  b7  and fall even further behind in development. }
8. Qxb7
8. Qb6{ forces White to waste even more time with the queen while Black continues developing. }
9. Qxb6( 9.Qxa8 Nc6 10.Qxf8+ Bxf8-+ { White doesn't stand a chance here with half of his forces undeveloped. } )
9. axb6{ brings the  a8  rook into the game. Black is almost fully mobilized while White's kingside pieces are still on their starting squares. Black will soon restore material equality as the following sample lines illustrate: }( {  (a)  Aiming to rapidly develop the kingside with }10.Nf3 { is sensible. }10...dxc4 11.dxc5 bxc5= { Black has restored material equality and is even threatening ...  Nd5 . It's up to White to maintain the balance in this position, Black's side is certainly easier to play! } )( {  (b1)  }10.dxc5 bxc5 11.a3 dxc4 12.Nd1 Ra4 13.Ne2 Nc6 14.Nec3 Ra7 15.Nb5 Rb7 16.Nc7 { was all seen in ½-½ (53) Batchuluun,T (2517)-Jumabayev,R (2548) Incheon 2013. In  Playing the Grünfeld , Kovalchuk correctly points out that }16...Bf5! 17.Na6 Nd7 18.Rxc4 Na5 19.Nxc5 Nxc4 20.Nxb7 Nxb2 21.Nxb2 Bc3+ 22.Kd1 Bxb2↑ { is very unpleasant for White. The king on  d1  is exposed, the  b7  knight is out of the game and the kingside is still not fully developed. } )( {  (b2)    }11.cxd5?! Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Bxd5 13.Rxc5 e6 { White's two pawns up but the entire queenside is about to fall. } )
