5. e3{ is White's most flexible move.  e3  is surely part of White's setup while it's not clear whether the  g1  knight belongs on  f3  or  e2 . }
5. O-O( 5...c5 { is a good alternative. I am, however, not too fond of the positions arising after }6.dxc5 Qa5 7.Rc1 dxc4 8.Bxc4 O-O 9.Nge2 { The symmetric nature of this position means that, even if objectively fine, Black's winning chances are very limited. White is essentially playing for two results in the vast majority of these lines. } )
6. Rc1{ is the mainline and a very logical move. White anticipates the long diagonal is likely to open up and pre-emptively reinforces the  c3  knight. The rook on  c1  simultaneously discourages the ... c5  break and indirectly aims at the  c7  pawn. }
6. Be6{ exploits the main drawback of holding back the  g1  knight, that is  Nf3 - g5  is not in the position. The pressure on the  c4  pawn forces White to clarify the central tension. }
7. c5{ This is arguably the most critical continuation. White gains space and makes the ... e6  bishop look slightly misplaced. }
7. Ne4{ is super rare and interesting. The idea is to swap a pair of knights and then prepare the ... e5  break now that the  g7  bishop is unobstructed. }( 7...c6 { has featured in 100s of top level games. White can ask a couple of questions and I wasn't completely satisfied with Black's chances, especially considering the large amount of theory to remember here. } )
8. Bd3
8. Nxc3
9. Rxc3( 9.bxc3 { is answered by }9...b6! { immediately undermining White's center. } )
9. Nc6{ is step one in our plan to break in the center with ... e5 . Next up is moving the  e6  bishop out of the way. }
10. h3( 10.Bg3 { has yet to be played but is quite clever. White pre-empts Black's ...  e5  break and intends to play  f2 - f4  and  Nf3  to clamp down on  e5 . }10...a5! { is a useful move in this structure, holding back White's queenside pawns. }11.h3 Bd7 12.f4 Qc8= { with ideas of ... Nb4  and/or ... Bf5  is fine for Black. We'll eventually get ... e5  in with the preparatory moves ... f6  and ... Re8 . } )
10. Bd7{ Black drops the bishop back to liberate the e-pawn. }
11. Nf3
11. Re8
12. O-O
12. e5{ The ... e5  break is in meaning Black can look to the future with confidence. }( { The only game in my database to reach this position continued }13.dxe5 Nxe5 14.Nxe5 Bxe5 15.Bxe5 Rxe5 16.Bc2 Qe7 17.Qd4 Re8 18.Rd1 c6 19.Ra3 { and a draw was agreed in the correspondence game ½-½ (19) Limbert,N (2341) -Ionita,M (2288) ICCF email 2017. Black could have certainly played on with }19...a6 { and then look to create play on the kingside with moves like ... h5  and ... Rg5 . } )
