4. e3{ is a tricky move order. White prioritizes kingside development and holds back the queenside knight. }( { White's intention is to meet the standard Grünfeld move }4...d5 { with }5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.e4! { taking advantage of the fact that there's no ... Nxc3  in the position. } )( 4.g3 d5 { transposes to the Fianchetto variation  chapter. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2
5. c5{ Heading for a Benoni structure is the way to go! }{ White may have rendered ... d5  ineffective but his setup is known to be innocuous against the Benoni. }( { The  key idea  behhind }5...c5 { is to execute the positional 'threat' of playing }6.-- cxd4 7.exd4 d5 { when Black has an excellent version of the reversed Tarrasch. With ... Nc6  and the strong bishop on  g7 , Black will readily gang up on the  d4  pawn. Furthermore, this pawn will become isolated and even more exposed along the d-file after a subsequent ... dxc4 . } )( { Note that }5...d5 { still runs into }6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.e4⩲ { . } )
