4. Bg7
{ In this chapter, we're focusing on the  Russian  variation that occurs after }5. Qb3{ first played by Ragozin against Romanovsky in Leningrad 1932. White brings the queen out early on to put pressure on the  d5  pawn and induce ... dxc4  intending to later take over the center with  e2 - e4 . }
5. dxc4
6. Qxc4
6. O-O
7. e4{ White successfully establishes the ideal central pawn duo  e4  and  d4  without compromising the queenside structure. The knights are ideally placed on  f3  and  c3  supporting the central pawns in true classical fashion. The first player is, however, behind in development and the queen on  c4  is a target, having come out into the game much earlier than normal. }
7. a6{ Black prepares ... b5  with tempo, immediately exploiting the exposed nature of White's queen. This continuation is aptly named the  Hungarian  variation in homage to the Hungarian players Barczay, Barcza and Ribli who all essayed 7...  a6  in the 1969 Hungarian national championship. It's now achieved mainline status in large part due to Kasparov, Svidler, Leko, Nepo and MVL.     Here, we'll focus predominantly on the following two mainlines: }( 8.e5 { played in 1500+ OTB games. } )( 8.Be2 { seen in 1700+ OTB games. } )
