1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Qb3
4. dxc4( { Black forces the queen forward and will bring out his pieces with tempi just like in the Russian system, namely   }4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Qb3 { . } )
5. Qxc4( { The main idea of White's move order, that is refraining from  4. Nf3  and opting to bring the queen to  b3  immediately, is to not commit the }g1 { knight immediately to  f3  in an attempt to get an improved version of the Russian system. For example, should Black go }5...Bg7 6.e4 O-O 7.Be2 { White gets a more flexible version of the Russian system mainline as the  g1  knight may not necessarily have to come out to  f3 , depending on how Black proceeds. }( { The downside of this move order though is that Black also gets extra options, specifically }5...Be6! { with a tempo on White's queen, often followed by a quick ... c5  break. } ) )
5. Be6
6. Qb5+
6. Bd7{ is a calm response. White is more than welcome to take on  b7  and fall critically behind in development. }
7. Qxb7
7. Nc6{ Black's moves play themselves: ... Nc6  comes with the threat of ... Nxd4  and clears the way for ... Rb8 ! }
8. e3
8. Rb8
9. Qa6
9. Nb4{ wins yet another tempo on the queen and threatens a deadly incursion on  c2 . }
10. Qe2
10. c5{ Black is two moves away from completing development while White only has 1 piece in the game and will have to spend another tempo moving the queen. Full compensation for the pawn is not even up for the discussion, the real question is how big Black's advantage is. }
