13. Nd7{ Black is fully developed and will pick up the  c5  pawn in short order as evidenced in the following sample continuations, which advanced/higher-rated players can opt to train in the next set of alternative  lines. }( 14.b4 { was the main idea behind  Rc1 . After }14...a5 { , I examined: } )( {  (a)    }15.a3?? Nxe3 16.fxe3 Bxc3+ 17.Rxc3 axb4 { is disastrous for White as }18.axb4 Ra1+-+ { skewers the  h1  rook. } )( {  (b)    }15.Bxb5 Nxe3 16.fxe3 axb4 17.Nd5 Bxd5 18.exd5 Nf6= { with threats of ... Nxd5 , ...  Rxa2  and ... Ra5  Black will soon restore material equality. } )( {  (c)    }15.Nxb5 { is arguably best. After }15...axb4 16.c6 { may seem dangerous but Black can just take it. The point is that after }16...Bxc6 17.Rxc6 Nde5 18.Nxe5 Nxe5= { the  d3  bishop will drop with check. } )
