1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. Qb3{ was first played by Ragozin against Romanovsky in Leningrad 1932 and has been coined the  Russian  variation. White brings the queen out early on to put pressure on the  d5  pawn and induce ... dxc4  intending to later take over the center with  e2 - e4 . }
5. dxc4
6. Qxc4
6. O-O
7. e4{ White successfully establishes the ideal central pawn duo  e4  and  d4  without compromising the queenside structure. The knights are ideally placed on  f3  and  c3  supporting the central pawns in true classical fashion. The first player is, however, behind in development and the queen on  c4  is exposed, having come out into the game much earlier than normal. }
7. a6{ Black prepares ... b5  with tempo, immediately exploiting the exposed nature of White's queen. This continuation is aptly named the Hungarian variation in homage to the Hungarian players Barczay, Barcza and Ribli who all essayed 7...  a6  in their 1969 national championship. It's now achieved mainline status in large part due to Kasparov, Svidler, Leko, Nepo and MVL. }
8. Be2{ If White could magically swap the position of his queen and bishop, he'd have a huge advantage. As it stands, the queen on  c4  is a big target and White simply doesn't have the time to shore up the center. }
8. b5{ Independently of whether White drops the queen to  d3  or  b3 , we will strike in the center with ... c5 . }
9. Qb3{ is far more testing than 9.  Qd3 . }
9. c5{ Just like after 9.  Qd3 , Black does best in immediately striking in the center with ... c5  before White has time to complete development. Sacrificing a pawn for dynamic play is the name of the game in the Grünfeld! }
10. dxc5( 10.e5? Be6! 11.Qd1 Nd5 { only helps Black activate the knight. } )
10. Be6{ This is the downside of tucking the queen back to  b3 , that is Black gets the bishop out with tempo. }
11. Qc2{ White's queen has been on quite the journey, namely  d1🡒b3🡒c4🡒b3🡒c2 . That's 5 queen moves in the space of just 11 total moves! }
11. Nbd7{ The knight comes out to  d7  to target the  c5  pawn. }
12. Be3{ A logical, multipurpose move: White develops the bishop and covers the  c5  pawn. }( 12.c6 Nb8= { followed by ... Nxc6  will pick up the c-pawn. } )( 12.b4 { is no good due to }12...a5! { when White's queenside will collapse. } )
12. Rc8
13. Rd1{ White pins the  d7  knight in one last attempt to hold onto the  c5  pawn. }( 13.c6 { with the idea }13...Rxc6 14.Nd4 { is simply met by }14...Rd6 { when White has simply wasted valuable tempi. } )( 13.b4? { fails tactically to }13...Nxe4! 14.Nd4 Ndxc5! { Boom goes the dynamite! The point is that }15.bxc5 Bxd4-+ { is completely winning for Black. } )
13. Qa5{ With 13... Qa5 , Black simply steps out of the pin and renews the threat of ... Nxc5 . The queen is also excellently placed on  a5 , from where it pins the  c3  knight and thus indirectly pressures the  e4  pawn. This is by far Black's most practical option at this junction. }( 13...b4 { is 20 times more popular, which necessarily entails learning way more theory and for little gain. Certainly not what we're going for! } )
14. a3{ intending  b4  is the most challenging continuation. Black cannot allow this and should push ahead with ... b4  himself. }
14. b4
15. axb4
15. Qxb4{ The  c5  pawn isn't long for this world and ...  Bb3  is a huge threat. Black is in great shape as several games have demonstrated.      Note:  the following clickable lines are also given as alternative  lines, which advanced/higher-rated players may wish to train: }( {  (a)  }16.Bxa6 Ra8 { Black is threatening ... Bb3  so there's no time to retreat the  a6  bishop. }17.Rd4 { is thus forced and after }17...Qb8 18.Bc4 Nxc5 { White is behind in development and already needs to watch out for threats like  ... Ra1 +  and  ... Ng4 xe3 . } )( {  (b)  }16.Nd4 Nxc5 17.O-O Ng4! { Once again, this knight sortie gives Black good counterplay. }18.Bxg4 Bxg4 19.f3 Be6! { is the right square for the bishop. Black must prevent  Nc3 - d5 . }20.Nd5 Bxd5 21.exd5 Bxd4! { is necessary as White was threatening  Nc6 . }22.Rxd4 Qb7 23.Qe2 { Sam Shankland stopped here in the Chessable course  Lifetime Repertoires: Sam Shankland's 1.  d4  - Part 2  and stated that  'At stupid high depths, Stockfish calls this position equal. I won't argue with it and I don't claim that I could beat it from here, but from a human point of view, Black's position looks very scary to me. I could easily see a disaster happening on the dark squares around his king, White doubling rooks on the c-file and landing a rook on  c6 , or both. Black should be very precise to maintain the balance.'  This is, however, a rather convenient point to stop when you're writing a White repertoire course. Black has an immediate equalizer in the form of }23...Nb3Ν { . A new move that improves over the games ½-½ (55) Abdusattorov,N (2627)-Vakhidov,J (2533) Tashkent 2021 and ½-½ (29) Shmeliov,D (2436)-Tiglon,B (2391) New York 2022. Black hits the  d4  rook and is ready to pressure the  d5  pawn with ... Rfd8 . }24.Rd3 Rfd8 25.Rfd1 Qb5= { Black has little to worry about as all of White's pieces are tied down to the defense of the  d5  pawn. }( {  (b1)  For example   }26.Bh6 { hoping to exploit the weak dark-squares around Black's king is strongly met by }26...Nd4! { Exclam! The knight is headed to  f5  courtesy of the pin along the  a6 - f1  diagonal. }27.Qxe7 Nf5 28.Qg5 { We've transposed into the game ½-½ (29) Shmeliov,D (2436)-Tiglon,B (2391) New York 2022 where Black played 28... Rd6  and agreed to a draw after 29.  Qd2 . However, Black is actually slightly better and could have played for a win with }28...Qxb2! { which grabs a pawn and threatens ... f6 . After }29.d6 f6 30.Qf4 Rc3 { White needs to be extremely accurate to stay in the game. Best play by both sides follows }31.Rxc3 Qxc3 32.h4 Nxh6 33.Qxh6 Rxd6! 34.Rxd6 Qe1+ 35.Kh2 Qe5+ 36.Kh1 Qxd6= { which White should be able to draw. Black is the only one having fun here though! This variation is a good illustration of how the position after 23... Nb3  is far from one sided. } ) )( {  (c1)  }16.c6 { intending to meet }16...Rxc6 { with }17.Nd4 { is the most challenging continuation, which occurred in several high-level correspondence games. }17...Rd6 18.Nxe6 Rxd1+ 19.Bxd1 fxe6 { At first sight, it may seem like White has the upper hand. The first player has the two bishops and has damaged Black's structure. However, the doubled e-pawns aren't all that bad, for example the  e6  pawn controls the key  d5  square. Moreover, Black is about to play ... Rb8  and target the weak  b2  pawn, which is far from easy to defend. }20.O-O Rb8 21.f4 { is well met by }21...e5! { as in ½-½ (41) Khanas,V (2392) -Morozov,D (2475) ICCF email 2019. } )( {  (c2)    }21.Bf4 Rb7 { and the bishop has back to  c1  to defend the  b2  pawn giving White has no hopes for an advantage. Black had no problems whatsoever in the correspondence game ½-½ (26) Bubir,A   (2531) -Sasikiran,K (2552) ICCF 2020. } )( {  (c3)    }21.b3 a5 22.Na4?! Nxe4! { and Black was already better, going on to win in 0-1 (47) Maghsoodloo,P (2701) -Paravyan,D (2617) Chess.com INT 2022. } )
