5. h4{ is an ambitious continuation, which Morozevich brought to top-level chess all the way back in 2012. A year later Grischuk essayed it against Magnus Carlsen in the 2013 London Candidates and it's remained popular ever since. }( { Compared to the  4.h4  variation, the presence of the knight on  f3  gives White more control over the center such that an early }5...c5? { break is nowhere near as effective. After }6.dxc5 Qa5 7.cxd5 Nxd5 { White can ignore the attack on  c3  and simply take on  d5  with }8.Qxd5 { since }8...Bxc3+ { can be met with }9.Bd2! { when }9...Bxd2+ 10.Qxd2 Qxd2+ 11.Nxd2⩲ { leaves White with an extra pawn. The first player went on to win in 1-0 (41) Fridman,D (2604)-Kantans,T (2443) Riga 2014 and 1-0 (52) Vitiugov,N (2742)-Belousov,D (2314) St Petersburg 2014. } )
5. dxc4{ is the most dynamic continuation. Black takes on  c4  and is ready to follow up with ... c5 . }( 5...c6 { is a solid alternative. After }6.cxd5 cxd5 { resembles more the exchange Slav with a somewhat unusual inclusion of ... g6  +  Bg7  and  h4 . This is certainly playable, but I'd wager that  h4  is more useful than fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop in this structure. Let's leave this boring line aside and instead for the sharp and exciting mainline with 5...  dxc4 ! } )
