2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. h4{ Moving the h-pawn up the board on move 3 has its ideas, it's somewhat critical on move 5 as we'll see later in this chapter see but on move 4 it's rather mistimed! }
4. c5{ Black reacts in the center, a perfect counter to White's flank attack! }
5. cxd5( 5.h5 { isn't at all a threat since White does not have enough control over the center. }5...cxd4 6.Qxd4 Nc6 7.Qd1 d4-+ { and Black was already considerably better in 1-0 (57) Pichot,A (2625)-Csonka,B (2474) Chess.com INT 2022. Black ended up losing this online blitz game, but that had nothing to do with the opening. The conclusion here is that White should first increase his control over the center with 4.  Nf3  and only then expand on the kingside with 5.  h4 . } )
5. Nxd5
6. Na4{ An interesting one-game idea, which Carlsen succesfully used to beat MVL in the online game 1-0 }{ (37) }{ Carlsen,M }{ (2847) }{ -Vachier Lagrave,M }{ (2751) }{ chess24.com INT 2021. White steps out of ... Nxc3  and goes after the  c5  pawn. }( 6.dxc5?! { is dubious and incongruent with }4.h4 { in the sense that White has illogically shifted from playing on the kingside to the center. Concretely, }6...Nxc3 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 8.bxc3 Bg7= { gives Black very easy play. The second player has a lead in development,  c3  is a target and the  c5  pawn will drop to ... Na6xc5 . } )
6. Nf6{ After careful analysis, I concluded this novel move is Black's best way of fighting for an edge. }( {  (a)  }6...Nc6 { was played by MVL. }7.e4 Nf6 8.d5 Nd4 { is playable but I believe Black can aim for more. } )( {  (b)  Black should stay clear of the endgame that ensues after }6...cxd4 7.Qxd4 Nf6 8.Qxd8 Kxd8 9.Nf3 Nc6 { This position was reached in the games 0-1 (40) Makarian,R (2533)-Kushagra,M (2359) Belgrade 2022 and 0-1 (7) Van Foreest,J (2702)-Ragger,M (2643) Chartres 2022. Despite the fact that Black won both encounters, White has the better chances in this endgame should he go for the novel }10.Bf4!  )
7. Nxc5
7. e5{ The point behind 6... Nf6  is now revealed. Black lured White into playing  Nxc5  to create a target on  c5  and undermine the  d4  pawn. }
8. Nb3( {  (a)  }8.dxe5? { is no good on account of }8...Qxd1 9.Kxd1 Bxc5 10.exf6 Bxf2⩱ { White is temporarily a pawn up but the  f6  pawn will soon drop to  ... Nd7 xf6 . White's structural weaknesses and exposed king are, however, permanent features of this position. }( {  (b)  }8.Nf3?! { is dubious as after }8...exd4 9.Nb3 Nc6 10.Nfxd4 { is strongly met by }10...Ne4!⩱ { with the deadly threat of ... Bb4 +. Even worse is }10.Nbxd4? { which loses material to }10...Ne4 11.a3 Qa5−+ { . } ) )
8. Nc6
9. e3
9. exd4
10. Be2( 10.Nxd4 { loses outright to }10...Bb4+ 11.Bd2 Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2 Ne4! 13.Qc2 Qa5+ 14.Kd1 Bf5-+ { White's king is in no man's land. Enough said! }( 10.exd4?! Bb4+ 11.Bd2 Qe7+ 12.Be2 O-O⩱ { leaves White completely pinned down. } ) )
10. Bb4+{ is the most enterprising continuation. }( { Alternatively, the simple }10...dxe3 { leads to a balanced endgame after }11.Qxd8 Nxd8 12.Bxe3 Bg7 13.Nf3 O-O= { . } )
11. Kf1
11. O-O{ White's way behind in development and the king on  f1  is in no man's land. I'd definitely take Black here! }
