3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. h4{ is an ambitious continuation, which Morozevich brought to top-level chess all the way back in 2012. A year later Grischuck essayed it against Magnus Carlsen in the 2013 London Candidates and it's remained popular ever since. }
5. dxc4{ is the most dynamic continuation. Black takes on  c4  and is ready to follow up with ... c5 . }
6. e4{ White has to fight for the center if he ever hopes to later start a kingside attack with  h5 . }
6. c5{ And we fight back - our typical Grünfeld break to undermine White's center works very well here! }
7. d5{ White closes and stabilizes the center - a necessary pre-condition to starting play on the flanks. }( 7.h5 { is very premature. Black can simply go ahead and capture it with }7...Nxh5 { followed by ... Bg4  with an excellent game. } )
7. b5{ is the entire point behind 5... dxc4 . Black protects the  c4  pawn and continues to fight for central control by introducing ... b4  into the position. }
8. h5{ is invariably played. White is now threatening  h6  which forces Black to castle kingside. }
8. O-O{ There's really no other way to deal with the threat of  h6 . It might seem like Black is castling right into an attack, but the fianchetto structure is very resilient. }( 8...Nxh5?! { places the knight offside and releases the pressure on the  e4  pawn, allowing }9.Nxb5 Qa5+ 10.Nc3⩲ { with at least a slight edge. Note that }10...Bxc3+?! 11.bxc3 Qxc3+? 12.Bd2 Qa3 13.Rc1+- { is terrible for Black. The  c4  pawn is about to drop and White's dark-squared bishop will be an absolute monster. } )
9. hxg6
9. fxg6{ is the best recapture. Black opens up the f-file for the  f8  rook and keeps the h-file closed. The major drawback of this recapture is that the king is slightly exposed on the  a2 - g8  diagonal, which Black must be a tad careful about. Also, the  e6  square is now slightly weaker. }( 9...hxg6 { would only open up the h-file for White. } )
10. Qc2{ White covers the  e4  pawn and is now threatening  Nxb5 . }( 10.Nxb5 { still doesn't work. Black responds with the standard }10...Qa5+ { forcing White's knight back. }11.Nc3 Nxe4 12.Bd2 Nd6Ν { is my preferred continuation, holding onto the  c4  pawn with a slight edge for Black. }( { (  }12...Nxc3 { is a decent alternative. }13.Qc1 Nd7 14.Bxc3 Bxc3+ 15.bxc3⩱ { . }{ ) } ) )
10. Na6{ doesn't give White a chance to take on  b5  as ... Nb4  is coming. }
11. a3{ We wanted  Nb4 , of course. }
11. Qa5{ renews the threats of ... Nb4  and ... Nxe4 . This clearly isn't what White had in mind. }( 12.Bd2 Nb4! 13.Qb1 Nd3+∓ { gets rid of the  f1  bishop, which is one of White's strongest minors in this structure (mainly due to ... fxg6  that weakened a bunch of light squares). } )
