20. c3{ looks to blast open the long diagonal. White may be an exchange up but is virtually undeveloped and has to be precise here to not get in trouble. }
21. b3( 21.Ra2 Nxd6 22.bxc3 Nxa4 { Black is on the verge of taking over here with ... Bxc3  coming. } )
21. Nxd6
22. Bf4
22. c4{ Exclam! }( { The point is White has no time for }23.Bxd6?? { as }23...cxb3 { gives Black two unstoppable connected passed pawns. } )
23. bxc4
23. Ndxc4( 23...Nbxc4? 24.Nb5 { is a very annoying pin. } )
24. Nd5
24. Re8
25. Nxb6
25. Nxb6
26. Be3
26. c2{ Natural and strong. Black advances the dangerous passer and opens up the dark-squared bishop. }
27. Rc1
27. Bxa4
28. Bxb6
28. Bc3+
29. Kf1
29. Bb2{ A relatively forced sequence now follows... }
30. Bc4+
30. Kg7
31. Be3
31. Rxe3
32. Rxc2
32. Bxc2
33. fxe3
33. a4{ White's extra exchange is immaterial as the a-pawn is far too strong. }( { For example }34.Ke2 Be4 35.Kf2 a3 36.Rd1 Kf6 37.Rd6+ Kf5 38.Ra6 h5 39.Ra5+ Kf6 40.Kg3 g5= { White has no way of making progress. } ){ There's no need to memorize this entire line given Black’s play is quite logical. Nevertheless, I felt the need to provide with you all this analysis as this line was recommended in the Chessable course  Fighting the Grünfeld with Harry  by InfiniteFlash. }
