1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. h4{ is an ambitious continuation, which Morozevich brought to top-level chess all the way back in 2012. A year later Grischuck essayed it against Magnus Carlsen in the 2013 London Candidates and it's remained popular ever since. }
5. dxc4{ is the most dynamic continuation. Black takes on  c4  and is ready to follow up with ...  c5 . }
6. e4{ White has to fight for the center if he ever hopes to later start a kingside attack with  h5 . }
6. c5{ And we fight back - our typical Grünfeld break to undermine White's center works very well here! }
7. d5{ White closes and stabilizes the center - a necessary pre-condition to starting play on the flanks. }
7. b5{ is the entire point behind 5... dxc4 . Black protects the  c4  pawn and continues to fight for central control by introducing ... b4  into the position. }
8. h5{ is invariably played. White is now threatening  h6  which forces Black to castle kingside. }
8. O-O{ There's really no other way to deal with the threat of  h6 . It might seem like Black is castling right into an attack, but the fianchetto structure is very resilient. }
9. hxg6
9. fxg6{ is the best recapture. Black opens up the f-file for the  f8  rook and keeps the h-file closed. The major drawback of this recapture is that the king is slightly exposed on the  a2 - g8  diagonal, which Black must be a tad careful about. Also, the  e6  square is now slightly weaker. }( 9...hxg6 { would only open up the h-file for White. } )
10. e5{ is White's most direct and popular continuation. The plan is to roll Black over in the center with  e5  followed by  d6  and a nifty  Qd5 + check afterward. }
10. Ng4
11. d6
11. e6{ is absolutely necessary to stop  Qd5+ . }
12. Rxh7{ The  e5  pawn is hanging so White must continue in a forcing manner. }( { The rook is untouchable as }12...Kxh7 { loses to }13.Ng5+ Kg8 14.Qxg4 { Black has no good way of stopping  Qh3 - h7 . }14...Bxe5 15.Qh3+-  )
12. Rf5{ is an important move to remember. Black stops  Ng5  while upping the pressure on the  e5  pawn. }( 12...Kxh7?? { I know I'm repeating myself but do NOT take the rook, which loses immediately to }13.Ng5+ Kg8 14.Qxg4+- { . Black is defenseless versus  Qh3 - h7 . } )
13. Rxg7+{ sacrificing an exchange is the first move to consider. }
13. Kxg7
14. Nxb5
14. Nc6{ White's center quickly comes under rapid fire, meaning there's no time to go after Black's king on  g7 . }( { A sample continuation goes }15.Bd2 Rb8 16.Bxc4 Ngxe5 17.Bc3 Kf7= { steps out of the long diagonal. White is an exchange down and there's no obvious way to continue the attack. I'd already take Black here, even if the machine insists the position is equal. } )
