16. Bb7{ We've reached an unclear position where Black is a pawn up. White certainly has enough compensation with a strong bishop on  e7  and rook on  h7 , but not enough for an advantage. You can find further analysis below and in the subsequent alternative lines, which you can opt to train. }( {  (a)  }17.g4 Rf7! { is a fantastic resource. Note that }18.Nxf7 Qxf7 19.Ng5? { runs into the nasty }19...Nf3+! { . } )( {  (b)  }17.Rxg7+ Kxg7 18.Nxe6+ { can be met with the calm }18...Kg8 { not fearing }19.Nc7 { as Black is after all an exchange up. }19...Qf7 20.Ng5 Rxg5 21.Bxg5 Rf8↑ { with good play against White's kingside. } )( {  (c)  }17.Qc2 Nc6! { hits  e7  and threatens ... Nd7 , which effectively forces }18.Rxg7+ Kxg7 19.Qc3+ e5 20.Ne6+ Kg8 21.Nc7 Qf7= { with the idea ... Nxe7  was fine for Black in ½-½ (37) Esipenko, A (2686) -Svidler,P (2723) Moscow 2020. } )( {   }19.Nxe6+? { is tempting but wrong. }19...Kg8 20.Nc7 Nd4! 21.Qd2 Qf7-+ { and White is busted. The  e4  knight is hanging so there's no time to take on  a8 . } )
