[White "12) 4.h4 & 4.Nf3 5.h4"]
[Black "10. e5 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. h4{ is an ambitious continuation, which Morozevich brought to top-level chess all the way back in 2012. A year later Grischuck essayed it against Magnus Carlsen in the 2013 London Candidates and it's remained popular ever since. }
5. dxc4{ is the most dynamic continuation. Black takes on  c4  and is ready to follow up with ...  c5 . }
6. e4{ White has to fight for the center if he ever hopes to later start a kingside attack with  h5 . }
6. c5{ And we fight back - our typical Grünfeld break to undermine White's center works very well here! }
7. d5{ White closes and stabilizes the center - a necessary pre-condition to starting play on the flanks. }
7. b5{ is the entire point behind 5... dxc4 . Black protects the  c4  pawn and continues to fight for central control by introducing ... b4  into the position. }
8. h5{ is invariably played. White is now threatening  h6  which forces Black to castle kingside. }
8. O-O{ There's really no other way to deal with the threat of  h6 . It might seem like Black is castling right into an attack, but the fianchetto structure is very resilient. }
9. hxg6
9. fxg6{ is the best recapture. Black opens up the f-file for the  f8  rook and keeps the h-file closed. The major drawback of this recapture is that the king is slightly exposed on the  a2 - g8  diagonal, which Black must be a tad careful about. Also, the  e6  square is now slightly weaker. }( 9...hxg6 { would only open up the h-file for White. } )
10. e5{ is White's most direct and popular continuation. The plan is to roll Black over in the center with  e5  followed by  d6  and a nifty  Qd5 + check afterward. }
10. Ng4
11. d6
11. e6{ is absolutely necessary to stop  Qd5+ . }
12. Rxh7{ The  e5  pawn is hanging so White must continue in a forcing manner. }( 12.Rxh7 { The rook is untouchable as }12...Kxh7 { loses to }13.Ng5+ Kg8 14.Qxg4 { Black has no good way of stopping  Qh3 - h7 . }14...Bxe5 15.Qh3+-  )
12. Rf5{ is an important move to remember. Black stops  Ng5  while upping the pressure on the  e5  pawn. }( 12...Kxh7?? { I know I'm repeating myself but do NOT take the rook, which loses immediately to }13.Ng5+ Kg8 14.Qxg4+- { Black is defenseless versus  Qh3 - h7 . } )
13. Rh3{ After 12... Rf5 , the rook on  h7  was hanging so White brings it back to safety. }
13. Nc6{ A strong reply, White's center quickly comes under pressure just like in the 13.Rxg7  variation. Black can choose to capture on  e5  with either knight depending on how White continues. In case of ... Ngxe5 , Black preserves the option of ... Nd4  while ...  Ncxe5  maintains the pressure on the  f2  pawn. }( 13...b4?! { provokes }14.Ne4± { a move White wanted to play anyhow, not to mention the  c4  pawn is now weak. }( 13...Nxe5? { fails tactically to }14.Nh4! { with problems on  g6 . For example }14...Rh5 15.Nxg6+− { wins the  g6  pawn immediately }{ while }14...Rf7 15.f4+− { will pick it up on the next turn. } ) )
14. a4{ Undermining the  c4  pawn is far less critical. Daniel Barrish gave this move an exclamation mark, but I think he got a bit overexcited about White's chances. }
14. Ngxe5{ We don't need to be asked twice to take down White's center. }( 14...b4 { is playable, but the text is more ambitious. } )
15. axb5
15. Nd4( { We don't want to give White the option of meeting }15...Nxf3 { with }16.Rxf3 { . As such, we first play ... Nd4  before taking on  f3 . } )
16. Be3( 16.Nxe5 Rxe5+ 17.Be2 Bb7 18.Kf1 Nxe2 19.Nxe2 Rd5 20.Qc2 Rxd6= { I'd definitely take Black with the two bishops. ... Rd3  is likely coming next. } )
16. Nexf3+{ This is Black's strongest continuation, which Daniel Barrish failed to mention in the Chessable course  The Principled Queen's Gambit - Part 2 . }
17. gxf3
17. Qxd6
18. Bxc4
18. Bb7
19. Ne4
19. Qe5{ Despite the engine shooting an endless string at zeros, I believe Black is calling the shots here with immediate threats of ... Rd8  and  ... Nxf3 + . }
