1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
( { We'll start out by examining the premature advance }3.d5 { . } )3. h4{ This move was tried by a few players throughout the 2000s. Veselin Topalov essayed it in the 2016 Candidates, but it never got much traction possibly due to Topalov ending up at the bottom of the crosstable. Grischuk took notice though and two years later he played it whenever possible with White scoring some fine wins against several 2700+ players. }( { Note that }3...Bg7 4.Nc3 { This early h-pawn advance works pretty well against the standard Grünfeld move order with }4...d5 { as }5.h5! { gives White a turbocharged version of the 5.h4 variation not having spent a tempo on  Nf3 . As such, we're going to switch to a King's Indian-like setup where  h2 - h4  often turns out to be premature. }5...Nxh5 6.cxd5 e6 7.g4↑ { occurred in the high-profile game ½-½ (32) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2767) Jerusalem 2019 and is a position I'd rather avoid. } )
3. Bg7
4. Nc3{ After careful analysis, I chose to recommend }
4. Nc6{ is an interesting, trendy move. The idea is to meet  e4  with ... e5 , not worrying much about  d4 - d5  which does displace the  c6  knight but weakens the central  e5  and  c5  squares as well as increase the scope of the  g7  bishop. }{    This move was  not  considered in the Chessable course  The Harry Attack: Fighting Kingside Fianchettos after 1. d4  by GM Simon Williams and IM Richard Palliser. }
