7. d6{ White was threatening to go  f4  on the previous turn so ... d6  taking control over the  g4  square is mandatory. We now see the drawback of White's early  h2 - h4 , that is the  g4  square has been permanently weakened such that  f2 - f4  now loses all its bite. }
8. Nf3
8. Neg4( 8...c6 { is also playable. However, I'd rather avoid the position after }9.Bf4! { - a very tricky move that prevents the natural }9...Qe7 { on account of }10.c5! { - Black instead develops the queen with }{   }9...Qa5 10.O-O O-O 11.Qxd6 Nxf3+ 12.Bxf3 Be6=∞ { Black should have enough for the pawn here but I see no need to go here. } )
9. Nd4
9. c6{ Black is ready to castle and likely follow up with ... Re8 . Long term, we can look to break in the center with  d4 - d5  (which ... c6  was a precursor to). In case of  f2 - f3 , the knight can simply drop back to  e5 . }( { Importantly, }10.h5 Nxh5 11.Bxg4? { fails to win a piece given the  d4  knight drops after }11...Bxg4 12.Qxg4 Bxd4∓ { . } )
