7. c6{  h4-h5  is not an immediate threat so there's no need to play 7... h5  as in 0-1 (41) Fedoseev, V (2696)-Carlsen,M  (2847) Krasnaya Polyana 2021. Instead, it's more productive to chip away at White's center with ... c6 . }( 7...c6 8.h5?! { is premature. Black can simply take, not worrying about }8...Nxh5 9.Bxh5 gxh5 10.Qxh5? { with the king still on  e8 . Black is the only side attacking here with }10...Bg4 11.Qg5 Bf6-+ { which forces White's queen back. The  c4  pawn is also en prise. } )
8. Nf3{ has yet to be played but I consider it to be White's most natural move. }( 8.Nh3 { featured in 0-1 (71) Atakhan,A (2294)-Darini,P (2432) Teheran 2021. Black could have simply castled here }8...O-O { noting that }9.Nf4?! { gets hit by }9...b5! 10.cxb5 cxb5 11.Bxb5 Qa5↑ { .  Black has the initiative and is already threatening to win material with ... Nxe4 . White has to tread carefully to not lose immediately. } )
8. Nxf3+
9. Bxf3
9. Bd7{ is a useful developing move. Black should delay  O-O  until White does so since  h4 - h5  becomes harmless without the rook on  h1 . Another rule of thumb is to delay ...  h5  until White has developed the dark-squared bishop such that  Bg5  can be met with ... h6 . }( {  (a)  }10.O-O O-O 11.Bg5 h6 12.Be3 h5 13.Rc1 Bg4= { is very decent for Black. The queen is likely to come out to  b6  or  a5  and the  a8  rook to  c8 . } )( {  (b)  }10.h5 { is nothing to worry about. }10...Nxh5 11.Bxh5 gxh5 12.Rxh5 Qb6= { gives Black good play. } )
