6. Bg4( { An important move to remember, Black first pins the knight before playing ... e5 . With White's knight already on  f3 , }6...e5?! { does not quite work as after }7.d5 Nd4 8.Nxd4 exd4 9.Qxd4 O-O 10.Bg5! { is very strong. The idea is that following }10...h6 11.Bxf6 Bxf6 12.Qd2⩲ { Black's knights are gone and so it'll be hard to exploit the weak dark squares. Sure, Black has an unopposed bishop on this color complex but it's not quite enough for an entire pawn. } )
7. Be2
7. e5{ is very timely. If White were to get in  Be3 , then Black would lose to access the  d4  square. }
8. d5
8. Bxf3{ Black eliminates the  f3  knight and is ready to jump into  d4 . }
9. Bxf3
9. Nd4
10. Be3
10. a6{ readies counterplay on the queenside based on the ... b5  break. We're not particularly worried about  Bxd4  as we'll get tremendous play on the dark squares. }( 10...c5 { as recommended by Svidler in his Lifetime Repertoire course here on Chessable is also interesting. } )
11. Bxd4
11. exd4
12. Qxd4
12. O-O{ Next up is ... Nd7  with full compensation for the pawn. White's king is in a real conundrum:     (a)  If it heads to the  queenside , it can quickly come under attack after ... b5  opening up lines.      (b)  Castling  kingside  will be hard with the pawn on  h4  loose.     (c)  Staying in the  center  will run into the pawn break ... f5  with play down the e- and f-files. }( { I should also point out that Black is threatening to take on  e4 , for example }13.h5? Nxe4! { wins material. } )
