3. h4{ This move was tried by a few players throughout the 2000s. Veselin Topalov essayed it in the 2016 candidates, but it never got much traction possibly due to Topalov ending up at the bottom of the crosstable. Grischuk took notice though and two years later he played it whenever possible with White scoring some fine wins against several 2700+ players. }( { Note that }3...Bg7 4.Nc3 { This early h-pawn advance works pretty well against the standard Grunfeld move order with }4...d5 { as }5.h5! { gives White a turbocharged version of the 5.h4 variation not having spent a tempo on  Nf3 . As such, we're going to switch to a King's Indian-like setup where  h2 - h4  often turns out to be premature. }5...Nxh5 6.cxd5 e6 7.g4↑ { occurred in the high-profile game ½-½ (32) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2767) Jerusalem 2019 and is a position I'd rather avoid. } )
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ is an interesting, trendy move. The idea is to meet  e4  with ... e5 , not worrying much about  d4 - d5  which does displace the  c6  knight but weakens the central  e5  and  c5  squares as well as increase the scope of the  g7  bishop. }{    This move was  not  considered in the Chessable course  The Harry Attack: Fighting Kingside Fianchettos after 1. d4  by GM Simon Williams and IM Richard Palliser. }
5. Nf3
5. d6
6. d5{ White immediately knocks back the  c6  knight. Black now has to play energetically not to get overrun. }( 6.Bg5?! { featured in 0-1 (14) Peric,B  (1810)-Matko,M  (2099) Sentjur 2008. However, }6...h6Ν 7.Bxf6 Bxf6 { only helps Black. } )
6. Nb8
7. e4
7. e6{ is the pawn break to go for here. Black is looking to open the e-file as fast as possible, intending a quick ... O-O  and ... Re8 . }( 7...c6 { allows White to consolidate the space advantage. }8.Be2 Bg4 9.Be3 Qa5 10.O-O O-O⩲ { White was slightly better in ½-½ (32) Bluebaum,M (2669)-Ivic,V  (2582) Krasnaya Polyana 2021, although Black's position remained playable. } )
8. Be2( 8.Bg5Ν { is a logical move that has yet to be played, a testament to how unexplored these positions are in practice. As usual, we start by knocking the bishop back with }8...h6 9.Bf4 exd5 10.cxd5 Nbd7! { Black shouldn't rush with 10... O-O  so as not to have to lose a tempo defending the  h6  pawn after 11.  Qd2 . }11.Qc2 O-O = { followed by ... Re8  gives Black decent counterplay. If White's king heads to the queenside, then ... c6  to open the c-file becomes very attractive. } )( {   }11.Qd2 Nc5! { The attack on the  e4  pawn is very awkward for White to meet. } )
8. O-O( 8...c6? { is premature on account of }9.dxe6 Bxe6 10.Bf4+− { when the  d6  pawn drops. } )
9. O-O{ Natural but way too cooperative. }( 9.dxe6Ν Bxe6 10.Nd4 Qe8! { is a great square for the queen, which can pop out to  e5  after ... Nc6  and ... Bd7 . Black can also look to break with ... f5  (hence why we can keep the rook on  f8 ) after ... Nh5 . } )
9. exd5
10. exd5
10. Re8{ The engine eval bar is already tipping in Black's favor with the second player going on to win in 0-1 (35) Collin,M (2129)-Gomez Barrera,J (2210) Biel 2022. White would much rather have the h-pawn back on  h2  in this position. }
