1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. f3{ is the  Saemisch anti-Grunfeld  - one of White's most ambitious continuations. The plan is to play 4.  e4  and take over the entire center. }( { Moreover, it pre-empts the standard Grunfeld play based on }3...d5 { as after }4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e4 { Black's knight has to go back as there's quite obviously no ...  Nxc3  in the position. All this doesn't come for free though, the  g1  knight no longer has the  f3  square available which can make it cumbersome for White to develop the kingside. } )
3. c5{ This Benoni-like approach gives Black a dynamic game and avoids the long theoretical debates after 3... d5 , which requires learning a ton of lines for little upside. }( { My files on }3...d5 { stretch well past move 30 and Black has far fewer chances to ever play for the full point - certainly not what this course is about! } )
