1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. f3{ is the  Saemisch anti-Grunfeld  - one of White's most ambitious continuations. The plan is to play 4.  e4  and take over the entire center. }( { Moreover, it pre-empts the standard Grunfeld play based on }3...d5 { as after }4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e4 { Black's knight has to go back as there's quite obviously no ...  Nxc3  in the position. All this doesn't come for free though, the  g1  knight no longer has the  f3  square available which can make it cumbersome for White to develop the kingside. } )
3. c5( { This Benoni-like approach gives Black a dynamic game and avoids the long theoretical debates after }3...d5 { , which requires learning a ton of lines for little upside. } )
4. d5( 4.dxc5?! { surrenders the center. }4...e6 { Attempting to hold onto the  c5  pawn with }5.Be3 { can easily backfire after }5...b6! 6.cxb6 axb6↑ { followed by ... d5  or ...  Bb4+  gives Black a fantastic game. We can wish White good luck developing the kingside in a timely manner. } )
4. d6
5. e4
5. e6{ An important detail to remember in this structure is that White's  g1  knight would ideally like to go to  f2  via  h3 . That's currently impossible with the bishop on  c8  as we'd just chop on  h3 . As a rule of thumb Black should delay ... Nbd7  until White's knight can no longer pop out to  h3 . }( { Case in point: }6.Nh3? exd5 7.cxd5 Bxh3 { destroys White's kingside structure. After }8.gxh3 Nh5∓ { ... Qh4 + is about to show up on the board. White is in big trouble. } )
6. Bd3{ was essayed by Ding Liren in the 2021 Candidates tournament, going on to take down Ian Nepomniachtchi in the last round of the event (which the Russian GM had already won by then). }
6. Nbd7{ is a new move and a very logical one at that. In the Samisch variation of the King's Indian, it's very typical for Black to bring out the knight to  e5  when White goes for setups involving  Bd3 . }
7. Ne2( 7.Nh3 { taking advantage of the fact that Black played  Nbd7  and can no longer take on  h3  doesn't work out concretely as }7...Ne5 { grabs the  d3  bishop. White is not in time to retreat it with }8.Be2 { since }8...exd5 9.cxd5 Bxh3 { cripples White's kingside structure. } ){  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable variation in the upcoming  alternative trainable line. }
7. Ne5{ Black will be able to pick White's  d3  bishop - a major achievement for Black in these Benoni structures. Let me explain: it's not that White's bishop is all the great. Rather, Black has less space and typically can't find great squares for all 4 of his minor pieces. By exchanging one pair of minors, however, this issue goes away. }
8. Nbc3
8. exd5
9. cxd5
9. Nxd3+
10. Qxd3
10. Bg7{ Black has no problems whatsoever in this position. Importantly, the second player has succeeded in exchanging a pair of pieces, which makes White's space advantage essentially a non-issue. }
