3. c5{ This Benoni-like approach gives Black a dynamic game and avoids the long theoretical debates after 3... d5 , which requires learning a ton of lines for little upside. }
4. d5( 4.dxc5?! { surrenders the center. }4...e6 { Attempting to hold onto the  c5  pawn with }5.Be3 { can easily backfire after }5...b6! 6.cxb6 axb6↑ { followed by ... d5  or ...  Bb4+  gives Black a fantastic game. We can wish White good luck developing the kingside in a timely manner. } )
