7. Nec3{ Instead of putting the knight on  g3 , where it is often subject to ...  h5 - h4 , White opts to transfer it to the queenside. The  b1  knight will come out to  d2  and later hop to  c4  once ... exd5   cxd5  happens. The downside of this setup is that by transferring the  g1  knight to the other side of the board, White's kingside will be far more vulnerable. }
7. Nh5{ attempts to immediately exploit the downsides of  Ne2 - c3 . Black's queen is threatening to come out to  h4 . This move was  not  covered in the Chessable course  The Principled Queen's Gambit - Part 2  by FM Daniel Barrish. }( 7...a6!? { with the idea ... exd5   cxd5   b5  is also interesting. }8.a4 Nh5 9.Be3 f5 { leads to similar play as the text. } )
8. Be3
8. f5{ Black would love to get in  f4  and secure the fantastic  e5  outpost for one of the knights, which White won't be able to challenge. }
9. Qd2
9. O-O{ renews the threat of  ... f5 -f4  and gives Black an excellent game. }( { In the game Gnojek, P (2254)-Plischki, S (2375) Marianske Lazne 2022, White quickly got in trouble after }10.Bd3 f4! 11.Bf2 exd5 12.Nxd5 Nc6⩱ { with more space and fantastic central outposts on  e5  and  d4 . Black has the upper hand. } )
