3. g3{ The  Fianchetto  variation was first played by Alekhine against Oscar Mueller in 1923 and Rubinstein would later go on to essay it against Ernst Grünfeld. Positional masterminds Karpov and Botvinnik were also great exponents of this variation. In the late 2000s, 3.  g3  surged in popularity in large part due to Boris Avrukh's seminal 1.  d4  GM Repertoire book series and has remained relatively popular ever since. White brings the bishop out to  g2  to exert pressure down the long diagonal and fight for the critical  e4  and  d5  squares. }
3. d5{ is the most combative and dynamic response to the fianchetto system. Black goes for ... d5  right away in true Grünfeld style! }( 3...c6 { with the idea  d5  to erect a Slav structure is fully playable but not at all exciting. White has a myriad of move orders and setups, not to mention the option of taking on  d5  and going for a symmetric position where only the first player can ever be better. } )
4. Bg2{ is more flexible than  Nf3 . White's bishop surely belongs on  g2  while the  g1  knight may choose to come out to  e2 . }
