8. O-O
8. O-O
9. e3{ is White's most popular and ambitious continuation. The first player is aiming to complete development with  Bb2  and  Qe2  and then gradually suffocate Black by moving the central pawns forward. Black's play will revolve around exploiting the weak light squares in White's camp, especially  c4  and  e4 . To this end, the light-squared bishop will be developed to  f5  and can later move into  e4 . Black's queen can pop out to  a5  or can swing to  h5  via the  d5  square. By blockading the light squares, Black will keep White's center at bay and relegate the  c1  bishop to passivity. }
9. Nc6
10. Qe2{ is an excellent square for White's queen, from where it supports a future  e2 - e4  and clears the way for  Rd1 . }
10. Bf5{ We already know this is where the light-squared bishop belongs! Apart from locking down  e4 , I should also mention the bishop controls the  b1  square thus ruling out  Rb1 . }
11. Rd1( 11.Bb2 Qb6 12.Rfd1 { has no independent value. } )( 11.Nh4 { runs into }11...Bg4 { . } )
11. Qb6{ Black steps out of the d-file and vacates the  d8  square for ... Rfd8 . The queen can't be challenged as ... Bf5  ruled out  Rb1  and  Nc4  walks into a pin after ... Qa6 . }
12. Bb2{ There's really no better square for the bishop. From  b2 , it supports the  d4  pawn and White can look to activate the bishop with  c3 - c4  later on. }
12. Rfd8{ All of Black's pieces are well placed and White's center isn't moving forward anytime soon. Black is in excellent shape with ... Be4  and ... Rac8  on the agenda. }( { For example, }13.Rac1 Be4 14.Nc4 Qa6 { is a typical reaction. The pin on the  c4  knight is quite annoying for White. }15.Bf1 Bd5 16.Nfd2 Be6! { Black steps out of  e4  with tempo and after }17.Ra1 Qa4= { has good play on the light squares. } )
