16. b6{ stops  Nc5  and makes White's queenside pieces look silly. White's central pawns eventually made it up the board but not the way the first player imagined it'd go. Their advance has left behind a whole host of weak squares, which Black will readily exploit with  ... Nb4 (/ Nc7 )-d5 . White's queenside pieces are also incredibly silly. }
