8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Re1{ has also been played a decent number of times. The idea is simple: White wants to expand in the center with  e2 - e4 . }
9. Nc6{ The knight surely belongs on  c6  so we might as well develop it right away. }
10. Bb2
10. Qb6{ Natural and strong. Black's queen comes out with a tempo on the  b2  bishop and ups the pressure on the  d4  pawn. }
11. Nc4{ was recommended by IM Christof Sielecki in the course  Keep it Simple: 1.d4 . However, he missed the following strong resource }
11. Qb5{ This is Black's best move, first provoking White's queen to  b3  before dropping back to  a6 . }
12. Qb3
12. Qa6{ Black drops back the queen and now has threats of ... Be6  and ... b5 . This is why we provoked White's queen to  b3  by first playing ... Qb5  and only then ... Qa6 ! }
13. e4( 13.Nce5 Nd7 14.Nxc6 bxc6 15.e3 Rb8= { gave Black a good game in ½-½ (38) Ingersol,H (2443) -Jacobs Jr,C (2228) ICCF email 2020. } )
13. Be6{ It seems like Black is walking right into a fork, but things are not so simple! }
14. d5( 14.Bf1 b5 15.Qa3 Qxa3 16.Nxa3 { occurred in the game ½-½ (49) Serner,A (2409)-Van Habberney,G (2352) ICCF email 2019. Now the simplest is }16...Bg4 17.Nd2 b4⇆ { with good counterplay. } )
14. Nxd5{ This is the point: Black sacrifices the knight for two pawns and annoying pressure on the  c4  knight. }
15. exd5
15. Bxd5
16. Nfd2
16. Bxg2
17. Kxg2
17. b5{ knocks the knight back while opening up the long diagonal for ...  Qb7 . Black is ready to say hello to White's vulnerable king on  g2 ! }
18. Ne3
18. Ne5{ The  d2  knight is exposed to a tempo like ... Rfd8 , the  b2  bishop is restricted and White's king on  g2  is vulnerable. With two pawns for the piece and a big initiative, I'd definitely take Black here. }( { The following game is good evidence for White's position being far from easy to play. A 2600 GM playing White quickly found himself in a worse position and eventually lost after }19.c4 Nxc4 20.Ndxc4?! bxc4 21.Nxc4 Rab8 22.Qa3 Qb7+ 23.Kg1 Bxb2 24.Nxb2 Qxb2 25.Qxa7 c4 26.Qxe7 Rfc8 27.a4 c3 28.Qf6 Qb4 29.a5 c2 30.Qf4 Rc4 31.Qe3 Qb2 32.Qc1 Qc3 33.a6 Rbc8 34.Kg2 R4c7 35.a7 Ra8 36.Qh6 Rcxa7 37.Rac1 Qc6+ 38.Kg1 Rd7 39.Qe3 Rad8 40.Qb3 Rd2 41.h4 h5 42.Rf1 Qe4 43.Rfe1 Qd4 44.Qf3 Rd3 { 0-1 (44) Predke,A (2611)-Grandelius,N (2694) Skopje 2019. } )
