1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. g3{ The  Fianchetto  variation was first played by Alekhine against Oscar Mueller in 1923 and Rubinstein would later go on to essay it against Ernst Grünfeld. Positional masterminds Karpov and Botvinnik were also great exponents of this variation. In the late 2000s, 3.  g3  surged in popularity in large part due to Boris Avrukh's seminal 1.  d4  GM Repertoire book series and has remained relatively popular ever since. White brings the bishop out to  g2  to exert pressure down the long diagonal and fight for the critical  e4  and  d5  squares. }
3. d5{ is the most combative and dynamic response to the fianchetto system. Black goes for ... d5  right away in true Grünfeld style! }
4. Bg2{ is more flexible than  Nf3 . White's bishop surely belongs on  g2  while the  g1  knight may choose to come out to  e2 . }
4. Bg7{ White has three main options at this junction:      
 Forego  cxd5  and simply bring the knight to  f3 ;      Take on  d5  and then develop the knight to  f3 ;     Take over the center with  cxd5  followed by  e2 - e4  and  Ne2 .     
  }
5. cxd5
5. Nxd5
6. Nf3{ Rather than expand in the center with 6.  e4 , White focuses on developing the kingside. }
6. Nb6{ Black steps out of the d-file and  e2 - e4  tempi moves while uncovering the  d8  queen, which now aims straight at the  d4  pawn. The  b6  knight is in prime position to later jump onto the weak  c4  square, courtesy of White having developed the light-squared bishop to  g2 .     Rather than go for the traditional central break with ... c5 , which would lead to a dull symmetric position, we're going to develop the  b8  knight to  c6  and aim for ... e5 .     Finally, the move order matters here. Black should first drop back the knight before castling kingside. }( 6...O-O 7.O-O Nb6 { is too little too late as White can meet }8.Nc3 Nc6 { with }9.d5 { forcing Black's knight back. The critical difference is that here }9...Bxc3 { does not come with check such that White can instead play }10.dxc6 Bg7 11.Bf4± { with strong pressure on Black's queenside. } )( {   }7...c5 { going for a symmetric pawn structure eventually equalizes but gives Black close to zero winning chances. } )( { Starting with }6...Nc6?! { allows White to steamroll in the center with }7.e4! Nb6 8.d5 Na5 9.Qc2 { when }9...f5 { fails to give Black adequate counterplay versus both }10.Ng5 { and }10.e5! { . } )
