[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6
3. g3{ The  Fianchetto  variation was first played by Alekhine against Oscar Mueller in 1923 and Rubinstein would later go on to essay it against Ernst Grünfeld. Positional masterminds Karpov and Botvinnik were also great exponents of this variation. In the late 2000s, 3.  g3  surged in popularity in large part due to Boris Avrukh's seminal 1.  d4  GM Repertoire book series and has remained relatively popular ever since. White brings the bishop out to  g2  to exert pressure down the long diagonal and fight for the critical  e4  and  d5  squares. }
3. d5{ is the most combative and dynamic response to the fianchetto system. Black goes for ... d5  right away in true Grünfeld style! }
4. Bg2{ is more flexible than  Nf3 . White's bishop surely belongs on  g2  while the  g1  knight may choose to come out to  e2 . }
4. Bg7{ White has three main options at this junction:      
 Forego  cxd5  and simply bring the knight to  f3 ;      Take on  d5  and then develop the knight to  f3 ;     Take over the center with  cxd5  followed by  e2 - e4  and  Ne2 .     
  }
5. cxd5
5. Nxd5
6. Nf3{ Rather than expand in the center with 6.  e4 , White focuses on developing the kingside. }
6. Nb6{ Black steps out of the d-file and  e2 - e4  tempi moves while uncovering the  d8  queen, which now aims straight at the  d4  pawn. The  b6  knight is in prime position to later jump onto the weak  c4  square, courtesy of White having develop the light-squared bishop to  g2 .     Rather than go for the traditional central break with ... c5 , which would lead to a dull symmetric position, we're going to develop the  b8  knight to  c6  and aim for ... e5 . }
7. Nc3
7. Nc6{ The knight comes out to  c6 , from where it targets the  d4  pawn and supports the key ... e5  central break. }
8. e3{ is forced. The  c1  bishop is not all that excited though! }( 8.d5? { blunders a pawn to }8...Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 Qxd5⩱  )( 8.Be3 { runs into ... Nc4  after }8...O-O 9.O-O Nc4!  )
8. O-O
9. O-O{ White's plan in this position is to complete development with  b3  followed by  Bb2  and then slowly suffocate Black by pushing the central pawns. We naturally won't let this happen! }
9. Re8{ is a useful waiting move. The rule of thumb here is that Black should only break with ... e5  when  d4 - d5  is not an option. }( { The immediate }9...e5 { is answered by }10.d5 { To avoid having the  g7  bishop staring at the  e5  pawn, Black must go for the forcing continuation }10...e4 11.dxc6 Qxd1 12.Rxd1 exf3 13.Bxf3 bxc6 { as seen in ½-½ }{ (44) }{ Fedoseev,V }{ (2707) }{ -Vidit,S }{ (2718) }{ Danzhou 2018 and ½-½ }{ (41) }{ Lenderman,A }{ (2607) }{ -Shankland,S }{ (2714) }{ Saint Louis 2021. While Black is objectively fine, I see no need to go for this and prefer to keep more fight in the position with 9... Re8 . } )
10. Re1{ White responds to 9... Re8  with a useful waiting move of his own. The first player will look to meet the ... e5  break with  e3 - e4  and even  f2 - f4  later on. }( 10.d5 { is premature as after }10...Na5 11.Nd4 Bd7= { Black will follow up with ... c6  and readily eliminate White's center. } )
10. a5{ Turns out that Black has plenty of useful waiting moves of his own. ... e5  still doesn't work because of  d5  so Black brings the a-pawn into play. Black can look to create weaknesses on the queenside with ... a4 - a3  and even bring the  a8  rook into the game via the  a5  square. }
11. Qe2{ is by far the mainline. The surge in popularity of this move can be traced back to Boris Avrukh's bestselling 1.d4 GM repertoire books published over a decade ago. }( {  (a)  }11.h3 { succeeds in stopping  Bg4  but Black's bishop can come into the game via  e6  and even pop out to  c4  thus discouraging  Qe2 . }11...a4 12.Qe2 Be6 { Black is now threatening ... Bc4  and if }13.Nd2 Nb4 { vacates the  c6  square with tempo such that }14.Rd1 { to avoid the fork on  c2  can be met with }14...c6= { which effectively blunts the  g2  bishop and any hopes White had for an edge. } )( {  (b)  }11.Qc2 { isn't such a great square for the queen as it's exposed to both ... Nb4  and ... Bf5 . }11...a4 12.Rd1 Bf5 13.Qe2 Qc8 { steps out of the d-file, both liberating the e-pawn and preparing ... Bg4  which can no longer be met with  h3 . } )( {  (c)  }11.b3 { weakens the long diagonal allowing Black to strike with }11...e5! { since }12.d5 { runs into }12...e4∓ { with trouble on the long diagonal. } ){  Note:  you can opt to train these clickables in the next  set of alternative trainable lines. }
11. Be6{ Taking control of some light squares, especially  c4 . Black will try to harass white's queen with ... Bc4 , and in the event of  Qc2 , then ... Nb4  can be considered. }( 11...e5 { is also fully playable. } )
12. Nd2{ comes with the dual idea of preventing ... Bc4  and later rerouting the knight to  c5 . }( 12.Rd1 { allows Black to move in with ... Bc4 . White's queen will now be chased down to the back rank. }12...Bc4 13.Qc2 Nb4 14.Qb1 e5! { solves all of Black's problems. A funny line that highlights the misplaced nature of White's queen follows }15.dxe5?? Qxd1+! 16.Nxd1 Bd3-+ { which traps the queen and nets Black an exchange. } )
12. Nb4{ Black threatens a deadly fork on  c2  and prepares to blunt White's bishop with ... c6 . This is a key maneuver worth remembering! }
13. Rd1
13. c6{ White's bishop on  g2  is restricted and the one on  c1  hasn't even seen the light of day. Black has an excellent game with ideas of ... a4 - a3 . }( { A sample line goes }14.a3 N4d5 15.Nce4 Qc8! { A strong move, Black covers the  b7  pawn and thus pre-empts  Nc5  as well as prepares ... Bg4 . }16.Nc5 Bg4 17.f3 Bh3 18.Bxh3 Qxh3 19.Nde4 Qc8 20.Nf2 Rd8= { Black is ready to kick back the  c5  knight, White's only active piece, with ... Nd7  and had no problems in the correspondence game ½-½ }{ (85) }{ Wunderlich,H }{ (2618) }{ -Maia,J }{ (2479) }{ ICCF email 2014. } )
