7. Ne2( 7.Nf3 { blocks the  g2  bishop such that after }7...Bg4 8.d5 O-O 9.O-O Qd7 { followed by ... c6  will eliminate White's center. White's knight would much rather be on  e2  here when the  g2  bishop would help defend the center. } )
7. c5{ is very timely. Black must undermine White's center at once. }( 7...O-O 8.O-O c5 { allows }9.dxc5! { now that White has already castled. } )
8. d5
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. e6{ strikes at the head of White's central pawn chain in an attempt to bring it down. In general, Black should keep the tension and only take on  d5  once White has committed the dark-squared bishop and the knights. This is because in the event of a quick ... exd5   exd5 , White will push ahead with  d6  and support it with  Bf4 . The  g2  bishop would then come alive and the  d6  pawn would greatly restrict Black's pieces - absolutely not what we want!     White can now choose the develop the  b1  knight with  Nbc3  or place it on  d2/a3 , in which case the  e2  knight will occupy the  c3  square. }
10. Nbc3
10. exd5{ is an opportune moment to take on  d5 . The reason is that after  exd5 , Black will follow up with ... Bf5  and look to plant a knight on the weak  d3  square with ...  Na6 - b4 . }
11. Nxd5{ Trading a pair of knights is sensible given the  e2  knight was slightly duplicating the one on  c3 . }
11. Nxd5
12. exd5( 12.Qxd5 Na6 13.Nc3 Qb6 { is completely fine for Black. } )
12. Bf5
13. Nc3{ White improves the knight and is now threatening to drive back Black's bishop with  g4 . }
13. c4{ Black takes firm control over the  d3  square, which is a fantastic outpost for the bishop. }
14. Qa4( 14.Bf4 { is also possible. Black gets a good game after }14...Qb6 Qd2 Nd7= { with ideas of ... Ne5  and ... Rfe8 . } )
14. Bd3
15. Re1
15. Qb6{ A nice square for the queen, from where it eyes the  b2  and  f2  pawns. The  b8  knight can come into the game via  a6 - c5 . Black followed up with ... Bd4  to target  f2  and had a fine game in ½-½ (25) Boettcher,F (2259)-Tsygankov,E (2399) LSS email 2013. }
