2. c5{ is one of the most dynamic ways of meeting the Trompowsky. Black immediately undermines the  d4  pawn and opens up the  a5 - d8  diagonal. This enables a quick queen sortie to  a5  or  b6  in many lines. Black will look to make an argument that White has developed the  g5  bishop prematurely. }
3. e3{ White simply reinforces the  d4  pawn. This is too tame an approach to set any problems. }( 3.Nc3 d5 { transposes to the Veresov . } )( 3.dxc5 e6 4.e3 Bxc5= { gives Black very easy play. } )
3. Qb6{ This early queen sortie illustrates one of the main points behind 2... c5 . Black immediately hits the  b2  pawn, which  Bg5  left undefended. }
4. b3{ Popular but bad. This move drastically weakens White's queenside. }( 4.Nc3 cxd4 5.exd4 e6 6.Nf3 Be7 7.Be2 d5= { gives Black an easy game. White's knight on  c3  is completely misplaced here. } )
4. Ne4{ A very natural move - Black's knight moves into the center of the board with tempo. It's clear White's early bishop sortie yielded absolutely nothing. }
5. Bf4
5. Nc6
6. Nf3( 6.d5? { blunders }6...g5! 7.Bxg5 Bg7 8.Nd2 Bc3-+ { .  Note:  the tactical sequence in this clickable is given as a trainable puzzle here . } )
6. cxd4
7. exd4
7. e5{ A strong clearance sacrifice! Black clears the route for ...  Bb4 + with tempo and puts White in big trouble. }( {  (a)  }8.dxe5?? Qxf2 { is game over! } )( {  (b)  }8.Bxe5 Bb4+ 9.Ke2 d5-+ { White's king is in no man's land. Black has a huge advantage. } )( {  (c)  }8.Nxe5 Bb4+ 9.Bd2 Qxd4-+ { is crushing. } )
