2. c5{ is one of the most dynamic ways of meeting the Trompowsky. Black immediately undermines the  d4  pawn and opens up the  a5 - d8  diagonal. This enables a quick queen sortie to  a5  or  b6  in many lines. Black will look to make an argument that White has developed the  g5  bishop prematurely. }
3. d5
3. Ne4{ The knight lunges into the center of the board with a tempo on White's bishop. What could be more natural? }( 3...Qb6 4.Nc3 Qxb2 5.Bd2 { The Vaganian gambit scores well for White in practice and is a variation I'd rather avoid. } )
4. Bf4{ is the best square for the bishop and White's main continuation by a mile. }( {  (a)  }4.Bh4? { runs into }4...Qb6 5.Qc1 g5! { vacating the  g7  square with tempo. After }6.Bg3 Bg7 7.c3 e6 8.dxe6 Qxe6∓ { Black is clearly better with ...  d5  and/or ... f5  on the agenda. White has no development, less space and zero control over the center. } )( {  (b)  }4.Bc1 { is very passive. }4...e6 5.c4 Qa5+ 6.Nd2 b5Ν { is a strong novelty. White's center collapses after }7.e3 bxc4 8.Bxc4 Bb7=  )
