8. Nf6{ Black has more space so logically avoids exchanges. The knight drops back to  f6  to pressure the  d5  pawn in conjunction with ... Bb7 . White needs to be precise to keep the d-pawn alive. }
9. e4( 9.a4! { is the engine's top choice, intending to meet }9...Bb7 { with }10.b4! { This is far from easy to find over the board. Best play by both sides continues }10...cxb3 11.Nxb3 Qb6! 12.axb5 a6 { The  d5  and  b5  pawns are hanging. Black will soon restore material equality, for example }13.c4 axb5 14.Rxa8 Bxa8 15.cxb5 Bxd5= { followed by ... e6  and ... Bd6  with easy development. The  b5  pawn may very well turn out to be a weakness.      Note:  up next, this clickable variation is given as an alternative  line that you can opt to train. } )
9. Bb7
10. Ngf3
10. e6{ White's central construction is about to collapse. Black has excellent prospects. }
