1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Bf4{ It's now time to cover the  London  system. Underestimate it at your own peril as this is an opening where White can play ambitiously and fight for an advantage.    Attempts to  refute  or  crush  the London usually backfire. One course with such a title on Chessable fails to even equalize with Black. Now I'm all for trying to 'crush' incorrect openings, but the London certainly does not fall into this category.     I'll be recommending a reliable system with 2... g6  aiming for Grunfeld-like structures wherever possible. After careful analysis with powerful cloud engines running Stockfish and LeelaZero, I've found numerous improvements over current theory that'll allow you to fight for the full point. }
2. g6
3. Nc3{ We'll start by covering all the setups with White's knight on  c3 . The idea is clear - White wants to take over the center with  e2 - e4 . }( { Note that   }2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 g6 { has no independent value. } )
3. d5{ Our standard Grünfeld move, taking control over the  e4  square. }( 3...Bg7 { allows a transposition to the Pirc defense after }4.e4 { which is only suitable if you play the Pirc with Black. } )
{ White now has three main continuations: }4. e3{ is White's most popular move seen in 1400+ OTB games. }( 4.Qd2 { is second most common with 500+ OTB games. } )( 4.Nf3 { is the third most played continuation with 150+ OTB games. } )
