3. Bg5{ The  Torre  attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to  g5 .     White typically places his light-squared bishop on  e2  or  d3 , the queenside knight on  d2 , and reinforces the  d4  pawn with  c2 - c3 . The first player then hopes to push forward with  e2 - e4  and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on  g5  can chop off knight on  f6  – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment. }
3. Bg7
4. Nbd2{ White has different move orders, most of which will transpose to the mainline. }( {  (a)  }4.e3 d5 5.Be2 O-O 6.Nbd2 { transposes to 3.  Bg5   Bg7  4.  Nbd2   O-O  5.  e3   d5  6.  Be2 .  }( {  (a1)    }5.c3 { will also transpose to the mainline as White can't do without  Nbd2 . } )( {  (a2)    }5.Nbd2 { is a direct transposition to the mainline after 4.  Nbd2   d5  5.  e3 . } ) )( {  (b)  Starting with }4.c3 { also has no independent value. }4...O-O 5.Nbd2 { transpoes to 4.  Nbd2   O-O  5. c3 . }( {  (b1)  }5.e3 d5 6.Nbd2 { transposes to  4.  Nbd2   O-O  5.  c3   d5  6. e3 . } ) )( {  (c)  }4.Nc3 d5 { transposes to the  Barry attack , which is covered via the 2.  Nf3   g6  3.  Nc3   d5  4.  Bg5   d5  move order here . } )
4. O-O{ Here we'll consider White's three most common moves, namely }
5. c3{ with 2600+ OTB games. }( 5.e4 { played in 2300+ OTB games. } )( 5.e3 { which featured in 1300+ OTB games. } )
