3. Bg5{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to  g5 .    White typically places his light-squared bishop on  e2  or  d3 , the queenside knight on  d2 , and reinforces the  d4  pawn with  c2 - c3 . The first player then hopes to push forward with  e2 - e4  and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on  g5  can chop off knight on  f6  – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment. }
3. Bg7
4. Nbd2
4. O-O{ There is no need to prevent  e4  with ... d5  since it's not a good option for White. }
5. c3
5. d5{ is my preferred approach. The alternative setup with 5... d6  is also fully playable, but why not take up more space in the center? }
6. e3
