9. b4{ A very interesting plan which has been played by several 2600+ GMs. The center is stable so White wants to expand on the queenside. }
9. c6{ This is my favorite approach, discouraging  b5 . The idea is that if White later goes  b5 , we can close the center with ... e4  and then bypass the b-pawn with .... c6 - c5  (this way not allowing en passant) and thus gain a lot of space. We can also undermine White's  b4  pawn with ... a5  next. }
10. a4
