3. g3{ We will now examine the  g3 system . This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course  Keep it Simple: 1.d4 .    White delays }{ (and often entirely foregoes) }{  c2-c4 , preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3. Bg7
4. Bg2
4. O-O
5. O-O{ is a flexible move. White can play  c2 - c4  next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5. d5{ is the move Grunfeld players should make. }
6. Bf4{ has been played a few hundred times. It is usually connected with the idea of  Qc1  and  Bh6 . }
6. c6{ is a good reply. Black hints at ... Qb6  to attack the  b2  pawn, which has been left unprotected after 6.  Bf4 . }
7. Qc1{ is White's main idea, supporting the  c4  break and possibly playing  Bh6 . }( 7.Nbd2 { is harmless. After }7...h6 8.c3 Nbd7= { Black takes control over the  e5  square. White's dark-squared bishop is now short on squares and can be hit with ... g5 . } )
7. Be6{ has never been played but is very logical, stopping White from immediately breaking with  c4 . There is no need to worry about  Bh6 . }
8. Bh6( { Worse is }8.Ne5?! { as after }8...Nbd7 9.Nd3 Rc8⩱ {  ...c5  is coming next. White's queen on  c1  is misplaced. } )( 8.Ng5?! { only loses a tempo to }8...Bg4 { hitting  e2 . }9.Nf3 Nbd7=  )( { The natural }8.Nbd2 { is also possible. After }8...Nbd7 9.c4 h6= { Black is very comfortable and can continue with ... g5 , ... Ne4  and ... Rc8 . } )
8. Nbd7
9. Bxg7
9. Kxg7{ I struggle to see what White achieved with  Bf4 ,  Qc1  and  Bh6 , apart from wasting 3 tempi that is. In the meantime, Black has completed development and his king is perfectly safe. }
10. Nbd2
10. a5{ A few years ago such flank moves would be frowned upon. It is both Leela and Stockfish's top choice, gaining space on the queenside. }
11. c4
11. b5{ is another remarkable Stockfish suggestion, attempting to open the c-file and expose White's queen. }
12. cxb5( { White can push forward with }12.c5 { but after }12...h6= { Black is in great shape. He can play ... Qc7 , ... Bf5  and ... Re8  to prepare the ... e5  break. } )
12. cxb5
13. Nb3
13. Rc8
14. Qe3
14. Qb6{ Black is in fantastic shape. He has more space on the queenside and is ready to jump into  e4 . }
