3. d5{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to  c3 , taking control over the  e4  square and thus preventing  e2 - e4 . }
4. Bg5{ The  Barry Attack , which is British slang for 'rubbish' attack according to the New in Chess Yearbook. Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after 4... Ne4 . }( 4.Bf4 { is covered in chapter 17  on the London System with }Nc3 { . } )
4. Ne4{ which is 5 times less popular than 4... Bg7  but much stronger. While 4... Bg7  comfortably equalizes, 4... Ne4  gives Black a significant advantage (or even an outright winning position) in every single line. }
5. Nxe4{ is the most popular move at the club level. It is, however, fairly dubious. }
5. dxe4{ forces White's knight back, which has no good place to retreat to. }
6. Ng1{ keeps the  d4  pawn alive. Nevertheless, if White is forced to undevelop his pieces, then the opening has obviously been a disaster. }
6. Bg7
7. c3( 7.e3 c5 8.c3 O-O { transposes to the text. } )
7. O-O
8. e3{ is most logical, preparing to complete development with  Bc4  and  Ne2 . Notice how our pawn on  e4  stops White from developing the knight to  f3 , which is its best square. }( { Alternatively }8.g3 { intending to fianchetto the light-squared bishop is strongly met by }8...Qd5! { hitting White's bishop and threatening ... e4 - e3 , thus forcing }9.Be3 { and after }9...Nd7 10.Bg2 Nf6∓ { Black is clearly better. The pawn on  e4  gives the second player a big space advantage and severely restricts White's pieces. } )
8. c5{ increases the pressure on the  d4  pawn. Next up is ... Nc6 . }
9. Bc4
9. Nc6
10. Ne2
{ This position was reached in the correspondence game 0-1 (35) Jina,J (2113) -Eilmes,D (2349) ICCF email 2005, where Black had the opportunity to gain the bishop pair advantage with }10. Na5
11. Bb3
11. Nxb3
12. axb3
12. h6{ Black is clearly better with the extra space afforded by the  e4  pawn and the two bishops. Next up are ... Be6  and ... Qb6  to attack the weak pawn on  b3 . }
