4. Ne4{ which is 5 times less popular than 4... Bg7  but much stronger. While 4... Bg7  comfortably equalizes, 4... Ne4  gives Black a significant advantage (or even an outright winning position) in every single line. }
5. Bf4{ is the most popular move at the master level and basically an admission that 4.  Bg5  was not a good move. If White wanted to place his bishop on  f4 , he should have done so on move 4! }
5. Nxc3{ permanently damages White's pawn structure just like in the 5.  Bh4  variation. The doubled c-pawns will remain a weakness for the rest of the game. }( 5...Bg7 { is playable but the text is far stronger. } )
6. bxc3
6. c5{ immediately undermines White's center. Black will be able to pressure it with ... Bg7  and .. .Qa5 in the near future. }
7. e3{ is the most popular continuation. }( 7.Qd2 { with the idea ... Bh6  has also been tried. However, after }7...Bg7 8.Bh6 Bxh6 9.Qxh6 { Apart from wasting valuable time, White did not achieve anything with this  Bh5  excursion. In fact }9...Qa5∓ { forces White's queen back with a clear advantage. White has nothing to show for his crippled pawn structure. } )( 7.dxc5?! { is obviously terrible, leaving White with tripled pawns on an open file. }7...Bg7 8.Be5 f6 9.Bg3 Qa5∓ { with a clear advantage for Black. } )
7. Bg7
8. Bb5+{ is the most popular position for the light-squared bishop. The alternatives below give Black at least a clear advantage. }( {  (a)  }8.Be2 { is very passive. After }8...Qa5 9.Qd2 Nd7 10.O-O O-O∓ { Black is clearly better. White has less space and no compensation for his crippled pawns. } )( {  (b)  }8.Bd3?! { is an OTB novelty and not a particularly good one as it runs straight into }8...c4 9.Be2 Qa5 10.Qd2 Nd7! { Black's knight is headed to  f6  and then  e4 , which will fork White's queen and the  c3  pawn. }11.O-O Nf6 12.Be5 { fails to solve White's problems as after }12...Ne4 13.Qe1 f6 14.Bg3 Qxc3-+ { the  c3  pawn falls anyway. } )
8. Nd7
9. Ne5{ is the most logical continuation after 8.  Bb5 . White is trying to exchange off as many minor pieces as possible to simplify the position, hoping that Black won't have enough material to attack the weak queenside pawns. However, White won't have such luck. }( 9.O-O?! { makes little sense as after }9...O-O∓ { White's bishop on  b5  isn't doing anything constructive and is even liable to tempo moves like ... Qa5 . } )
9. O-O
10. Nxd7
10. Bxd7
11. a4{ is White's best chance. The idea is that after ... Bxb5 , Black no longer has the option of playing ... Qa5  and White can try to make use of the a-file. Notwithstanding, White is still in dire straits. }( { Alternatively }11.Be2 { can be met with }11...Qa5 { attacking the pawn on  c3 . }12.Qd2 Rfc8∓ { is clearly better for Black. White has nothing to show for the crippled c-pawns. } )
11. Bxb5
12. axb5
12. Qd7{ gives Black a clear advantage with ...  Rfc8  coming next. The pawn on  b5  is very weak and White's doubled c-pawns are also big targets. }( { A couple of sample continuations are }13.Qb1 { is White's best way of covering the pawn but he's still clearly worse after }13...Rfc8 14.O-O h5∓ { Black can continue to strengthen his position with ... Bf6  and ... Kg7  and even consider starting a kingside attack by marching the h-pawn down the board, potentially backed up by ... Rh8 . White's c-pawns are also ever weak. } )( { Worse is   }13.Qe2 c4 { blocks White's queen from defending the pawn. }14.Rb1 a5 15.bxa6 bxa6−+ { gives Black a dangerous passer on the a-file and a decisive advantage. } )( { Similarly   }13.Rb1 a5 14.bxa6 bxa6−+ { is also winning for Black. } )
