1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. f3{ The so-called  Richter Attack . White prepares to expand in the center with  e2 - e4 . In doing so, he deprives the knight on  g1  of its best square. While the engines rate this 'attack' as fairly dubious, White scores quite well in faster time controls. As such, good knowledge of the variations is required to punish White's dubious play. }
3. c5{ is a typical reaction when White is threatening  e4 . }
4. e4{ The only logical follow up to White's previous move. }( 4.e3 { is incongruent. The pawn on  f3  now makes no sense. }4...Nc6 5.Bb5 e6 6.Nge2 Bd6 7.O-O O-O { followed by ... Bd7  and ... a6  gave Black a clear advantage, which he easily converted in 0-1 15 Bucher,R 2055 -Klovans,J 2394 Triesen 2002. White's knight on  e2  is completely misplaced and the bishop on  c1  is restricted. } )
4. cxd4
5. Qxd4
5. Nc6{ Developing with tempo. }
6. Bb5{ is almost invariably played. White wants to keep the queen on  d4 , where it pressures the  d5  pawn and supports  e4 - e5  in some variations. }
6. Bd7{ Breaks the pin and renews the threat of ... Nxd4 , practically forcing  Bxc6 . }
7. Bxc6
7. bxc6{ is the strongest recapture. It is Stockfish's top choice and much rarer than 7...  Bxc6 , thus packing good surprise value. The idea behind ... bxc6  is to play ... e6  and then kick back White's queen with ...  c5 , taking over the center. }( 7...Bxc6 { was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in  GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 Sidelines . The text is, however, stronger. } )
8. e5{ Pushing ahead is White's most popular continuation. }( 8.exd5?! cxd5 9.Nxd5 Qa5+ 10.Nc3 e5∓ { is certainly in Black's favor. White is very underdeveloped and his queen is being kicked around. } )
8. Ng8{ Yes, we have to undevelop the knight but White cannot exploit this. We're ready for ... e6  and potentially ... c5 , taking over the center. }
9. f4{ Reinforces the  e5  pawn and vacates the  f3  square for the knight. }( { White can also develop the knight with }9.Nge2 e6 { threatens ... c5 . If White tries to stop it with }10.Na4 { then }10...Ne7 11.Bd2 Qc7 { followed by ... Nf5 , when Black will get ... c5  in with a clear advantage. } )( {   }10.Be3?? { loses immediately to }10...c5 11.Qd3 d4−+  )
9. e6
10. Nf3
10. Qb6{ is simple and effective, aiming for a clearly better endgame for Black. }( 10...c5 { is an excellent alternative. } )
11. Qxb6
11. axb6{ Black has a clear advantage. ... c5  is up next and the kingside will be developed via ... Be7  and ... Nh6 - f5 . Later on, Black can look to activate to mobilize the center with ... Bc6  and ... d4 . }
