[Result "*"]

1. c4{ The  English  opening was first essayed in tournament play by the 19th-century English master, Howard Staunton, in 1851. The opening didn't catch on immediately among Staunton's contemporaries and only started to garner attention in the twentieth century.     The English, a trademark hypermodern opening, diverges from the classical strategy of occupying the central  e4  and  d4  squares at the outset. Instead, it focuses on controlling and pressuring the center indirectly from the flanks. It is often used as a transpositional device to bypass established responses to 1.d4, such as the Nimzo-Indian and the Grünfeld defenses. }
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of the most principled replies to 1.  c4 . We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Naively developing in the same style as we would against 1.  d4  2.  c4  doesn't quite work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! I should note that }{   }3...e5!? { as recommended by Svidler in his Lifetime Repertoire is playable yet requires Black to be rather precise to equalize. } )
{ In this chapter, we will cover all of White's setups revolving around }2. Nc3( 2.g3 Nc6 3.Bg2 g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 { is another way to reach this chapter's mainline. } )
2. Nc6( { We continue in symmetrical fashion. Unless White plays }3.Nf3 { , we are going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ... g6  next and hold back the  g8  knight. This allows us to anchor down the  d4  square and makes it harder for White to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . } )
3. g3( {  (a)  We then turn our attention to the four knights symmetrical English arising after }3.Nf3 Nf6 { and meet }4.g3 { with }4...d5! { . } )( {  (b)  }3.Nf3 Nf6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 e6 { is covered in the next chapter via the 2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nc3 e6  move order. } )( {  (c)    }4.e3 { is also covered in the next chapter via the 1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.e3  move order. } )
3. g6
4. Bg2
4. Bg7{ and here we focus on White's four big mainlines: }( {  (a)  }5.Nf3 { played in 12000+ games. } )( {  (b)  }5.e3 { seen in 6000+ games. } )( {  (c)  }5.a3 { essayed in 5000+ games. } )( {  (d)  }5.d3 { featured in 4000+ games. } )( { The Botvinnik setup arising after }5.e4 d6 6.Nge2 e6 7.d3 Nge7 { is covered via the 5.  d3  move order here . } )
