1. c4
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of Black's most principled replies to 1.  c4 . We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Simply developing in the same style as we would against 1.  d4  2.  c4  doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nc3
2. Nc6( { We continue in symmetrical fashion. Unless White plays }3.Nf3 { , we are going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ... g6  next and hold back the  g8  knight. This allows us to anchor down the  d4  square and makes it harder for White to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . } )
3. g3
3. g6
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. Nf3{ is by far White's most popular move. White develops the knight to its most active square and clears the way for  O-O . The first player will then typically aim to break in the center with  d4 . }
5. d6{ We're the first to break the symmetry while keeping the knight on  g8  flexible. }( 5...e6 { was Svidler's recommendation while Vigorito went for the reversed Botvinnik setup with }5...e5 { in their respective Lifetime Repertoires. } )( 5...Nf6 6.d4 { is a line I'd rather avoid. While Black is theoretically ok, this line requires learning large amounts of theory. } )
6. O-O
6. Rb8{ A rare move that has recently been essayed by several 2700+ GMs and I expect to rapidly gain in popularity. Black's idea is to quickly expand on the queenside with ... a6  and ... b5 . This is only possible because White committed the  g1  knight to  f3  so early, meaning the  g2  bishop no longer eyes the  c6  knight. }
7. e3{ This logical move is White's main continuation. White prepares to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . As the saying goes, a break in the center is the best reaction to play in the flanks. }( 7.d3 a6 8.a4 Nf6 { gives Black an improved version of the positions in the mainline given the weak  b4  square. } )
7. Nf6{ Black switches gears and foregoes immediate queenside play. }( 7...e5? { is to be avoided as White can play }8.d4! { anyhow. After }8...cxd4 9.exd4 exd4? 10.Re1 { , Black has big problems down the e-file. For example, }10...Nge7 11.Nd5 O-O 12.Bg5+− { and Black is close to lost. } )
8. d4
8. O-O{ Black has secured the kingside and welcomes  d4 - d5 . This will lead to a Benoni structure where White is not in time to stabilize the center with  e4  given how quick ... e6  and/or ... b5  can come in. }
9. d5{ is always a move to check. Black has an excellent version of the Benoni as queenside counterplay with ...  a6  and ... b5  will come very quickly. }( 9.dxc5? { is a positional mistake as after }9...dxc5 { White's bishop on }c1 { is completely restricted by the }e3 { pawn and }10.b3? { is impossible due to }10...Ne4−+ { . } )
9. Na5
10. Qe2( 10.Nd2 { is met by }10...e6 11.e4 exd5 12.exd5 { Now }12...a6↑ { with ideas of ... b5  and ... Bg4  gives Black the initiative. } )
10. a6
11. e4
11. b5
12. cxb5( 12.e5 Ne8Ν { uncovers the  g7  bishop. White can't keep the center together. } )
12. axb5
13. Nxb5
13. Nxe4{ A typical tactical shot in these structures taking advantage of White's overloaded queen. White's center has been liquidated and all that remains is a weak pawn on  d5 .     Black was already for choice and went onto to win in the correspondence game 0-1 (56) Przyborowski,A (1775)-Kadonas,K (1711) ICCF email 2016. }
