1. c4
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of Black's most principled replies to 1.  c4 . We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Simply developing in the same style as we would against 1.  d4  2.  c4  doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nc3
2. Nc6( { We continue in symmetrical fashion. Unless White plays }3.Nf3 { , we are going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ... g6  next and hold back the  g8  knight. This allows us to anchor down the  d4  square and makes it harder for White to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . } )
3. g3
3. g6
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. a3{ White keeps the center pawns flexible and goes for the  b4  break straight away. This is White's third most popular continuation and a logical one at that given how prevalent the  b4  break is in these structures. }
5. b6{ I really like this move, despite it only being Black's sixth most popular option. We reinforce the  c5  pawn ahead of time and prepare to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. Just like White did with 5.a3, we avoid committing the e and d-pawns right away. }
6. b4{ The logical follow-up to 5.  a3 . }( 6.e3 Bb7 7.Nge2 Nf6 8.O-O O-O = { is very comfortable for Black. We can prepare ... d5  with ... e6  and always have the option of exchanging off the light-squared bishops with ... Na5 . } )
6. Bb7( 6...cxb4?! { is dubious as after }7.axb4 Bb7 8.b5 Na5 9.Bxb7 Nxb7 10.Bb2⩲ { White has a big space advantage on the queenside and a clear target on  a7 . } )
7. Rb1
7. cxb4{ is the most direct continuation. }( 7...d6 8.Bb2 e6 9.Nf3 Nge7 { is another possible setup. However, Black won't really be able to do without ... cxb4  so we might as well cut down White's options and take on  b4  right away. } )
8. axb4
8. Qc8{ Black protects the  b7  bishop and is now threatening to win a pawn with ... Nxb4  given White's  g2  bishop is unprotected. From  c8 , the queen also eyes the weak  c4  pawn. }
9. Nd5{ White tries to plug the long diagonal and wants to expand in the center with  e2 - e4  when he'd have a good case for a slight edge given the space advantage. }( {  (a)  }9.c5? { lets Black execute his threat. }9...Nxb4 10.Bxb7 Qxb7 { . White has no time to take on  b4  as the  h1  rook is hanging. }11.Nf3 bxc5-+ { . Black picked up a pawn and easily won in (41) Lomsadze,D   (2332)-Kekelidze,M (2367) Tbilisi 2017. } )( {  (b)  }9.b5?! { blunders a pawn after }9...Ne5 10.Bxb7 Qxb7 11.Nf3 Nxc4∓ { . } )
9. Nd4{ A very proactive reply. ...  e6  is a big threat and the  c4  pawn is hanging. }
10. d3
10. e6
11. Ne3
11. Bxg2
12. Nxg2
12. Qb7{ The queen replaces the bishop on the long diagonal and makes it very awkward for White to complete development. }
13. Kf1
13. Ne7{ When White has to resort to moves like  Kf1  to not lose material, things have definitely gone wrong. Black has the upper hand. }
