1. c4
1. c5{ The  Symmetrical English  is one of Black's most principled replies to 1.  c4 . We immediately take control over the  d4  square and avoid getting move-ordered out of our Grünfeld repertoire. }( 1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 { Simply developing in the same style as we would against 1.  d4  2.  c4  doesn't work. After }3.e4 { , Black isn't getting ... d5  in and }3...Bg7 4.d4 { lands us in a King's Indian. Certainly not what us Grünfeld players want! } )
2. Nc3
2. Nc6( { We continue in symmetrical fashion. Unless White plays }3.Nf3 { , we are going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ... g6  next and hold back the  g8  knight. This allows us to anchor down the  d4  square and makes it harder for White to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . } )
3. g3
3. g6
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. d3{ White mirrors our strategy and keeps the  g1  knight flexible, which could pop out to  f3  or  e2 . }
5. d6{ Black continues the waiting game and retains maximum flexibility. White will now have to commit to a development scheme. }( 5...Nf6 6.e3 e6 7.Nge2 O-O 8.O-O b6 { was Svidler's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. Black has a fine game with ... Bb7  and ... d5  on the agenda. This is fully playable, but I prefer to retain more flexibility with 5... d6  rather than committing to ... e6  so early on. } )
6. Qd2{ White protects the  c3  knight and prepares to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with  b3  and  Bb2  so as to neutralize our bishop on  g7 . Certainly an interesting setup, but is rather slow. }
6. Nf6{ is my preferred setup. The knight pops out to  f6 , from where it prevents an exchange of dark-squared bishops by blocking the long diagonal and supports the ... d5  break. Our plan is very straightforward: . ..O-O, ... e6  and ... d5 . }
7. b3
7. O-O
8. Bb2
8. e6
9. e3( 9.Nf3 d5Ν 10.O-O Qe7 11.e3 Rd8= { Black will complete development with ... b6  followed by ... Bb7  and can enjoy the extra space in the center. } )
9. d5{ The ... d5  break is in and Black may very well push the pawn one step further to  d4 . }
10. Nge2
10. d4{ is far more ambitious than ... dxc4  played in ½-½ (21) Aronian,L (2773)-Areshchenko,A (2678) Karlsruhe 2020. And why not push the pawn further? Black gains space in the center and dislodges the  c3  knight.     We've entered a favorable, reversed Benoni structured where White's bishop on  b2  is misplaced. If White isn't careful, he can easily find himself in a worse position. }
