12. Be3{ Here's an important  rule of thumb  in the Botvinnik: When White plays  Be3  and threatens  d3 - d4 , Black should play ... Nd4 . }( 12.b5 { gaining space on the queenside and provoking }12...Nd4 { is second most common. After }13.Nxd4 { , Black can choose between two possible captures: } )( {  (a)    }13...Bxd4 { is simple way to go. Following, }14.Ne2 Bg7 15.Bb2 Bxb2 16.Rxb2 { White would love to get in  a4 - a5  and  f2 - f4 , but Black can go for }16...Rad8! { preparing the ... d5  break. This move was  not  considered in the Chessable course  The Iron English: Botvinnik Variation . The ... d5  break doesn't work immediately due to  d3 - d4  but after the text }17.d4 { is well met by }17...f5! { , cross-examining White's center, while }{   }17.Re1 d5 18.cxd5 exd5 19.e5 d4= { leads to the exchange of the light-squared bishops and a juicy square on  d5  for our knight.  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable variation in the following alternative  trainable line. } )( {  (b1)    }13...cxd4 { is the more ambitious way to play, keeping the bishops on the board. If }14.Ne2 { ,then }14...e5= { and Black is doing well with ... f5  on the agenda. } )( {  (b2)  Alternatively,   }14.Na2 { with the idea  Nb4  is seldomly seen. Best play by both sides continues }14...d5! 15.cxd5 exd5 { . The interesting pawn sacrifice }16.e5!? { was recommended in the Chessable course  The Iron English  with Palliser and Williams' analysis continuing }16...Bxe5 17.Re1 Bd6! 18.Nb4 Qxb5 19.Nxd5 Qxb1 20.Nf6 Kh8 21.Bxb7 { and here they only analyzed the dubious 21... Rad8 . Instead, Black should simply give back the exchange with }21...Rac8! { when }22.Bxc8 Rxc8= { is objectively equal, albeit easier to play with Black. } )
12. Nd4
13. f4
13. f5{ A well-known reaction. Here's another  rule of thumb  when countering the Botvinnik setup: whenever White goes  f2 - f4 , Black should be ready to meet it with ... f5 . This puts a stop to any ideas White had of gaining space on the kingside with  g4  and  f5 .     Black is very comfortable and will likely follow-up with ... Nec6  and ... Rae8 . In the long run, we can look to engineer the ... e5  break. }
