2. Nc6( { We continue in symmetrical fashion. Unless White plays }3.Nf3 { , we are going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ... g6  next and hold back the  g8  knight. This allows us to anchor down the  d4  square and makes it harder for White to break in the center with  d2 - d4 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6{ Once again, we mirror White's knight development. }( 3...g6 { is another mainline but it would not be compatible with our repertoire against 2.  Nf3 . Specifically, we plan to meet }{   }1.c4 c5 2.Nf3 { with }2...Nf6 { when }3.Nc3 Nc6 { transposes to the text. } )
4. g3{ Going for the standard English Fianchetto is unsurprisingly White's most popular move. }
4. d5{ If White's delaying  d4 , we may as well break in the center first! This early break is especially timely given White's light-squared bishop is still on  f1  and the knight on  f3  is blocking the long diagonal. }
5. d4{ White effectively goes for a reversed Grunfeld and ups the pressure in the center. }
5. cxd4
6. Nxd4
6. dxc4
7. Nxc6
7. Qxd1+
8. Nxd1
8. bxc6{ We've reached an interesting endgame where Black's structure has been compromised. The doubled c-pawns are particularly vulnerable and White will soon pick up the  c4  pawn. To compensate, Black has the bishop pair and can put pressure on White's queenside with ... Rb8 . The  f6  knight can establish itself on  d5  and plug the long diagonal. }
9. Bg2{ White logically brings the bishop to the long diagonal and immediately puts pressure on the  c6  pawn. }( 9.Ne3 { is an inaccurate move order as it gives Black enough time to bring the bishop to  d5 . }9...Be6 10.Bg2 Bd5! { with an improved version of the mainline as seen in the game 0-1 (46) Vachier Lagrave,M (2774) -So,W   (2767) chess. com INT 2019. } )
9. Nd5{ The knight comes to the center and plugs the long diagonal. White doesn't have a good way to kick it as  e2 - e4  would block in the  g2  bishop. }
10. Ne3
10. e6
11. Nxc4
11. Ba6{ The bishop comes out with tempo and puts pressure on the  c4  knight and  e2  pawn. }
12. b3
12. Bb4+
13. Bd2
13. Ke7{ All of Back's pieces are in the game while White has issues completing development. The  c6  weakness is largely immaterial as White can't attack it with enough pieces. }( { A sample line goes }14.Rc1 Rhc8 15.Bxb4+ Nxb4 16.a3 Bxc4! 17.Rxc4 Nd5 18.O-O Rab8 19.b4 Rb5= { Black is about to play ... a5  and vacuum the queenside pawns off the board. He easily drew in the correspondence game ½-½ (36) Stadelmann, H (2061)-Garau,B (2296) ICCF email 2021. } )
