1. c4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6( { Black has a variety of options at his disposal to meet  2.Nf3 . We go for  2...Nf6  such that   }1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 { can be met with }2...c5 { , transposing to the text. } )
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nc6
5. g3{ White prioritizes the development of the  g2  bishop instead of  Nc3 . As a result, White ends up lacking control over the  d5  square in many lines. }
5. e5{ Black sends the  d4  knight packing. Normally, such a move would be a positional mistake due to the weakening of the  d5  square. However, White is in no position to exploit this with only one minor piece in the game. }
6. Nb5{ White would love to drop the knight in on  d6 . Naturally, we're not going to allow it! }( { Apart from the threat of  Nd6 , White also prevents the immediate }6...d5? { break. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qxd5! Qxd5 9.Nc7++- { and White wins a piece. } )
6. Bb4+{ Black wants to play ... d6  to take control over this square. Logically, the bishop is first developed outside the pawn chain. }
7. Bd2{ is one way to block the check. The drawback of this move is that White's queen no longer eyes the  d6  square, enabling back to kick back the  b5  knight immediately. }
7. a6
8. Bxb4
8. axb5( 8...Nxb4?? 9.Nd6++- { is disastrous. } )
9. Bd6{ White's bishop has made it to  d6 , where it is very active and stops ...  O-O . However, the  a5 - d8  diagonal is now vulnerable which Black can readily exploit with moves like ... Qa5 + and ... Ne4 . }
9. Qa5+{ an important check disturbing the White camp. }( 9...Ne4 10.Bg2 Qa5+? { is the wrong way to do things as White now has the strong }11.b4! { the point being that }11...Nxb4 { is met by }12.Bxe4 { The extra  Bg2  move Black allowed by starting with ... Ne4  comes back to bite him. The tactics work out for White. }12...Nc2+ 13.Kf1 Nxa1 { was all seen in the game 1-0 (19) Bacrot,E (2705)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2705) Bastia 2012. Now, White could have got a decisive advantage with the simple }14.Na3Ν bxc4 15.Qxa1+- { White's two minor pieces, particularly the strong bishop on  d6 , are far stronger than Black's rook not to mention Black's atrocious lack of development. White is winning. } )
10. Nd2( {  (a)  }10.Qd2?! { is strongly met by }10...Ne4! { when Black exchanges queens on his term. }11.Qxa5 { is forced and after }11...Nxa5⩱ { White has no good way to counter the threats of ... Nb3xa1 , exploiting the pin along the a-file, and ... Nxd6 .  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the upcoming  alternative trainable line. } )( {  (b)  }10.Nc3 { is an inferior way to block the check compared to  Nd2  as White's knight is exposed to }10...b4! 11.Nb5 b3+ 12.Qd2 Qxd2+ 13.Kxd2 Ne4+↑ { With ... Rxa2  coming and ... Nxd6  on tap, Black had the initiative and went on to win in 0-1 (36) Ju,W (2560)-Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Chess.com INT 2021.  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. } )
10. Ne4{ The natural follow-up to ... Qa5 . Black ups the pressure on the  d2  knight while hitting the bishop on  d6 . }
11. c5{ is the only way for White to maintain equality. Yes, you read that right - it's already White that needs to be precise to equalize. }( 11.Bc7 { is too clever for White's own good. The strong intermediate move }11...Nxf2! 12.Bxa5 Nxd1∓ { nets Black at least a pawn. ... Nxb2  and ... Ne3 , with the threat of ... Nc2 +, are on tap as well as ... Rxa5 . } )
11. Nxd6
12. cxd6
12. Qb4{ With the  d6  bishop gone, Black will have no trouble bringing his pieces out. The  d6  pawn is really only a target in this position, and so are  b2  and  a2 .     Black has scored 4.5/5 with 2600+ GM Fressinet going down thrice with the White pieces. Enough said! }
