11. Nb6{ An important, prophylactic move that avoids unfavorable piece trades on  d5 . White's knights on  c3  and  b1  duplicate each other, so Black does best in avoiding trades. }( 11...O-O ?! { is natural, yet inaccurate due to }12.Nxd5 Bxd5 13.Bg5! { This tactical shot uncovers a discovered attack on the  d5  bishop. }13...Qxg5 14.Qxd5⩲ { White has a small but nagging edge due to the uncontested bishop on the long diagonal. Black managed to hold in ½-½ (53) Artemiev,V (2709) -Salgado Lopez,I (2629) Skopje 2018 and ½-½ (50) Rapport,R (2763)-Svidler,P  (2714) Paris 2021, but there's no need to allow this. } )
12. Na4{ is a tactical solution to bring the  b1  knight into the game. }
12. Bxd2
13. Bxc6+
13. bxc6
14. Nxb6
14. Qxb6
15. Qxd2
15. O-O{ The trades have finally subsided and Black has completed development. Positionally, Black's weak queenside pawn formation is compensated by weak light squares around the White king. Concrete ideas include bringing the rooks out to  d8  and  b8  as well pushing the c-pawn all the way to  c4 , fixing the weakness on  b2 . }( { Barbosa won an instructive game with the Black pieces from this position against a 2600+ GM: }16.Nc3 Rfd8 17.Qc2 c5 18.Rfd1 Rd4 19.e3 Rb4 20.Rd2 Rb8 21.Rad1 g6 22.Rd6?! Qb7 23.Nd5 Rxb2 24.Qxc5 Rb5 25.Qc4 Rb1 26.Rxb1 Qxb1+ 27.Kg2 Rb4 28.Nf6+?? Kg7 29.Ne8+ Kf8 30.Qc5 Bh3+! 31.Kf3 Qh1+ 32.Ke2 Qf1+ 33.Kd2 Rb2+ { 0-1 (33) Shimanov,A (2625)-Barbosa,E (2446) Katowice 2014 } )
