5. Nc3
5. e6
6. g3{ Fianchettoing the light-squared bishop is White's most popular and English-like continuation. The bishop is most active on the long diagonal where it's not blocked in by the  c4  pawn. }
6. Qb6{ White's play is rather slow and Black wastes no time activating the queen. The  d4  knight now has to find a new home. What is more, Black now has ideas of ...  Ne5  followed by ... Qc6  in many lines to target the  c4  pawn, which will be somewhat vulnerable once the  f1  bishop comes out to  g2 . }
7. Ndb5( { White chooses to go forward. }7.Nb3 { is the other mainline at this junction. } )
7. Ne5{ Black springs the knight into the center to target the  c4  pawn while also threatening ... Qc6 . }
8. Bf4
8. Nfg4{ A dual-purpose move: Black reinforces the  e5  knight and targets the  f2  pawn. }
9. e3{ The saner option, blocking the queen on  b6 . White is now threatening to win material with  h2 - h3 . }
9. a6{ Turns out White's knight on  b5  is also vulnerable. }( 9...Qc6?! { is one to avoid as after }10.h3! Qxh1? 11.hxg4± { Black has no good way to meet both  Nc7 + and  Bxe5 . } )
