[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3{  1.Nf3 , referred to by some as the Knight's or Zukertort's opening, captures the essence of hypermodern chess strategy: control of the center from the wings, rather than immediate occupation. Named after Johannes Zukertort, a prominent player from the late 19th century, this opening is notable for its versatile and flexible nature.     It is frequently used as an 'information-seeking' move. If Black attempts to transpose into a variation that White deems unfavorable, White can reject this and pursue an independent line. Conversely, if Black steers towards a variation White is comfortable with, White can opt to follow along.      Many GMs use this opening move to steer clear of mainline 1.d4 variations like the Grünfeld where White has struggled to fight for an advantage.  Worry not, I’m proposing a practical response to 1.  Nf3  that avoids move order tricks and comfortably equalizes everywhere. }
1. Nf6
2. g3( {  (a)  }2.c4 c5 { conveniently transposes to the 1.c4  c5  2.Nf3  chapter. } )( {  (b)  }2.b3 { has gained some traction, mainly as a way to avoid theory, but poses little to no theoretical problems. }2...g6 3.Bb2 Bg7 { is my recommendation. We will examine the following options: } )( {  (b1)  }4.g3 { The  double-fianchetto  setup has been seen in 4000+ games. } )( {  (b2)  }4.e3 { played in well over 3000 games. } )( {  (b3)  }4.c4 { transposing back into English structures, was essayed in 1500+ games. } )( {  (c)  Finally, we look at }2.e3 { played in 3800+ games. } )
2. g6
3. Bg2( 3.b4 { has attracted some attention at the top-level, primarily in faster time controls. }( 3.b3 Bg7 4.Bb2 b6 { is covered via the 2.  b3  move order here . } ) )
3. Bg7
4. O-O( 4.c4 c5 { transposes into a symmetrical version of the English opening that we're yet to examine. I'm recommending a setup revolving around the early ... d5  break in this chapter. } )
4. O-O
( 5.c4 c5 { is yet another transposition into the Symmetrical English that we'll cover here. } )5. d3{ The  King's Indian Attack  is very popular with thousands upon thousands of games played. }
5. d5{ Despite the name of the opening, White will have a total of zero chances to attack our king on  g8  courtesy of the fianchetto setup we're employing. }
