1. Nf3{  1.Nf3 , referred to by some as the Knight's or Zukertort's opening, captures the essence of hypermodern chess strategy: control of the center from the wings, rather than immediate occupation. Named after Johannes Zukertort, a prominent player from the late 19th century, this opening is notable for its versatile and flexible nature.     It is frequently used as an 'information-seeking' move. If Black attempts to transpose into a variation that White deems unfavorable, White can reject this and pursue an independent line. Conversely, if Black steers towards a variation White is comfortable with, White can opt to follow along.      Many GMs use this opening move to steer clear of mainline 1.d4 variations like the Grünfeld where White has struggled to fight for an advantage.  Worry not, I’m proposing a practical response to 1.  Nf3  that avoids move order tricks and comfortably equalizes everywhere. }
1. Nf6
2. g3{ White starts by developing the bishop to  g2  and will only then decide whether to go for English likes with  c4 , head back into  d4  territory or opt for a King's Indian attack setup. }( 2.c4 c5 { is covered in the 1.c4  c5  2.Nf3 Nf6  chapter. } )
2. g6{ Black follows suit with ... Bg7  coming next. }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. c4
4. c5{ A rule of thumb in our repertoire is that  c2 - c4  should be met with ... c5 . }
5. Nc3
5. O-O{ Kingside development is complete and Black is now ready to break in the center with ... d5 . }
6. d4( 6.O-O d5 { is covered via the 4.O-O 5.c4  move order. } )
6. cxd4( 6...d5 { was Svidler's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. Black has no problems equalizing here, but has to remember a variety of forced lines. I prefer the text, which keeps more play in the position and is less taxing on our memory. } )
7. Nxd4( 7.Qxd4 { allows Black to break in the center with }7...d5! 8.Nxd5 Nxd5 9.Qxd5 a5! { Black sets the a-pawn in motion, aiming to get it all the way down to  a3  and put pressure on the  b2  pawn. He can look to the middlegame with confidence. } ){  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. }
7. Qc7{ Black immediately exposes the one drawback in White's setup, namely the vulnerable  c4  pawn. }
8. b3
8. d5{ highlights another point behind ... Qc7 . After  b3 , the  c4  pawn is pinned and can be immediately undermined! Black now wants to take on  c4  and split White's queenside pawns. }
9. O-O
9. dxc4
10. Ncb5{ White gets a free tempo on our queen but this activity is on temporary. Conversely, the first player will be left with a permanent weakness on  c4 . }
10. Qd8
11. bxc4
11. a6{ sends the knight packing. }
12. Nc3
12. Ng4{ Black uncovers the  g7  bishop and initiates a thematic maneuver. The knight is heading to  e5  to attack the weak  c4  pawn. }
13. e3
13. Ne5{ Black followed up with ... Nbc6  and had an excellent position out of the opening in 1-0 (38) Svidler,P  (2749) -Grischuk,A (2763) Astana 2012. White did win this high profile game, but it had nothing to do with the current position. In fact, Black was better for a large portion of it, only blundering much later on. }
