6. Nbd2{ White goes for the standard King's Indian Attack setup, angling for the  e2 - e4  break. Despite the name of the opening, White will have exactly zero attacking chances as the  g7  fianchetto setup is virtually unbreakable. }( {  (a)  }6.c3 { has little independent value. After }6...c5 7.Nbd2 Nc6 8.e4 { , we reach the mainline of this chapter. } )( {  (b)  }6.c4 { is most easily met by }6...dxc4 7.dxc4 Qxd1 8.Rxd1 c6= { The pawn on  c6  restricts the light-squared bishop while its counterpart on  c4  is a target. Black is completely fine with ... Be6  and ... Na6  likely coming next.  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. } )( {  (c)  }6.Nc3 { runs straight into }6...d4 7.Na4 e5! { taking over the center. This move highlights how misplaced the  a4  knight is given that }8.Nxe5?? { loses a piece to }8...Qe8! { forking both knights. Instead, }{   }8.c4 Re8⩱ { Black had an excellent version of the reversed Benoni and came out on top in 0-1 (38) Lomsadze,D (2336)-Fier,A (2579) Tbilisi 2014.  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. } )( {   }7.Nb5 { is also possible. }7...c5 8.c4 Nc6 { and I'd certainly take Black with the extra space. } )
6. c5{ Black gains more space in the center and will bring the knight out to  c6  next, achieving a very harmonious setup. White is playing a King's Indian with an extra tempo, which is nowhere near enough to fight for an advantage. }
7. e4( 7.c3 Nc6 8.e4 dxe4 { or 8... e5  leads to very similar play as the mainline. } )
7. Nc6
8. exd5{ is premature. }
8. Nxd5
