1. Nf3
1. Nf6
2. g3{ White starts by developing the bishop to  g2  and will only then decide whether to go for English likes with  c4 , head back into  d4  territory or opt for a King's Indian attack setup. }( 2.c4 c5 { is covered in the 1.c4  c5  2.Nf3 Nf6  chapter. } )
2. g6{ Black follows suit with ... Bg7  coming next. }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. O-O
4. O-O
5. d3
5. d5
6. Nbd2{ White goes for the standard King's Indian Attack setup, angling for the  e2 - e4  break. Despite the name of the opening, White will have exactly zero attacking chances as the  g7  fianchetto setup is virtually unbreakable. }( 6.c3 { has little independent value. After }6...c5 7.Nbd2 Nc6 8.e4 { , we reach the mainline of this chapter. } )
6. c5{ Black gains more space in the center and will bring the knight out to  c6  next, achieving a very harmonious setup. White is playing a King's Indian with an extra tempo, which is nowhere near enough to fight for an advantage. }
7. e4( 7.c3 Nc6 8.e4 dxe4 { or 8... e5  leads to very similar play as the mainline. } )
7. Nc6
8. Re1
8. dxe4{ Black has a pleasant choice at this junction. Taking on  e4  is simplest and leads to a comfortable position where Black will have no trouble bringing out his remaining forces. }( 8...e5 { is a good alternative to keep more tension in the position. }9.exd5 Nxd5 10.Nc4 f6= { has been seen in many GM encounters. Black is doing very well in this structure, planning to complete development with ...  Be6  and ... Qd7 . He'll then take a look around and start to prepare the ... f5  break with moves like ... Kg8  and ... Rae8 . } )
9. Nxe4{ is dubious. Exchanging a pair of knights not only helps open up the  g7  bishop, but also has concrete problems. }
9. Nxe4
10. Rxe4{ is surprisingly more popular than 10.  dxe4  and already a serious mistake. }( 10.dxe4 Qxd1 11.Rxd1 Bg4 { The pin creates threats of ... Ne5/ d4  and is very awkward for White to meet.  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. } )
10. Bf5{ sends the rook packing with tempo. }
11. Re1
11. Qc7{ Every single one of Black's pieces is superior to White's counterpart. And Black is about to extend that lead by capturing more space with ... Rad8  and ... e5 . White is considerably worse. }
