1. Nf3
1. Nf6
2. b3{ A setup that's gained some traction, mainly as a way to avoid theory. Unsurprisingly, Black has several good setups at his disposal and even good chances to take over the game should White be inaccurate. }
2. g6{ We continue in Grünfeld fashion and are going to play ... Bg7  followed by ... O-O  pretty much irrespective of White's moves. }
3. Bb2
3. Bg7
4. e3
4. O-O( { This position can also arise via the   }1.Nf3 Nf6 2.e3 g6 3.b3 Bg7 4.Bb2 O-O { move order. } )
5. d4{ I never really understood the point of this setup for White. It only really makes sense to play this way when Black has already committed to ... d5 . In that case,  d2 - d4  cements White's control over the key  e5  square. As it stands, with Black's pawn still on  d7 ,  d2 - d4  is rather premature. }
5. b6{ Black retains maximum flexibility with the e and d-pawns by holding them back and instead preparing to challenge the  d4  pawn with ... c5 . The  c8  bishop will pop out to the long diagonal where it'll be very active and control the key  e4  and  d5  squares.     This double fianchetto setup equalizes very easily and was not considered by IM Yuriy Krykun in the Chessable course  1.  Nf3 : The Reversed Queen's Indian . }
6. Be2
6. c5
7. O-O
7. cxd4{ Simple and effective. Black resolves the tension in the center of the board and prepares to bring the bishop out to  b7 . }
8. Nxd4( 8.exd4 { cannot be recommended as after }8...e6 9.c4 d5= { White's  b2  bishop is permanently shut it by its own pawn on  d4 . Black has an excellent game with ...  Bb7 , ... Nc6  and ... Rc8  coming next. } ){  Note:  you can opt to train this clickable in the following  alternative trainable line. }
8. Bb7
9. c4
9. d5{ Black takes a stake in the center and has ideas of ...  bxc4  followed by a quick ... e5  in many lines. }
10. Nc3( {  (a)  }10.Bf3 e5 11.Nb5 e4 { forces White's bishop back. } )( {  (b)  }10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Nc3 Nxc3 12.Bxc3 e5! 13.Nf3 Qe7 { is a position where only Black can even be better. } )
10. dxc4
11. Bxc4
11. a6{ Black takes control over the ... b5  square in preparation for ... e5 . We definitely don't want White to be able to meet the latter with  Nb5 . }
12. Be2
12. e5
13. Nf3
13. Qe7{ With ... Rd8  on the way and the extra space afforded by the  e5  pawn, Black was already slightly for choice in 1-0 (35) Niemann,H (2465)-Xiong,J (2709) chess24.com INT 2020. Xiong did lose this blitz game, but certainly not as a result of the opening. }
